\n|event    = [[House show]]\n|notes    = \n|ref      = <ref name=\"Phantom1\"/><ref name=\"Phantom2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/world_title.htm|title=WWWF/WWF/WWE Heavyweight Title History|website=The History of WWE.com|accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|sort number = 8.5\n|type     = vacated\n|date     = {{dts|December 6, 1979}}\n|location = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|event    = [[House show]]\n|days2    = yes\n|notes    = [[Antonio Inoki|Inoki]] immediately vacated the title after a title defense rematch with [[Bob Backlund]] ended in a [[Professional wrestling#No contest|no contest]] due to the interference of [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]'s [[Tiger Jeet Singh]].\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Phantom1\"/><ref name=\"Phantom2\"/>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|sort number = 8.5\n|type     = unrecognized\n|champion = {{sortname|Bob|Backlund}}\n|reign    = 2\n|date     = {{dts|December 17, 1979}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|December 17, 1979|October 19, 1981}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[New York City|New York City, NY]]\n|event    = ''[[WWF on MSG Network]]''\n|notes    = Defeated [[Bobby Duncum Sr.|Bobby Duncum]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Last Man Standing match|Texas death match]] to fill the vacancy. WWE recognizes Backlund's first and second reigns as being uninterrupted and considers this a continuation of the first. \n|ref      = <ref name=\"Phantom1\"/><ref name=\"Phantom2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=27824|title=WWF on MSG Network|work=Cagematch|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{PWtitlereign\n|sort number = 8.5\n|type     = unrecognized\n|champion = {{sortname|Greg|Valentine}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|October 19, 1981}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|October 19, 1981|November 23, 1981}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[New York City|New York City, NY]]\n|event    = ''[[WWF on MSG Network]]''\n|notes    = Valentine was awarded the title by a stunned [[Referee (professional wrestling)|referee]] despite Backlund winning the match. WWE has acknowledged the incident, albeit it still recognizes Backlund's first reign as being uninterrupted, lasting from February 20, 1978 to December 26, 1983 for a total of 2,135 days.\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Phantom1\"/><ref name=\"Phantom2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=3943|title=WWF on MSG Network|work=Cagematch|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|sort number = 8.5\n|type     = unrecognized\n|champion = {{sortname|Bob|Backlund}}\n|reign    = 3\n|date     = {{dts|November 23, 1981}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|November 23, 1981|December 26, 1983}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[New York City|New York City, NY]]\n|event    = ''[[WWF on MSG Network]]''\n|notes    = Defeated [[Greg Valentine]] in a rematch to end the controversy. Both the vacancy and Backlund win over Valentine are not recognized by WWE, albeit it has been acknowledged.\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Phantom1\"/><ref name=\"Phantom2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=3944|title=WWF on MSG Network|work=Cagematch|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 9\n|champion = {{sortname|The Iron|Sheik}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|December 26, 1983}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|December 26, 1983|January 23, 1984}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[New York City|New York City, NY]]\n|event    = ''[[WWF on MSG Network]]''\n|notes    = The Iron Sheik won by submission when [[Bob Backlund]]'s manager [[Arnold Skaaland]] threw in the towel when Backlund was put into Sheik's [[Professional wrestling holds#Camel clutch|camel clutch]] to prevent any major injury. The title was renamed the WWF World Heavyweight Championship when the WWF ended its affiliation with the NWA.\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Sheik1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454118 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051231061205/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454118 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2005-12-31 |title=The Iron Sheik's first reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=2007-03-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=4656|title=WWF on MSG Network|work=Cagematch|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 10\n|champion = {{sortname|Hulk|Hogan}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|January 23, 1984}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|January 23, 1984|February 5, 1988}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[New York City|New York City, NY]]\n|event    = ''[[WWF on MSG Network]]''\n|notes    = \n|ref = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=4657|title=WWF on MSG Network|work=Cagematch|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 11\n|champion = {{sortname|Andr\u00e9 the|Giant}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|February 5, 1988}}\n|days     = <1\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[Indianapolis|Indianapolis, IN]]\n|event    = ''[[The Main Event I]]''\n|notes    = Defeated [[Hulk Hogan]] when [[Referee (professional wrestling)|referee]] [[Earl Hebner]], who was bribed by [[Ted DiBiase]], scored the [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Fall|three-count]] despite Hogan [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Kick-out|raising his shoulder at the one-count]].\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Andre1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454122 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050624001310/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454122 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2005-06-24 |title=Andre the Giant's first reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=2007-03-20 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{PWtitlereign\n|sort number = 11.5\n|type     = unrecognized\n|champion = {{sortname|Ted|DiBiase}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|February 5, 1988}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|February 5, 1988|February 13, 1988}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[Indianapolis|Indianapolis, IN]]\n|event   