|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|April 11, 1963}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|April 11, 1963|May 17, 1963}}\n|days2    = {{age in days nts|April 25, 1963|May 17, 1963}}\n|location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|event    = [[House show]]\n|notes    = Won a [[WWE Championship#Origin|fictional tournament]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] after the WWWF left the [[National Wrestling Alliance]] (NWA), of which Rogers had been the [[List of NWA World Heavyweight Champions|7th]] [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship|NWA World Heavyweight Champion]] since defeating [[Pat O'Connor (wrestler)|Pat O'Connor]] on June 30, 1961. After Rogers' [[Professional wrestling match types#Singles match|one fall]] loss to [[Lou Thesz]] for the title on January 24, 1963, [[Capitol Wrestling Corporation|Northeast promoters]] (led by [[Vince McMahon Sr.]] and [[Toots Mondt]]) did not recognize this title change and withdrew their membership from the NWA to form the World Wide Wrestling Federation (WWWF). The WWWF billed Rogers as their world champion since January 25, 1963, but it did not recognize him as the first ever WWWF World Heavyweight Champion until April 11, 1963, when he received the [[Championship belt#Professional wrestling|title belt]]. However, WWE lists Rogers' reign and the establishment of the title beginning on April 25, 1963.\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Rogers1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/30445411 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050828211610/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/30445411 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2005-08-28 |title=Buddy Rogers's first reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=2007-03-17 }}</ref><ref name=\"Phantom1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/classics/phantom-title-changes|title=The secret history of phantom title changes|last=Melok|first=Bobby Melok|publisher=[[WWE]]|date=December 12, 2012|accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/buddyrogers|title=Buddy Rogers|publisher=WWE|quote=So in 1961, when he dethroned Pat O'Connor for the NWA World Championship in Chicago's Comiskey Park [...]|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref><br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/63.htm|title=1963|work=TheHistoryofWWE.com|quote=- 1/25/63: The World Wide Wrestling Federation (WWWF) was formed when promoters in the Northeast refused to acknowledge Rogers' one-fall loss of the NWA championship. The real reason was that Vince McMahon Sr. wanted to keep Rogers on as his territory's champion since so much money was being made from his title run. Rogers continued to wrestle as the \"world champion\" in the Northeast region and was recognized as the \"WWWF World Champion\" starting in April.|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/63.htm|title=1963|work=TheHistoryofWWE.com|quote=World Champion Buddy Rogers defeated Bobo Brazil|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/63.htm|title=1963|work=TheHistoryofWWE.com|quote=WWWF World Champion Buddy Rogers fought Bruno Sammartino to a no contest; it was prior to this bout that Rogers received the WWWF World Title though he had been billed as 'world champion' since January|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref><br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/wwe-world-championship|title=WWE World Championship|publisher=WWE|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 2\n|champion = {{sortname|Bruno|Sammartino}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|May 17, 1963}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|May 17, 1963|January 18, 1971}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[New York City|New York, NY]]\n|event    = [[House show]]\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Sammartino1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/408772|title=Bruno Sammartino's first reign|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-03-17|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070318015911/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/408772|archivedate=2007-03-18}}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 3\n|champion = {{sortname|Ivan|Koloff}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|January 18, 1971}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|January 18, 1971|February 8, 1971}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[New York City|New York, NY]]\n|event    = [[House show]]\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Koloff1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/30445416 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050715020508/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/30445416 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2005-07-15 |title=Ivan Koloff's first reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=2011-07-15 }}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 4\n|champion = {{sortname|Pedro|Morales}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|February 8, 1971}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|February 8, 1971|December 1, 1973}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[New York City|New York, NY]]\n|event    = [[House show]]\n|notes    = The title was renamed the WWWF Heavyweight Championship when the WWWF rejoined the NWA in 1971. \n|ref      = <ref name=\"Morales1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/30445418 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051210234107/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/30445418 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2005-12-10 |title=Pedro Morales's first reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=2007-03-17 }}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 5\n|champion = {{sortname|Stan|Stasiak}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|December 1, 1973}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|December 1, 1973|December 10, 1973}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, PA]]\n|event    = [[House show]]\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Stasiak1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454110 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051210235044/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454110 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2005-12-10 |title=Stan Stasiak's first reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=2007-03-17 }}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 6\n|champion = {{sortname|Bruno|Sammartino}}\n|reign    = 2\n|date     = {{dts|December 10, 1973}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|December 10, 1973|April 30, 1977}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[New York City|New York, NY]]\n|event    = [[House show]]\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Sammartino2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454112 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050724000316/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454112 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2005-07-24 |title=Bruno Sammartino's second reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=2007-03-17 }}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 7\n|champion = {{sortname|Superstar Billy|Graham}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|April 30, 1977}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|April 30, 1977|February 20, 1978}}\n|days2    = yes\n|location = [[Baltimore|Baltimore, MD]]\n|event    = [[House show]]\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Graham1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454114 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050724001044/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwechampionship/304454114 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2005-07-24 |title=Billy Graham's first reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=2007-03-17 }}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 8\n|champion = {{sortname|Bob|Backlund}}\n|reign    = 1\n|date     = {{dts|February 20, 1978}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|February 20, 1978|November 30, 1979}}\n|days2    = {{age in days nts|February 20, 1978|December 26, 1983}}\n|location = [[New York City|New York, NY]]\n|event    = ''[[WWF on MSG Network]]''\n|notes    = The title was renamed the WWF Heavyweight Championship when the WWWF became the World Wrestling Federation (WWF) in March 1979 for marketing purposes.\n|ref      = <ref name=\"Backlund1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ww