knapp]]||{{flagu|England}}||March 2002&nbsp;\u2013 November 2004||116||54||26||36||{{#expr:54/116 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Velimir Zajec]]||{{flagu|Croatia}}||November 2004&nbsp;\u2013 April 2005||21||5||4||12||{{#expr:5/21 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Alain Perrin]]||{{flagu|France}}||April 2005&nbsp;\u2013 November 2005||21||4||6||11||{{#expr:4/21 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Harry Redknapp]]||{{flagu|England}}||December 2005&nbsp;\u2013 October 2008||128||54||29||45||{{#expr: 54/128 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Tony Adams]]||{{flagu|England}}||October 2008&nbsp;\u2013 February 2009||22||4||7||11||{{#expr:4/22 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Paul Hart]]||{{flagu|England}}||February 2009&nbsp;\u2013 November 2009||30||9||6||15||{{#expr:9/30 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Avram Grant]]||{{flagu|Israel}}||November 2009&nbsp;\u2013 May 2010||33||10||7||16||{{#expr:10/33 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Steve Cotterill]]||{{flagu|England}}||June 2010&nbsp;\u2013 October 2011||61||18||17||26||{{#expr:18/61 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Michael Appleton]]||{{flagu|England}}||November 2011&nbsp;\u2013 November 2012||51||13||11||27||{{#expr:13/51 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Guy Whittingham]] ||{{flagu|England}}||November 2012&nbsp;\u2013 November 2013 ||51||11||15||25||{{#expr:11/51 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Richie Barker (footballer, born 1975)|Richie Barker]] ||{{flagu|England}}||December 2013&nbsp;\u2013 March 2014||20||4||8||8||{{#expr:4/20 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Andy Awford]] ||{{flagu|England}}||March 2014&nbsp;\u2013 April 2015 ||55||20||17||18||{{#expr:20/55 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Paul Cook (footballer)|Paul Cook]] ||{{flagu|England}}||May 2015&nbsp;\u2013 May 2017||107||52||27||28||{{#expr:52/107 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Kenny Jackett]]||{{flagu|Wales}}||June 2017&nbsp;\u2013 Present||165||87||33||45||{{#expr:87/165 * 100 round 2}}\n|}\n\n===Caretaker managers===\n:''Figures correct as of August 2018''\n:''Includes all competitive matches.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:10em\"|Name!!Nat!!Managerial Tenure!!P!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Ron Tindall]]||{{flagu|England}}||September 1974||2||0||0||2||{{#expr:0/2 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Tony Barton (footballer)|Tony Barton]]||{{flagu|England}}||March 1991&nbsp;\u2013 May 1991||12||5||2||5||{{#expr:5/12 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Keith Waldon]]||{{flagu|England}}||January 1998&nbsp;\u2013 January 1998||3||0||0||3||{{#expr:0/3 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Bob McNab]]||{{flagu|England}}||December 1999&nbsp;\u2013 January 2000||5||0||2||3||{{#expr:0/5 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Joe Jordan]]||{{flag|Scotland}}||November 2005&nbsp;\u2013 December 2005||2||0||0||2||{{#expr:0/2 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Stuart Gray (footballer, born 1960)|Stuart Gray]]||{{flagu|England}}||October 2011&nbsp;\u2013 November 2011||6||3||1||2||{{#expr:1/2 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Andy Awford]]||{{flagu|England}}||November 2013&nbsp;\u2013 December 2013 ||3||0||2||1||{{#expr:0/3 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Gary Waddock]]||{{flagu|England}}||April 2015&nbsp;\u2013 2 May 2015||4||1||1||2||{{#expr:1/4 * 100 round 2}}\n|}\n\n==Ownership==\nPortsmouth Football Club has operated under five different parent company names in its history:\n* '''Portsmouth Football and Athletic Company Limited''' (5 April 1898 \u2013 27 July 1912)\n* '''Portsmouth Football Club Limited''' (27 July 1912 \u2013 May 1999)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://companycheck.co.uk/company/00123460/PORTSMOUTH-FOOTBALL-CLUB-LIMITED/companies-house-data |title=Portsmouth Football Club Limited |work=Company Check |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Portsmouth City Football Club Limited''' (12 May 1999 \u2013 25 May 2010)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://companycheck.co.uk/company/03747237/PORTSMOUTH-CITY-FOOTBALL-CLUB-LIMITED/companies-house-data |title=Portsmouth City Football Club Limited |work=Company Check |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> (initially as 'Overflint Limited' from 7 April 1999 \u2013 12 May 1999)\n* '''Portsmouth Football Club (2010) Limited''' (25 May 2010 \u2013 10 April 2013)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://companycheck.co.uk/company/07264768/PORTSMOUTH-FOOTBALL-CLUB-2010-LIMITED/companies-house-data |title=Portsmouth Football Club (2010) Limited |work=Company Check |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> (initially as 'PFC Realisations Limited' from 25 May 2010 \u2013 23 November 2010)\n* '''Portsmouth Community Football Club Limited''' (10 April 2013 \u2013 Present)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://companycheck.co.uk/company/07940335/PORTSMOUTH-COMMUNITY-FOOTBALL-CLUB-LIMITED/companies-house-data |title=Portsmouth Community Football Club Limited |work=Company Check |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> (initially as 'Portsmouth Supporters Trust (Operations) Limited' from 7 February 2012 \u2013 14 September 2012)\n\nThe current owner of Portsmouth Community Football Club Limited is [[The Tornante Company]], which purchased the club from the Portsmouth Supporters Trust (PST) on 3 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2017/august/tornante-company-complete-purchase-of-portsmouth-fc/ |title=Tornante Company Complete Purchase Of Portsmouth FC |work=Portsmouth F.C. |date=3 August 2017 |accessdate=18 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Club crest==\n[[File:City Flag of Portsmouth.svg|thumb|left|Official flag of the [[Portsmouth|City of Portsmouth]]]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC 80's logo.png|thumb|upright=0.5|right|1980\u20131989.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth_City_Coat_of_Arms.jpg|thumb|upright=0.5|right|1993-1997.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC 90's logo.png|thumb|upright=0.5|right|1997\u20132008.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC crest.svg|thumb|upright=0.5|right|2015\u20132018.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC logo.jpg|thumb|upright=0.5|right|2018-Present. Shirt crest.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC logo.svg|thumb|upright=0.5|right|2018-Present. Club & Merchandising crest.]]\n\nAlthough Portsmouth F.C. were formed in 1898, the club did not have a club crest until one was introduced for the 1913\u201314 season. This would be the second season since Portsmouth's 1912 reformation, and their wearing of blue shirts for a second successive season. Their first season with a crest in 1913\u201314 would also become the last season before World War I began in 1914.\n\nThe official Coat of Arms of the [[Portsmouth|City of Portsmouth]] contains an eight pointed gold star and crescent moon on a blue shield, Portsmouth's adoption of the [[star and crescent]] is said to have come from when [[King Richard I]] (1157\u20131189), who granted the city \"a crescent of gold on a shade of azure, with a blazing star of eight points\" which he had taken from the [[Byzantine Emperor]]'s standard of Governor [[Isaac Komnenos of Cyprus|Isaac Komnenos]], after capturing [[Cyprus]].\n\nThe first 1913 Portsmouth F.C. crest was based on official symbols belonging to the town council of Portsmouth, which featured a golden eight-pointed star and a golden crescent moon.  The football club's first crest featured a horizontally elongated white crescent moon beneath a white five pointed star, with both symbols positioned in the centre of a blue four pointed shield. Portsmouth town council bestowed the privileged use (but not ownership) of their moon and star motifs to Portsmouth F.C., albeit with some colour and design changes.<ref name=\"historicalkits.co.uk\"/>\n\nThroughout their history Portsmouth F.C. have tried different variations of the crest before reverting to the basic gold star and crescent. After World War II, Portsmouth began using an eight-pointed star to match that used by the city of Portsmouth.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> In the 1950s and 1960s, the traditional crest was emblazoned on the shirt in white rather than gold but this was due to white being a cheaper alternative to a more expensive gold coloured thread.\n\nBetween 1980 and 1989, Portsmouth scrapped the traditional crest and replaced it with an entirely new design. This crest showed a football in front of an [[anchor]] (representing the navy) and a [[sword]] (representing the army), with the whole design surrounded by an outer ring of ships rope. An alternative version included a circular version of the traditional star and crescent crest in place of the football.\n\nDuring 1989 and 1993, the rope and anchor crest was dropped replaced with a simpler eight pointed star and crescent moon on a long narrow shield. At the foot of the shield, a blue banner featured \"''Portsmouth Football Club''\" written within it in capital letters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Portsmouth/Portsmouth.htm|title=Portsmouth - Historical Football Kits|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1993-1997, the 1989-93 long narrow shield design was replaced by an embroidered badge of the city of Portsmouth Coat of Arms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Portsmouth/Portsmouth.htm|title=Portsmouth - Historical Football Kits|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://greatestkits.co.uk/products/1993-95-portsmouth-home-shirt-l|title=1993/95 Portsmouth Home Shirt (L)|website=Greatest Kits|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nThe 1993-97 city arms crest was replaced in 1997, with an eight pointed gold star and a golden crescent moon on a blue shield edged with a gold outer rim. At the foot of the shield, a gold ribbon with \"''Portsmouth F.C.''\" written in blue gothic lettering completed the new design.  This new crest coincided with the rebuilding and reopening of the new Fratton End and tjhe clubs centennial anniversary in the 1997\u201398 season\n\nIn 2007, an additional \"Since 1898\" was added to the 1997 crest ribbon underneath the shield in time for the 2007\u201308 season.\n\nOn 6 May 2008, a month after their 110th Anniversary, Portsmouth revealed a new crest with a very three dimensional look, the tradition curved shield with \"three points\" at the top of the shield were replaced with two straightened angles, with \"Portsmouth F.C.\" written above the star on the shield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ffcw001.azureedge.net/-/media/team/england/crest/portsmouth.png?w=600&h=600|title=Portsmouth Crest|last=|first=|date=|website=ffcw001.azureedge.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The traditional elongated crescent moon was replaced with a new circular one, which closely resembled that on the city's Coat of Arms. The new crest had its debut in the 2008 FA Cup Final, in which Portsmouth also wore a new 110th Anniversary all-blue commemorative home strip.\n\nAs part of the World War I Centennial Commemorations in the 2014\u201315 season, the club opted to replace the 2008 crest on the home kit with one almost identical to that used in 1913\u201314. This was a more traditional-looking club crest featuring the traditional three points at the top of a slightly rounded shield but with a silver five-pointed star inside instead of the usual eight-pointed one. The moon featured on the crest was also silver, both appearing on a blue background.\n\nIn June 2015, following positive feedback from supporters, Portsmouth F.C. decided to revert the official club crest back to a familiar and traditional design, over the one introduced in 2008, which was often criticised by Pompey fans for looking too similar to Arsenal F.C.'s updated modern era crest. Portsmouth's new 2015 crest was virtually identical in design to that which has been used for the majority of the club's history. The famous \"star and moon\", both silver-white on a blue background, have a slight three-dimensional appearance. The star was restored back to the familiar eight pointed design, instead of the five pointed version used in the 1913 and 2014 crests. The crest's shield retains the three points at the top but is in a more traditional shape. No lettering or numbering features on the new club crest, just like that which was used on home shirts the previous 2014\u201315 season.\n\nOn 4 May 2017 at [[Portsmouth Guildhall]], The Tornante Company, owned by Michael Eisner met the Pompey Supporters Trust (PST), the fan-based owners of Portsmouth, to discuss a potential takeover of the football club. During the meeting, the prospective new owners identified a long overlooked ownership and copyright issue concerning the traditional Portsmouth crest \u2013 Portsmouth Football Club did not legally \"own\" the symbols on the crest, which had actually only been \"on loan\" to the club from Portsmouth City Council since 1913.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0n7DZY79jTY |publisher=The Tornante Company |via=YouTube.com |title=Michael Eisner's Q&A Session with Portsmouth Supporters Trust |date=13 May 2017 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe Tornante Company completed their purchase of Portsmouth on 3 August 2017 after a majority vote from members of the Pompey Supporters Trust to sell.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} To rectify the copyright and commercial marketing issues with the current 2015 crest, the decision was taken by the new owners to design and copyright a brand new crest for the future.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} Portsmouth's fans were consulted by traditional and digital media during late 2017 and early 2018 with various designs for new crests. Most of the designs were minor tweaks and adjustments of the existing 2015 crest, just enough to make a new crest design different from that of Portsmouth City Council's coat of Arms.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nOn 15 March 2018, two newly redesigned club crests were finally revealed. Both new crests featured a new eight pointed nautical compass star and the addition of an \"1898\" date, the founding year of the football club, beneath the crescent moon. The new crests are to be copyrighted and introduced for the new 2018\u201319 season. The first new crest, similar to previous crests, is intended for players shirts. The second crest, surrounded by a blue ring with \"Portsmouth Football Club\" written in it, will be used for letterheads, merchandise and other commercial purposes.<ref name=\"portsmouthfc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Home colours==\n{|\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _claretborder|\n pattern_b = _Roma2|\n pattern_ra = _claretborder|\n pattern_sh = |\n pattern_so = |\n leftarm = ff9999|\n body = ff9999|\n rightarm = ff9999|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n socks = 000000|\n title = 1899\u20131909\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _collar|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = FFFFFF|\n body         = FFFFFF|\n rightarm = FFFFFF|\n shorts = 003366|\n socks = 003366|\n title = 1909\u20131912\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _collarwhite|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = 0066FF|\n body         = 0066FF|\n rightarm = 0066FF|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n pattern_so = _2 white stripes|\n socks = 000000|\n title = 1912\u20131933\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _collarwhite|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n pattern_so = _2 white stripes|\n socks = 000000|\n title = 1933\u20131947\n}}\n|}\n\nIn their first 1899\u20131900 season in the Southern League Division One, Portsmouth's first home colours were salmon pink shirts with maroon collars and cuffs, matched with white shorts and black socks.  The pink shirts gave the early Portsmouth F.C. the alternative second nickname of 'The Shrimps'. The collars and cuffs were the same colour as the Corporation of Portsmouth's public trams, which were painted maroon at the time.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Portsmouth/Portsmouth.htm |title=Portsmouth |publisher=Historical Football Kits |website=historicalkits.co.uk |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref> These colours lasted until the end of the 1908\u201309 season. 'The Shrimps' nickname then also declined from common usage.\n\nAt the start of the 1909\u201310 season, Portsmouth changed to white shirts with navy blue shorts and navy blue socks. The next season, Portsmouth ended the poor 1910\u201311 season in bottom place and Portsmouth were relegated to Southern League Division Two. Following relegation, a financial crisis, fund raising, promotion in early 1912 and then another financial crisis, the original Portsmouth company that had been formed in 1898 was 'wound up'. A new limited company was formed on 27 July 1912 as Portsmouth F.C.'s parent company.\n\nFor the start of the 1912\u201313 Southern League Division One season, Portsmouth changed their home colours to azure blue shirts, white shorts and black socks. This was to become Portsmouth's home kit colour combination up until the start of the 1933\u201334 season, when the shirts were changed to a royal blue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Portsmouth/Portsmouth.htm|title=Portsmouth - Historical Football Kits|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk}}</ref> These colours remained until the start of the 1947\u201348 season, when the black socks were changed to red; this coinciding with the club's most successful period and has remained the favoured colours for the majority of the time since.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pompey's Home Kits Through The Ages |url=http://www.pompeyweb.co.uk/kits.htm |publisher=PompeyWeb |accessdate=27 August 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603114751/http://www.pompeyweb.co.uk/kits.htm |archivedate=3 June 2008}}</ref> Portsmouth F.C. changed their colour combination several times during the 1966\u20131976 period, before reverting to the now tradition post-war blue shirts, white shorts and red stockings in 1976.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> For the club's 110th anniversary season in 2008\u201309, Portsmouth played in an all blue home kit, which debuted in the previous season's successful 2008 FA Cup Final win.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Since the 2009\u201310 season, Portsmouth reverted to the now traditional blue-white-red home kit.\n\n===Red socks memorial===\n{|\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _collarwhite|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n socks = FF0000|\n title = 1947\u20131966\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _whiteborder|\n pattern_b = _whitecollar|\n pattern_ra = _whiteborder|\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n shorts = 0000FF|\n pattern_so = _whitehorizontal|\n socks = 0000FF|\n title = 1966\u20131972\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _whiteborder|\n pattern_b = _whitecollar|\n pattern_ra = _whiteborder|\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n pattern_sh = _blue stripes|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n pattern_so = _whitehorizontal|\n socks = 0000FF|\n title = 1972\u20131973\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _blueborder|\n pattern_b = _pfcaway10|\n pattern_ra = _blueborder|\n leftarm = FFFFFF|\n body = |\n rightarm = FFFFFF|\n shorts = 0000FF|\n pattern_so = _bluehorizontal|\n socks = FFFFFF|\n title = 1973\u20131976\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _vneckwhite|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n socks = FF0000|\n title = 1976\u20132008\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _whiteline|\n pattern_b  = _pfcccc|\n pattern_ra = _whiteline|\n leftarm    = 0000FF|\n body       = 0000FF|\n rightarm   = 0000FF|\n shorts     = 0000FF|\n socks      = 0000FF|\n title      = 2008\u20132009\n}}\n|}\nPortsmouth had predominantly worn black socks since their first match in 1899 up until the end of the post-World War II 1946\u201347 FA Cup season \u2013 in which the Football League had not yet resumed.\n\nDuring the Second World War and post-war periods, the British Army's [[Bernard Montgomery|Field Marshal Sir Bernard 'Monty' Montgomery]] had been based at [[Southwick House]], 5 miles to the north of Portsmouth. Montgomery regularly attended war-time League South matches at Fratton Park, becoming the honorary President of Portsmouth Football Club. Following the suggestion by Montgomery, red socks were introduced by the club as a memorial to soldiers lost in wartime as red is the traditional colour of the British Army and also the colour of the [[Remembrance poppy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2013/may/crest-of-a-wave/ |title=Crest Of A Wave |publisher=Portsmouth Football Club |date=22 May 2013 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nWith the resumption of a full professional Football League season in England in 1947\u201348, Portsmouth changed their socks from the usual black to red for the start of the 1947\u201348 season. This also gave the Portsmouth team a patriotic blue, white and red appearance similar to the United Kingdom's red white and blue [[Union Flag]].\n\nThe new red socks also coincided with Portsmouth's most successful period, as the club won two consecutive top-tier division (now 'Premier League') title honours in [[1948\u201349 Football League|1948\u201349]] and [[1949\u201350 Football League|1949\u201350]], so the red socks were retained for good luck.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===Away colours===\nThe most frequent away colours used by Portsmouth have been white shirts with royal or navy blue shorts and either blue or white socks.<ref name=\"historicalkits.co.uk\"/> The club has had white as either the second or third choice shirt for every season since 1998\u201399 to date.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} Other colours that have appeared several times on Portsmouth change kits have been yellow (usually with blue shorts) and red (often combined with black).{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} From the 2006\u201307 season to the 2008\u201309 season the club have used black with a gold trim as their third choice colours.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} In the 2009\u201310 season the third kit was black with blue trim and thin blue hoops.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} The away kit was white with two navy blue vertical lines running the whole way down the side of the shirt, with the badge superimposed on top of them.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} The home kit has been the classic red white and blue kit, with plain blue shirt, plain white shorts and plain red socks.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} For the [[2010 FA Cup Final]], Portsmouth wore a change kit of white shirts, burgundy shorts and burgundy socks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/7719775/FA-Cup-final-Chelsea-v-Portsmouth-preview.html|title=FA Cup final: Chelsea v Portsmouth preview|date=14 May 2010|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref> For 2010\u201311, the away kit was a white shirt, with maroon shorts and socks (image below). In 2011\u201312, the away kit was a black shirt, with black shorts and socks; the club also announced a third one, with a divided shirt half-black and half-red; shorts and socks were black. For 2012\u201313, the club returned with a white shirt as an away kit, and turned into an orange-type third kit, with black shorts and orange socks.\n\nFor the 2017\u201318 season, Portsmouth had two away kits. The first choice away kit had white shirts, blue shorts and blue socks. The second choice was an all navy blue strip with pink collars, cuffs and other trim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2017/july/201718-away-kit-now-on-sale/ |title=2017/18 Away Kit: Now On Sale |work=Portsmouth F.C. |date=27 July 2017 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2017/august/201718-third-kit-now-on-sale/ |title=2017/18 Third Kit: Now On Sale |work=Portsmouth F.C. |date=3 August 2017 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFor 2018\u201319 season, sportswear manufacturer Nike produced a first-choice away kit of white shirts with a blue v-neck and blue shoulders, trimmed with blue sleeve cuffs. The shorts and socks are plain blue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2018/july/pompey-unveil-201819-away-kit/ |title=Pompey Unveil 2018/19 Away Kit |work=Portsmouth F.C.  |date=13 July 2018 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref> An all-black third kit was revealed on 13 August 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2018/august/pompey-reveal-201819-third-kit/ |title=Pompey Reveal 2018/19 Third Kit |work=Portsmouth F.C. |date=13 August 2018 |accessdate=23 October 2018 }}</ref> to avoid clashing with other teams such as [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] who wear blue and white quartered shirts as their first choice home kit colours.\n\nFor 2019-20, Portsmouth revealed on 5 July 2019 an all purple-indigo third kit, based on Nike's ''Park Derby II SS'' template.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kitlocker.com/products/results,1-0?error=404|title=All Products &#124; Football, Rugby, Gym &#124; Kitlocker.com 404 The requested product does not exist.|website=www.kitlocker.com}}</ref> The third kit had a purple shirt with white shoulder stripe and cuffs, purple shorts with white side stripes, and purple socks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2019/july/pompey-launch-201920-third-kit/|title=Pompey Launch 2019/20 Third Kit|website=www.portsmouthfc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Other historic kits===\n\n{|\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _whiteline\n| pattern_b  = _pfcccc\n| pattern_ra = _whiteline\n| leftarm    = 0000FF\n| body       = 0000FF\n| rightarm   = 0000FF\n| shorts     = 0000FF\n| socks      = 0000FF\n| title      = [[2008 FA Cup Final]]\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _pompey1011a|\n pattern_b = _pompey1011a|\n pattern_ra = _pompey1011a|\n leftarm = fe8e7a|\n body         = 86202e|\n rightarm = fe8e7a|\n shorts = 800000|\n socks = 800000|\n title = [[2010 FA Cup Final]] (Away)\n}}\n|}\n\nFor the [[2007\u201308 FA Cup|2008 FA Cup Final]] victory against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], Portsmouth debuted an all blue home kit manufactured by [[Canterbury of New Zealand|Canterbury]] and sponsored by [[Oki Electric Industry|Oki Printing Solutions]] to commemorate the club's 110th Anniversary year. The all blue home kit was also used throughout the following 2008\u201309 season.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nPortsmouth again reached the [[2009\u201310 FA Cup|FA Cup Final in 2010]], but were defeated 1\u20130 by [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. Portsmouth, as the away team, wore a white and maroon kit inspired from elements of the original \"Shrimps\" era (1899\u20131909) kit in which maroon collars and cuffs featured on the salmon pink home shirts.\n\n===Kit manufacturers and sponsors===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!Years\n!Manufacturers\n!Shirt sponsors (front)\n!Shirt sponsors (back)\n|-\n|1976\u20131977\n|[[Umbro]]\n|rowspan=5|''No sponsors''\n|rowspan=18|''No sponsors''\n|-\n|1978\u20131980\n|[[Admiral Sportswear|Admiral]]\n|-\n|1980\u20131983\n|[[Gola (manufacturer)|Gola]]\n|-\n|1983\u20131984\n|[[Le Coq Sportif]]\n|-\n|1985\u20131987\n|[[Umbro]]\n|-\n|1987\u20131989\n|[[Admiral Sportswear|Admiral]]\n|[[Fiat]]\n|-\n|1989\u20131991\n|Scoreline\n|rowspan=3|[[Goodmans Industries|Goodmans]]\n|-\n|1991\u20131993\n|Influence\n|-\n|1993\u20131995\n|rowspan=2|[[ASICS]]\n|-\n|1995\u20131997\n|[[The News (Portsmouth)|The News]]\n|-\n|1997\u20131999\n|[[Admiral Sportswear|Admiral]]\n|KJC Mobile Phones\n|-\n|1999\u20132000\n|rowspan=3|Pompey Sport <sup>1</sup>\n|The Pompey Centre\n|-\n|2000\u20132002\n|Bishop's Printers\n|-\n|2002\u20132005\n|[[Ty Inc.|TY Europe]]\n|-\n|2005\u20132007\n|[[Jako]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Oki Electric Industry|OKI]]\n|-\n|2007\u20132009\n|rowspan=2|[[Canterbury of New Zealand|Canterbury]]\n|-\n|2009\u20132010\n|rowspan=4|Jobsite.co.uk\n|-\n|2010\u20132011\n|[[Kappa (company)|Kappa]]\n|-\n|2011\u20132013\n|[[Kappa (company)|Kappa]]\n|rowspan=3|Covers Timber & Builders Merchants <sup>2</sup>\n|-\n|2013\u20132018\n|[[Sondico]]\n|-\n|2018\u20132021\n|[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n|rowspan=3|[[University of Portsmouth]]\n|}\n\n'''<sup>1</sup>''' Portsmouth's own manufacturer.<br />\n'''<sup>2</sup>''' As from 2011\u201312 season, sponsors were added to the back of EFL clubs shirts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pompeyshirts.co.uk/history/ |title=Shirt History |work=Pompey Shirts |accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==\"Pompey\" nickname==\nPortsmouth Football Club are traditionally nicknamed '''''Pompey''''', a nickname already long associated with the English city of Portsmouth and its [[HMNB Portsmouth|Royal Navy base]]. An exact origin for the ''Pompey'' nickname has never formally been identified by historians, as many variations, sources and interpretations of the ''Pompey'' nickname exist.\n\nOne possible theory of the Pompey nickname is the [[Contraction (grammar)|grammatical contraction]] of the [[Old Portsmouth]] location name '''[[Portsmouth Point]]''' to the shorter '''Po'm. P.''' ('''Po''''''rts'''''m.'''''outh'' '''P.'''''oint'') which supposedly saved time and space when handwritten into a ship's logbook. Other theories include Royal Navy romanticism of the Roman character '''[[Pompey]]''' from [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Antony and Cleopatra]]'', used by officers to inspire the ship's company.\n\nAnother ''Pompey'' nickname theory, based on actual historic events, originates from {{HMS|Pompee|1793|6}}, originally a newly built [[T\u00e9m\u00e9raire-class ship of the line|T\u00e9m\u00e9raire class]] French frigate named ''La Pomp\u00e9e'' that was surrendered by French Royalists during the [[French Revolution]] to their British allies during the [[Siege of Toulon]] in 1793. The ship ''La Pomp\u00e9e'' eventually arrived at [[Spithead]] in 1794 and was recommissioned into the Royal Navy as ''HMS Pomp\u00e9e''.  In 1797, HMS ''Pomp\u00e9e'' was one of sixteen ships involved in the [[Spithead and Nore mutinies]] of 1797. During her later career, HMS ''Pomp\u00e9e'' also served as Portsmouth's guard ship and ended her career in the early nineteenth century anchored in [[Portsmouth Harbour]] as the chief prison ship ''Pompee''. ''Pompee'' was also used as prison ship for French prisoners captured during the [[Napoleonic Wars]] (1803\u20131815). The harsh treatment received aboard ''Pompee'' gained a national notoriety with the criminal classes of England, the name ''Pompey'' itself became a northern England slang word for prison.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/notesandqueries/query/0,5753,-2010,00.html?gusrc=gpd |title=Why is Portsmouth called Pompey? |work=The Guardian |author=David Francis |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> The ''Pompee'' became a familiar local landmark and gained a common association with the Royal Navy and the civilian Portsmouth population, who both then began associating ''Pompee'' with Portsmouth. ''Pompee'' was finally taken away to be broken up in [[Woolwich]] in 1817, but her name lived on in Portsmouth folklore, anglicised to \"''Pompey''\" over time.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe present Portsmouth Football Club were not the first football club in the city of Portsmouth to be known as ''Pompey''. In the 1890s, an amateur Portsmouth-based British Army team, '''Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C.''' were reported in newspapers with the ''Pompey'' nickname, as well as also being known as ''The Gunners''.  Royal Artillery Portsmouth's supporters were also responsible for creating [[Portsmouth F.C.#'The Pompey Chimes'|\"The Town Hall Chimes\"]] chant, which later became known as ''\"The Pompey Chimes\"'' chant in the twentieth century.  The chant originally began at Royal Artillery Portsmouth's home football ground at Burnaby Road, Portsmouth ([[United Services Recreation Ground]]) and was within easy earshot of the nearby Portsmouth Town Hall (now called [[Portsmouth Guildhall]]) clock bells, which had inspired the chant.\n\nRoyal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C. were disqualified for \"professionalism\" after an 1898\u201399 FA Amateur Cup match.  Royal Artillery were also forced to field only a team of amateur reserve players, thus weakening the remaining Royal Artillery team for the remainder of the 1898\u201399 Southern Football League season. Royal Artillery finished bottom of the [[1898\u201399 Southern Football League#Division One|table]], relegated after a relegation match with Cowes F.C. and were eventually disbanded. The \"Pompey\" nickname, the \"Town Hall Chimes\" chant, some of the Royal Artillery players and their supporters then migrated to a newly formed football club, named Portsmouth F.C., earlier formed on 5 April 1898.<ref name=\"portsmouth.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/heritage/history-of-the-chimes-1-1299340|title=History of the chimes|website=Portsmouth.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nPortsmouth F.C., as the \"new\" Pompey, played their first Southern Football League match away to Chatham Town on Saturday 2 September 1899, winning 0\u20131. Their first home match at Fratton Park stadium took place only four days later on Wednesday 6 September 1899, a friendly match against Southampton F.C., which Portsmouth won 2\u20130. During the first early seasons of Portsmouth F.C., the football team wore salmon pink shirts with maroon collars and cuffs, white shorts and black socks. The pink shirts gave rise to an alternative nickname, ''''The Shrimps''''. 'The Shrimps' went out of common usage after 1909 when Portsmouth F.C. began playing in white shirts, navy blue shorts and navy blue stockings. After the original 1898 founding company was replaced in 1912, Portsmouth began playing in their now familiar blue shirts in the 1912\u201313 season.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n==Stadium==\n[[File:Fratton Park entrance.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The entrance to Fratton Park's South Stand, with its mock Tudor facade]]\n{{main|Fratton Park}}\nPortsmouth F.C. play their home games at Fratton Park, in the district of [[Milton, Portsmouth]]. The stadium has been home to the club throughout its entire history since the club formed in 1898. Fratton Park is affectionately nicknamed \"The Old Girl\" by Portsmouth F.C. supporters.\n\nPlans for relocation were first mooted in the early 1990s, but due to various objections and financial obstacles, the club has continued to play at Fratton Park. Most recently, plans for relocation have included new stadia on a site offered by the [[Royal Navy]] at [[Horsea Island]], between Stamshaw and Port Solent, and on reclaimed land in Portsmouth Harbour beside the existing naval base. The former was mooted as a possible [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] venue as part of England's bid process. However, the cost to the city's taxpayers to join the bid was deemed too great a risk to take.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8378313.stm |title=Football \u2013 Portsmouth pulls out of 2018 bid |publisher=BBC News |date=25 November 2009 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> A third, oft returned-to option, is to build a new stadium on the site of the existing Fratton Park.\n\nFollowing Portsmouth F.C.'s financial troubles, subsequent relegation from the Premier League, and the failure of the England 2018 bid, as of May 2017 there are no active plans for a new club stadium.\n\n==Supporters and rivalries==\n{{main|South Coast derby}}\n[[File:Pompeywembley.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Portsmouth fans at Wembley Stadium for the 2007\u201308 FA Cup semi-final with West Bromwich Albion]]\nPortsmouth's main rivals are [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], who are 19.8 miles (31.8&nbsp;km) away, with the \"border\" between the two located in the Hampshire village of [[Titchfield]].  The [[South Coast Derby]] is one of the less frequently played rivalries within English football due to the clubs being in different divisions however this usually adds to the ferocity of the fixture.\n\nPrior to the mid/late 1960s, rivalry between Portsmouth and Southampton was largely non-existent, as a consequence of their disparity in league status. This [[Local derby|derby match]] has been sporadic. Since 1977, the teams have only played league games against each other in four seasons (1987\u201388, 2003\u201304, 2004\u201305 and 2011\u201312). Including Southern League games, there have been 64 league games between the clubs, but they have also met five times in the FA Cup, Portsmouth beating their rivals 4\u20131 at [[St Mary's Stadium]] in their last meeting in 2010, and twice in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] \u2013 with Southampton winning both times.\n\nMany Portsmouth supporters commonly use the derogatory nickname '''''Scummer''''' (plural: '''''Scummers''''') to describe Southampton fans, or collectively '''''Scum''''' to also include their football club, and indeed the city of Southampton itself.\n* A disproven common origin theory dating from the late twentieth century suggested that the ''Scum'' nickname was an acronym of ''Southampton Company of Union Men'', linked to a vague recollection of an unspecified and unsourced past dockers strike, in which Southampton-based dockers supposedly crossed Portsmouth dockyard picket lines when brought in as [[Strikebreaker|scab labour]] to work inside the naval base. This theory is almost certainly an urban myth, as Royal Navy dockers are not permitted to go on strike.\n* Victorian era dockers employed in the supposedly higher status [[HMNB Portsmouth|Portsmouth Royal Dockyard]], looked down in disdain upon the civilian merchant port dockers at [[Port of Southampton|Southampton Docks]] and nicknamed them ''Scum'', as scum, flotsam and jetsam are useless residue found floating on, or nearby water.\n* According to the Oxford English Dictionary, ''Scummers'' was a derogatory name with naval origins for pirates or buccaneers, and was first recorded in use in 1585.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/scummer |title=scummer |work=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=24 January 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/jan/23/newsstory.sport8 |title=Scummers v Skates |work=The Guardian |author=Kevin Mitchell |date=23 January 2005 |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Portsmouth supporters have had the equally derogatory nickname '''''Skate''''' bestowed upon them by Southampton fans as a rebuttal to ''Scummer'' since the 1987\u201388 Division One season. This was unofficially chosen by Southampton fans from a list of insults compiled by a Southampton-based supporters fanzine called ''The Ugly Inside'' in 1988.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fansnetwork.co.uk/football/southampton/news/48841/ |title=Why Bournemouth Will Never Be Saints Rivals ! |work=FansNetwork |date=17 October 2018 |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> Ironically, the chosen nickname ''Skate'' was actually stolen from the civilian population of Portsmouth, who had long used ''Skate'' as a derogatory insult or nickname for sailors based in Portsmouth Dockyard and other Royal Navy establishments. According to legend and folklore, Royal Navy matelots on long sea voyages were regularly denied female company, and would keep a [[Skate (fish)|skate]] (fish species) in their hammock or bunkside, as the mouth of the skate was supposedly used as a substitute vagina. Sailors ashore in Royal Navy uniform seeking the services of Portsmouth's prostitutes would often be refused service and met with a ''\"I ain't no skate bait, mate!\"'' rebuttal.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>\n\nAnother rivalry over the years, colloquially known as the \"Dockyard Derby\", is with [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/7201902.stm|title=Naval support for Dockyard Derby|date=22 January 2008|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2289954/Tynan-Plymouth-can-cause-derby-upset.html|title=Tynan: Plymouth can cause derby upset|date=25 January 2008|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> This rivalry is also known as the Battle of the Ports.<ref name=harvey>{{cite book |title=Rivals: The Off-Beat Guide to the 92 League Clubs |last1=Harvey |first1=Geoff |last2=Strowger |first2=Vanessa |year=2004 |publisher=Aesculus Press Ltd |location=Swadlincote, Derbyshire |isbn=1-904328-13-X |page=133 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mG7XLIPEHvAC&pg=PT111&dq=%22battle+of+the+ports%22+football |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> In recent seasons the club has also developed a minor rivalry with [[Sunderland AFC|Sunderland]], mainly stemming from the clubs meeting each other 5 times in the 18/19 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-portsmouth-story-so-far-16284128|title=Sunderland vs Portsmouth: A story of red cards, penalties and a simmering rivalry|first=Sean|last=Tighe|date=16 May 2019|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\nLesser rivalries exist with fellow South Coast clubs [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], [[Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton and Hove Albion]] and South London club [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].\n\n==='The Pompey Chimes'===\nThe best-known chant sung by Portsmouth supporters are \"The Pompey Chimes\". The chant is regarded as football's oldest chant still in use today.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew|last=Pettie|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/7821392/An-ode-to-footballs-rowdy-poets.html|title=An ode to football's rowdy poets|date=11 June 2010|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=McCallum>{{cite book |title=Glory Gunners: The History of Royal Artillery FC Portsmouth |first=Kevin |last=Smith |year=1999 |publisher=K.Smith |location=London |isbn=0-9534707-0-9 |page=69}}</ref>\n\n\"The Pompey Chimes\" were originally called \"The Town Hall Chimes\", and were created by the supporters of '''Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) Football Club''', a British Army artillery regiment team, who were the most popular and successful amateur football team based in Portsmouth for much of the 1890s. Royal Artillery played their home matches at the [[United Services Recreation Ground]] in Burnaby Road, Portsmouth,<ref name=\"portsmouth.co.uk\"/> and were already nicknamed \"Pompey\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hoppingaroundhampshire.blogspot.com/2013/04/39-united-services-portsmouth-fc.html|title=Hopping Around Hampshire: 39. United Services Portsmouth FC|first=Andrew|last=Ormerod|date=9 April 2013}}</ref> before the founding of Portsmouth F.C. in 1898.\n\nThe nearby Portsmouth Town Hall (now called the [[Portsmouth Guildhall]]), only 0.3 miles (0.5&nbsp;km) from Burnaby Road was completed in 1890, and would strike the various [[Westminster Quarters]] chimes every quarter hour. Football referees would use the Town Hall's clock bells as a reference to when the football match should end at 4&nbsp;pm. Just before 4&nbsp;pm the crowd of supporters would slowly lilt in unison with the Town Hall's chimes on the hour to encourage the referee to blow the whistle to signify full-time. The original words to 'The Pompey Chimes' (as printed in the 1900\u201301 Official Handbook of Portsmouth F.C.), were:\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\"> \\relative c' {    \\time 5/4 \\key e \\major e4 gis fis b,2 | e4 fis gis e2 | gis4 e fis b,2 |  b4 fis' gis e2 | R1*5/4\\fermataMarkup  \\bar \"||\"  \\clef bass \\time 4/4 e,1^\"Portsmouth Town Hall Chimes (4pm)\"  | e1| e1 | e1 |}</score>\n<!--[[File:Westminster Quarter 4.svg|frameless|upright=3.17]]\n<br>[[File:Westminster Big Ben.svg|frameless|upright=0.83]] ( Big&nbsp;Ben)-->\n\n''Play up Pompey,''<br />\n''Just one more goal!'' <br />\n''Make tracks! What ho!''<br />\n''Hallo! Hallo!!''\n\nWith the demise of Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C. after their expulsion from the 1898\u201399 [[FA Amateur Cup]] for alleged professionalism, many of Royal Artillery's supporters switched their allegiance in 1899 to Portsmouth F.C., taking the \"Town Hall Chimes\" chant and the \"Pompey\" nickname from Burnaby Road to [[Fratton Park]], a distance of 1.8 miles (2.8&nbsp;km).\n\nThe Pompey Chimes are still sung at Fratton Park today, and have evolved to be sung at a quicker tempo, and with a shortened chime style \u2013 usually twice:\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\"> \\relative c'' {\\time 5/4  \\key e \\major gis4 e fis b,2 | b4 fis' gis e2 | gis4 e fis b,2 | b4 fis' gis e2 |}</score>\n<!--[[File:Westminster Quarter 3.svg|frameless|upright=2.56]]-->\n\n''Play up Pompey,''<br />\n''Pompey play up!''<br />\n''Play up Pompey,''<br />\n''Pompey play up!''\n\n==Portsmouth in Europe==\n{{main|Portsmouth F.C. in European football}}\n\nPortsmouth made their European debut in the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Cup]]. After a home victory against [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]] and a home draw against [[A.C. Milan]], Portsmouth were knocked out at the group stages after a 3\u20132 away loss to [[VfL Wolfsburg]].\n\n==Women's football==\nThe club's female counterpart is [[Portsmouth F.C. Ladies|Portsmouth F.C. Womens]], which was founded in 1987. The team currently plays in the [[FA Women's Premier League National Division]], after having won the [[FA Women's Premier League Southern Division]] in 2012. Pompey are the current holders of the Hampshire Cup. Following the takeover of Portsmouth F.C. by the Portsmouth Supporters Trust, it was announced that there would be closer ties between the men's and women's clubs.\n\n==Affiliated clubs==\nPortsmouth have had a long-standing relationship with [[Havant & Waterlooville F.C.|Havant & Waterlooville]], with regular pre-season friendlies organised between the two clubs. Portsmouth have also previously used [[West Leigh Park]], Havant & Waterlooville's home stadium, for reserve team matches. Previous links with Belgian side [[S.V. Zulte Waregem|Zulte Waregem]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=554308&sec=england&cc=5739 |title=Portsmouth strike deal with Zulte Waregem|publisher=ESPN FC |date=9 July 2008 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> and Irish academy [[Home Farm F.C.|Home Farm]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouth.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=144840|title=Pompey announce link-up with Home Farm|publisher=portsmouth.vitalfootball.co.uk|date=23 February 2009}}</ref> have been cancelled.\n\nPortsmouth have developed a relationship with [[Gosport Borough F.C.|Gosport Borough]] after their promotion to the Conference South. Portsmouth fans were encouraged to support Gosport in their FA Trophy final match at Wembley in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/article/blues-backing-borough-1430566.aspx?pd=635308236000000000|title=Blues Backing Borough|publisher=Portsmouth F.C.}}</ref> They also play friendlies and loan out players to the side.\n\n==Club honours==\nSource for honours:<ref name=History>{{cite web|url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/club/history/|title=History|website=Portsmouth FC.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===League competitions===\n; [[Football League First Division]] (1888\u20131992) > [[Premier League]] (1992\u2013present)\n* '''Champions (2):''' [[1948\u201349 Football League|1948\u201349]], [[1949\u201350 Football League|1949\u201350]]\n\n; [[Football League Second Division]] (1892\u20131992) > [[Football League First Division]] (1992\u20132004) > [[EFL Championship]] (2004\u2013present)\n* '''Champions (1):''' [[2002\u201303 Football League|2002\u201303]]\n* Runners-up (2): [[1926\u201327 Football League|1926\u201327]], [[1986\u201387 Football League|1986\u201387]]\n\n; [[Football League Third Division South]] (1921\u20131958) > [[Football League Third Division]] (1958\u20131992) > [[EFL League One]] (2004\u2013present)\n* '''Champions (3):''' [[1923\u201324 Football League|1923\u201324 (South)]], [[1961\u201362 Football League|1961\u201362]], [[1982\u201383 Football League|1982\u201383]]\n\n;[[EFL League Two]] (2004\u2013present)\n* '''Champions (1):''' [[2016\u201317 EFL League Two|2016\u201317]]\n\n===Cup competitions===\n;[[FA Cup]]\n* '''Winners (2):''' [[1939 FA Cup Final|1938\u201339]], [[2008 FA Cup Final|2007\u201308]]\n* Runners-up (3): [[1929 FA Cup Final|1928\u201329]], [[1934 FA Cup Final|1933\u201334]], [[2010 FA Cup Final|2009\u201310]]\n\n;[[FA Community Shield]]\n* '''Winners (1):''' [[1949 FA Charity Shield|1949]] (shared)\n* Runners-up (1): [[2008 FA Community Shield|2008]]\n\n;[[EFL Trophy]] \n* '''Winners (1):''' [[2019 EFL Trophy Final|2018\u201319]]\n* Finalists (TBD): [[2020 EFL Trophy Final|2019\u201320]]\n\n;[[Hampshire Senior Cup]]\n* '''Winners (4):''' 1903, 1913, 1952, 1987\n* Runners-up (4): 1900, 1904, 1905, 1959\n\n===Lower league competitions===\n; [[Southern Football League|Southern Football League First Division]]\n* '''Champions (2):''' [[1901\u201302 Southern Football League|1901\u201302 (not elected for promotion)]], [[1919\u201320 Southern Football League|1919\u201320]] {{Efn|Portsmouth became founder members of the inaugural [[Football League Third Division]] in 1920.}}\n* Runners-up (2): [[1899\u20131900 Southern Football League|1899\u20131900]], [[1906\u201307 Southern Football League|1906\u20131907]]\n\n; [[Southern Football League|Southern Football League Second Division]]\n* Runners-up (1): [[1911\u201312 Southern Football League|1911\u201312]]\n\n; [[Western Football League|Western Football League First Division]]\n* '''Champions (3):''' [[1900\u201301 Western Football League|1900\u201301]], [[1901\u201302 Western Football League|1901\u201302]], [[1902\u201303 Western Football League|1902\u201303]]\n\n===Other/friendly honours===\n\n;[[London War Cup]] (replaced by [[Football League War Cup]])\n* Runners-up (1): 1942\n\n;[[Premier League Asia Trophy]]\n* '''Winners (1):''' [[2007 Premier League Asia Trophy|2007]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/2632222/pompey-win-asia-trophy |title=Pompey win Asia Trophy |publisher=Sky Sports |author=Peter Fraser |accessdate=11 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/402272 |title=History of the Premier League Asia Trophy |publisher=The Premier League |date=25 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n;[[Edmonton Cup]]\n* '''Winners (1):''' [[Edmonton Cup|2010]]<ref>http://www.portsmouth-mad.co.uk/feat/edy9/portsmouth_season_review_20102011_preseason_677836/index.shtml</ref>\n\n==Club records==\n* Home attendance record: '''51,385''' v [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], [[1948\u201349 FA Cup|1949 FA Cup Fifth Round]], 26 February 1949, [[Fratton Park]]\n* Away attendance record: '''99,370''' v [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]], [[1938\u201339 FA Cup|1939 FA Cup Final]], 29 April 1939, [[Wembley Stadium (1923)]]\n* Current [[Wembley Stadium]] attendance record for a football match: '''89,874''' (90,000 capacity), [[2008 FA Cup Final]], 17 May 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/10993576/which-wembley-records-could-tottenham-break-this-season |title=Which Wembley records could Tottenham break this season? |work=Sky Sports |author=Adam Smith |date=18 August 2017 |accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n* Record victory: '''9\u20131''' v [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], [[Football League Second Division|Division 2]], 9 April 1927\n* Record defeat: '''0\u201310''' v [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], [[Football League First Division|Division 1]], 20 October 1928\n* Highest scoring game: '''7\u20134''' v [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], [[Premier League]], 29 September 2007\n* Most consecutive wins (all competitions): '''9''' (4 January 2020 - 8 February 2020) <ref>https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/matches/results/</ref>\n* Most appearances for club: '''834''' [[Jimmy Dickinson]], 1946\u201365\n* Most league goals for club: '''194''' [[Peter Harris (footballer)|Peter Harris]], 1946\u20131960\n* Most league goals in a season: '''42''' [[Guy Whittingham]], 1992/93\n* Most goals for club: '''211''' [[Peter Harris (footballer)|Peter Harris]], 1946\u201360\n* Most international caps whilst at club: '''48''' [[Jimmy Dickinson|Jimmy Dickinson (England)]]\n* Transfer record (received): '''\u00a318&nbsp;million''' from [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] for [[Lassana Diarra]] December 2008\n* Transfer record (paid): '''\u00a311&nbsp;million''' to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] for [[Peter Crouch]], July 2008\n\n===Record signing===\nOn 11 July 2008, Portsmouth completed the club-record signing&nbsp;\u2013 thought to be around \u00a311&nbsp;million&nbsp;\u2013 of [[England national football team|England]] striker [[Peter Crouch]] in a four-year deal from Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web |title=Portsmouth agree Peter Crouch transfer fee |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/liverpool/2305024/Portsmouth-agree-Peter-Crouch-transfer-fee.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=7 July 2008|accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> This marked the second time Crouch had been Portsmouth's most expensive player as in 2001 his \u00a31.5&nbsp;million fee was a club record. Portsmouth's first million-pound signing was [[Rory Allen]] in July 1999.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pompey swoop for Spurs striker |url=http://archive.andoveradvertiser.co.uk/1999/7/15/90597.html |newspaper=Andover Advertiser |date=15 July 1999|accessdate=27 August 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108194850/http://archive.andoveradvertiser.co.uk/1999/7/15/90597.html|archivedate=8 January 2009}}</ref> The highest fee received was \u00a318&nbsp;million for midfielder [[Lassana Diarra]] from [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/portsmouth/3811291/Portsmouth-accept-exceptional-Real-Madrid-bid-for-Lassana-Diarra.html|title=Portsmouth accept exceptional Real Madrid bid for Lassana Diarra|work=The Telegraph |first=Jeremy |last=Wilson |date=17 December 2008 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Portsmouth FC}}\n\n===Official websites===\n* {{Official website|http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk}}\n* [http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2009/clubs/club=84297/matches/index.html Portsmouth F.C.] at the [[UEFA]] official website\n\n===News sites===\n{{BBC football info|portsmouth|Portsmouth F.C.}}\n* [http://www.skysports.com/football/teams/portsmouth Portsmouth F.C. news] from [[Sky Sports]]\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite book| ref = harv  | first = Simon  | last = Inglis  | title = Football Grounds of Britain  | year = 1996  | publisher = Collins Willow  | isbn = 0-00-218426-5  }}\n* {{cite book\n| first=Colin |last=Farmery\n| title=Portsmouth: the Modern Era \u2013 a Complete Record\n| publisher=Desert Island Books\n| year=2005\n| isbn=1-905328-08-7}}\n* {{cite book\n| first=Colin |last=Farmery\n| title=Portsmouth: From Tindall to Ball \u2013 A Complete Record\n| publisher=Desert Island Books\n| year=1999\n| isbn=1-874287-25-2}}\n* {{cite book\n| first=Colin |last=Farmery\n| title=Seventeen Miles From Paradise \u2013 Saints v Pompey: Passion, Pride and Prejudice\n| publisher=Desert Island Books\n| year=2004\n| isbn=1-874287-89-9}}\n* {{cite book\n| first1=Cass |last1=Pennant|first2=Rob |last2=Silvester\n| title=Rolling with the 6.57 Crew \u2013 The True Story of Pompey's Legendary Football Fans\n| publisher=John Blake Publishing\n| year=2004\n| isbn=1-84454-072-3}}\n\n{{Portsmouth F.C.}}\n{{Portsmouth F.C. seasons}}\n{{EFL League One}}\n{{Premier League}}\n{{EFL Championship}}\n\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1898]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Sport in Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Premier League clubs]]\n[[Category:English Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:FA Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:1898 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Companies that have entered administration in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "91.125.132.70", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portsmouth_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Ineos", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|Privately owned multinational chemicals company}}\n{{For|the British cycling team|Team Ineos}}\n{{COI|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name       = Ineos\n| logo       = Ineos logo.png\n| type       = [[Private company limited by shares|Private limited company UK]]\n| founder    = [[Jim Ratcliffe|Sir Jim Ratcliffe]]\n| key_people = {{ubl|class=nowrap\n | [[Jim Ratcliffe|Sir Jim Ratcliffe]] | {{small|(Chairman & CEO)}}\n | Andy Currie | {{small|(Director)}}\n | [[John Reece]] | {{small|(Finance Director)}}\n | Jim Dawson | {{small|(Non-Executive Director)}} }}\n| industry   = [[Chemical industry|Chemical]]s\n| products   = [[Chemical substance]]s, [[petrochemical]]s, [[plastic]]s\n| revenue    = [[US$]]  85 billion <small>(2019); <br>[[EBITDA]] = \u20ac4.3 billion</small><ref name=\"ineos.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ineos.com/Company/| title=INEOS is a world class producer of Petrochemicals and speciality chemicals |publisher=INEOS.com |date=1 June 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>\n| num_employees = 22,000<ref name=\"ineos.com\"/>\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1998|df=yes}}\n| location   = {{ubl|[[London]], UK|{{small|(Head office)}}|[[Lyndhurst, Hampshire|Lyndhurst]], Hampshire, UK|{{small|(Registered office)}}}}\n| homepage   = {{url|https://www.ineos.com/|Ineos.com}}\n}}\n'''Ineos''' is a privately owned UK [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] [[chemicals company]] headquartered and registered in [[London]], UK.It is mostly in chemicals and gas having $83 billion by  revenue.\n\nIneos is organised into around 20 standalone business units, each with its own board with the intention of operating almost entirely independently, albeit Ratcliffe, and his associates, still appear to occasionally sit on these boards.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/9318986c-8ec2-11e3-b6f1-00144feab7de.html|title=Jim D. Ratcliffe|first=Sylvia|last=Pfeifer|date=20 November 2014|publisher=|via=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe name Ineos is derived from Inspec Ethylene Oxide Specialities, a previous name of the business.<ref name=ineos>{{Cite web | url = https://www.ineos.com/es/inch-magazine/articles/issue-4/jims-a-leader-in-his-field | title = Jim's a Leader in His Field | publisher = ineos.com}}</ref> It also stems from one [[Latin]] and two [[Greek language|Greek]] words that Ratcliffe, and his two sons, found when searching for a company name. \"Ineo\" is Latin for a new beginning, \"Eos\" is the Greek goddess of dawn, and \"neos\" is Greek something new and innovative. As a result, Ineos states its name represents the \"dawn of something new and innovative\".<ref name=ineos/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Petrochemical plant - geograph.org.uk - 479373.jpg|thumb|Part of the Grangemouth petrochemical plant in Scotland; the site has been an oil refinery since 1924]]\n[[File:2012-05-28 Fotoflug Cuxhaven Wilhelmshaven DSC 3890.jpg|thumb|Part of the Ineos facility in Wilhelmshaven, Germany]]\nIn 1992, Inspec was formed by Sir Jim Ratcliffe, previously a director of the [[United States of America|U.S.]] [[private equity]] group [[Advent International]], and by John Hollowood, for the purpose of executing a [[management buy-in]] of [[BP|British Petroleum]]'s (BP) chemicals arm.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ratcliffe in joint bid for ICI's acrylics arm|last1=Marsh|first1=Virginia|last2=Rivlin|first2=Richard|work=[[Financial Times]]|location=London|date=18 September 1999|page=26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Murray Johnstone Backs Jim Ratcliffe in Ineos Buyout|last=Jury|first=Jennifer|work=UK Venture Capital Journal|date=1 June 1998|page=1}}</ref>  \n\nIn 1995, Inspec bought BP's [[ethylene oxide]], and [[glycol]], businesses for \u00a378 million, to become ''Inspec Ethylene Oxide Specialities''.<ref name=\"mortished\">{{cite news|title=Inspec sells Antwerp to managers|last=Mortished|first=Carl|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=15 April 1998|page=25}}</ref>  \n\nIn 1998, Ratcliffe, then a director of Inspec, established Ineos for the purpose of purchasing Inspec's ethylene oxide facility in [[Antwerp]], Belgium.<ref name=\"taylor\">{{cite news|title=Director to lead \u00a384m buy-out of Inspec arm|last=Taylor|first=Roger|work=[[Financial Times]]|location=London|date=15 April 1998|page=25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icis.com/v2/companies/9145300/ineos/structure.html |title=INEOS &#124; Company Structure Information from |publisher=ICIS |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  The \u00a384 million purchase was funded by three entities: the Scottish investment house [[Aberdeen Asset Management|Murray Johnstone]] (\u00a310 million), Ineos management (\u00a31.5 million), and the [[Investment banking|investment bank]] [[Alex. Brown & Sons|BT Alex Brown]] (\u00a372.5 million, raised through [[High-yield debt|junk bonds]]).<ref name=mortished/><ref name=taylor/><ref>{{cite news|title=Finance sector leads index to another record high|last=Clark|first=Michael|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=15 April 1998|page=26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=EDC in $500m five-year deal|last=Luce|first=Edward|work=[[Financial Times]]|location=London|date=29 April 1998|page=44}}</ref>\n\nThe company grew quickly through the acquisition of commodity chemical businesses from corporate giants such as [[BP]], [[Imperial Chemical Industries|ICI]] and [[BASF]].\n\nThere have been three distinct phases of Ineos's growth.<ref>{{cite web|author=Iain Dey in Geneva |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/business/Industry/article1257966.ece |title=What Jim Ratcliffe did next |publisher=The Sunday Times |date=12 May 2013 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  The first phase spanned over ten years, with Ineos acquiring 22 companies between 1998 and 2008.  The two most notable of these were Innovene, the [[olefin]]s and derivatives and refining subsidiary of [[BP]], in October 2005 for $9 billion,<ref>{{cite web|last=Catan |first=Thomas |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/1fb19d20-3740-11da-af40-00000e2511c8,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F1fb19d20-3740-11da-af40-00000e2511c8.html&_i_referer=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FIneos |title=BP to sell Innovene to Ineos in $9bn deal |publisher=FT.com |date=7 October 2005 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref> and ICI's commodity chemicals business in 2001.  \n\nThe second phase between 2008 and 2010 saw a period of consolidation as the company tackled the impact of the global recession.  As production of consumer goods, cars, and construction fell during this period, the company saw sales and earnings fall.  During this period a major competitor [[LyondellBasell]] filed for bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/01/06/lyondellbasell-us-unit-files-for-bankruptcy/ | work=The New York Times | title=Lyondell Files for Bankruptcy | date=6 January 2009}}</ref> Some predicted a similar fate for Ineos but the company emerged from this period intact. \n\nThe third phase commenced in 2011. In this phase the company has continued to grow through a series of strategic joint ventures.\n\nIn June 2011, the largest of these, Petroineos, was completed. It is a 50:50 joint venture between Ineos and [[PetroChina]]. It combines Ineos's refining interests at [[Grangemouth Refinery|Grangemouth]], [[Scotland]], and at Lav\u00e9ra near [[Martigues]], [[France]] (about 30 miles west of [[Marseille]]),  with PetroChina's access to upstream raw materials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ineoschlorvinyls.com/en/News/Ineos-Group/PetroChina-and-Ineos-announce-plans-for-new-trading-and-refining-JV-in-Europe/?business=Ineos+Group |title=PetroChina and INEOS announce plans for new trading and refining JV in Europe |publisher=INEOSchlorvinyls.com |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn June 2011, Ineos and BASF combined their [[styrene]] businesses to form another 50:50 partnership, [[Styrolution]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basf.com/group/corporate/en_GB/news-and-media-relations/news-releases/news-releases-usa/P-10-0018 |title=and INEOS sign joint venture contract for Styrolution - BASF - The Chemical Company - Corporate Website |publisher=BASF |date=31 May 2011 |accessdate=23 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130823113629/http://www.basf.com/group/corporate/en_GB/news-and-media-relations/news-releases/news-releases-usa/P-10-0018 |archivedate=23 August 2013  }}</ref>  \n\nIneos's growth has continued through this period, expanding production in the US and China. Most recently Ineos announced a joint venture with [[Solvay (company)|Solvay]] bringing together their European [[polyvinyl chloride]] businesses.<ref name=\"solvay.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.solvay.com/EN/NewsPress/20130507%20Solvay_Ineos.aspx |title=Solvay and INEOS join forces to create a world-class PVC producer |publisher=Solvay.com |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIneos's heritage is in a number of well-known blue chip chemical companies. These include [[Amoco]], [[BASF]], [[Bayer]], [[Borealis AG|Borealis]], [[BP]], [[Degussa]], [[Dow Chemical Company]], Enichem, Erd\u00f6lchemie, Hoechst, [[Imperial Chemical Industries|ICI]], Innovene, [[Lanxess]], [[Monsanto]], [[Norsk Hydro]] and [[Solvay (company)|Solvay]]. The company was formed in 1998 to affect a [[management buyout]] of the former [[BP]] petrochemicals assets in [[Antwerp]], Belgium.<ref>{{cite news|author=Migration Temp |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/migrationtemp/2813915/Ratcliffe-the-alchemist.html |title=Ratcliffe, the alchemist |publisher=Telegraph |date=12 August 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2013 |location=London}}</ref> Since then, it has expanded by purchasing several other businesses. Several of its divisions formerly belonged to BP, and others that have been divested by large companies such as [[Amoco]], [[BASF]], [[Imperial Chemical Industries|ICI]], [[Dow Chemical]], [[Solvay (company)|Solvay]] and [[UCB (company)|UCB]], as they have looked to focus more closely on their main product lines. In October 2005 Ineos agreed to purchase Innovene, BP's [[olefin]]s and derivatives and refining subsidiary, which had an estimated 2005 turnover of [[US$]]25 billion, for $9 billion.<ref>{{cite web|last=Catan |first=Thomas |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/1fb19d20-3740-11da-af40-00000e2511c8.html |title=BP to sell Innovene to Ineos in $9bn deal |publisher=FT.com |date=7 October 2005 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  The deal, which was completed on 14 December 2005, roughly quadrupled Ineos's turnover, which was previously around $8 billion.\n\nIn 2007 Ineos formed a joint venture with [[Lanxess]] and created Ineos ABS, comprising Lanxess's activities in [[acrylonitrile butadiene styrene]] production, located in [[Tarragona]]. Ineos paid \u20ac35 million in a first tranche.<ref>[http://www.lustran-polymers.com/lup/en/news/content/joint_venture_lustran_polymers_business/] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071105003718/http://www.lustran-polymers.com/lup/en/news/content/joint_venture_lustran_polymers_business/|date=5 November 2007}}</ref> In March 2010 Ineos Healthcare terminated its drug development programme for commercial reasons.\n\nIn February 2011 Ineos Bio broke ground on a landmark advanced [[biofuel]]s facility in Florida.\n\"INEOS Bio\u2019s biorefinery will have the capacity to produce 8 million gallons of [[ethanol]] and 6 megawatts (gross) of electricity per year.\" \"The INEOS Bio process can produce ethanol and [[renewable energy]] from numerous non-food feedstocks, including construction and [[municipal solid waste]], forestry and agricultural waste.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biofuelsdigest.com/bdigest/2011/02/10/ineos-bio-breaks-ground-on-landmark-advanced-biofuels-facility-in-florida/|title=INEOS Bio breaks ground on landmark advanced biofuels facility in Florida|publisher=Biofuels Digest|date=10 February 2011|accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  In July 2013 Ineos Bio announced that the Florida plant is producing [[cellulosic ethanol]] on a commercial scale and claim to be the first in the world to do so using this new technology.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ineos.com/en/News/INEOS-Group/INEOS-Bio-Produces-Cellulosic-Ethanol-at-Commercial-Scale/ |title=First facility in the world using new advanced bioenergy technology to convert waste to renewable fuel and electricity |date=31 July 2013 |accessdate=19 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925000043/http://www.ineos.com/en/News/INEOS-Group/INEOS-Bio-Produces-Cellulosic-Ethanol-at-Commercial-Scale/ |archivedate=25 September 2013  }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 October 2013 Ineos announced the closure of its petrochemical plant in [[Grangemouth]], Scotland,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-24631342|title=Grangemouth dispute: Ineos says petrochemical plant will close |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=23 October 2013 |accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref> following a dispute with the [[Unite the Union|Unite]] trade union over pensions and an attempt to impose a wage freeze and new contract on the workforce. However, by 25 October 2013 the union gave in to the closure threats, and agreed to all Ineos's demands meaning the plant would stay open and strike-free for three years<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-24640274 |title=Q&A: Grangemouth - What now?|publisher=bbc.co.uk|date=23 October 2013|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref> and in September 2016 the company completed a new headquarters building at Grangemouth as part of a \"site rejuvenation plan\".<ref>{{cite web|title=INEOS completes construction of its new, state of the art Grangemouth Headquarters as part of its site rejuvention plan|url=http://www.ineos.com/sites/grangemouth/news/ineos-completes-construction-of-its-new-grangemouth-headquarters/|publisher=INEOS|location=Grangemouth|date=6 September 2016|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Ineos reached an agreement to buy the [[Forties pipeline system]] in the North Sea from [[BP]] for $250 million. The sale included terminals at [[Dalmeny]] and Kinneil, a site in Aberdeen, and the Forties Unity Platform.<ref>{{cite news|title=BP sells Forties North Sea pipeline to Ineos|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-business-39476674|accessdate=3 April 2017|publisher=BBC News|date=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nTowards the start of 2019, in the wake of [[British MPs]] rejecting [[Theresa May]]'s [[Brexit]] Deal, the company chose to fund a \u20ac3bn investment (\u00a32.6bn) in petrochemical production in [[Antwerp, Belgium]].<ref>[https://www.ft.com/content/8df66d84-18d6-11e9-9e64-d150b3105d21 \"Ineos chooses Antwerp for \u20ac3bn petrochemical investment\"], Financial Times, 16 January 2019</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, during the [[2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic|Coronavirus Outbreak]] Ineos set up new plants to provide hand sanitiser free to hospitals <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theengineer.co.uk/ineos-hand-sanitiser-factory-up-and-running/ |access-date=2 April 2020 |website=The Engineer |title=INEOS hand sanitiser factory up and running |date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/stories-52126847 |access-date=2 April 2020 |website=BBC News |title=Coronavirus: Where has all the hand sanitiser gone?}}</ref>\n\n==Markets==\nIneos provides products for many markets including: Fuels and Lubricants (23.3%), Packaging and Food (18.5%) and Construction (16.1%). Other markets include Automotive & Transport, White Goods & Durables, Pharmaceutical & Agrochemical and Textiles.<ref name=\"http://www.ineos.com/en/Company\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ineos.com/en/Company/ |title=INEOS is a world class producer of Petrochemicals and speciality chemicals |publisher=INEOS.com |date=1 June 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803164239/http://www.ineos.com/en/Company/ |archivedate=3 August 2013  }}</ref>\nThe majority of Ineos's geographic earnings are distributed across Germany (16.8%), USA (16.1%), UK (12.3%), France (11.6%) and Benelux (10.8%).<ref name=\"http://www.ineos.com/en/Company\"/>\n\nIneos is involved in renewable energy and is one of the world's leading pioneers in the development of generating sustainable energy from waste material.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323681904578640450212016598 |title=Florida Plant to Produce Advanced Ethanol - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=31 July 2013 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIneos reportedly runs operations with minimal head office management, feeling that \"work teams\" are better suited for handling of the workflow day to day, without middle-management.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/mar2002/2002-03-06-05.asp |title=Big Cut in UK Firms' Carcinogenic Emissions |publisher=Ens-newswire.com |date=6 March 2002 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Ineos announced plans to invest up to \u00a3640m in [[shale gas]] exploration in the UK. The company plans to use the gas as a raw material for its chemicals plants, including Grangemouth near Falkirk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-30125028|title=Ineos to invest \u00a3640m in UK shale gas exploration - BBC News|publisher=}}</ref>  Ineos CEO, Jim Ratcliffe, has criticized restrictions on [[fracking]] in the UK.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-48125581</ref>\n\n==Joint ventures==\n===Petroineos===\nPetroineos is a refining and trading joint venture between Ineos and [[PetroChina]] formed in 2011. It is Europe's leading independent [[crude oil]] refiner, with a turnover of $15 billion. It has two refineries, one in Lav\u00e9ra (part of [[Martigues]]), France, and one in [[Grangemouth Refinery|Grangemouth]], Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/oilandgas/8614799/PetroChina-completes-1bn-Ineos-deal.html |title=PetroChina completes $1bn Ineos deal |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=23 August 2013 |location=London |date=4 July 2011}}</ref> The value of the Grangemouth chemicals plant, which Ineos had once valued at 400 million pounds was written down to nothing by them in October 2013 during conflict with the union. Later that month it was reported that PetroChina was unhappy with the return on the billion dollars cash they had paid for a 50% stake in the Grangemouth, Scotland and Lavera, France refineries.  According to a Hong Kong business analyst: \"The European refineries are pretty much loss making. In future there won't be any similar investments\".<ref>Singapore (Platts)--21Oct2013 [http://www.platts.com/latest-news/oil/singapore/china-abandons-downstream-investments-on-poor-27541936 China abandons downstream investments on poor returns]</ref>\n\n===Other ventures===\nPQ Corporation is a joint venture between Ineos (31%),  [[CCMP Capital|CCMP]] (58%), and PQ management (11%).  PQ is a global producer of inorganic chemicals, [[catalyst]]s and engineered glass products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccmpcapital.com/news?n=529|title=CCMP :: News|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nMost recently, [[Solvay S.A.|Solvay]] and Ineos are to create a 50:50 joint venture which will see them combine their chlorvinyls sites in Europe.  This joint venture will become the world's third largest producer of [[PVC]].<ref name=\"solvay.com\"/>\n\n== Ineos Automotive ==\n{{see|Ineos Grenadier}}\nIneos Automotive Ltd. was formed in 2017 by Jim Ratcliffe in order to develop and manufacture an [[off-road vehicle|off-road utility vehicle]], intended as a \"spiritual successor\" to the [[Land Rover Defender]], under the codename ''Projekt Grenadier''.<ref name=\"motor\">{{cite web |last1=Vijayenthiran |first1=Viknesh |title=Unofficial Land Rover Defender successor gets a name |url=https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1112769_unofficial-land-rover-defender-successor-gets-a-name-projekt-grenadier |website=Motor Authority |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=19 September 2017}}</ref> In September 2019, it was announced that vehicle, now officially named Ineos Grenadier, would be manufactured in two new factories in [[Estarreja]], [[Portugal]] (chassis and body) and [[Bridgend]], [[South Wales]] (final assembly), with [[powertrain]]s supplied by [[BMW]]. Launch is planned for 2021.<ref name=\"car\">{{cite web | last=Overland | first= Colin |title=Ineos Grenadier: Brit-built \u2018spiritual heir\u2019 to old Defender arrives 2021 |url=https://www.carmagazine.co.uk/car-news/first-official-pictures/ineos-projekt-grenadier-an-old-school-4x4-off-roader-for-2020/ |website=[[Car Magazine]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nIneos manufactures and distributes a wide range of petrochemicals, speciality chemicals and oil products:<ref name=\"http://www.ineos.com/en/Company\"/>\n{| class=\"sortable\"\n|-\n! Business !! Products\n|-\n|<small>Ammonia/nitric acid *</small>\n|<small>[[Ammonia]] and [[nitric acid]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Baleycourt *</small>\n|<small>[[Ester]]s, [[biodiesel]], and chlorinated paraffins</small>\n|-\n|<small>[[Chlorotoluene]]s *</small>\n|<small>[[Benzyl alcohol]], [[benzyl chloride]], [[benzaldehyde]], [[benzoyl chloride]], [[benzotrichloride]], dibenzyloxide, ortho-chlorobenzyl chloride and ortho-chlorobenzaldehyde</small>\n|-\n|<small>Compounds *</small>\n|<small>[[Polyvinyl chloride|PVC]] compounds</small>\n|-\n|<small>Ethanol *</small>\n|<small>[[Ethanol]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Inovyn</small>\n|<small>[[Brine]], [[Sodium hydroxide|caustic soda]], [[Organochloride|chlorinated solvents]], chlorine derivatives, [[chlorine]], [[Ethylene dichloride|EDC]], [[ethylene]], [[propylene]], [[Polyvinyl chloride|PVC]], Recycled PVC and VCM</small>\n|-\n| <small>Melamines *</small>|| <small>[[Formaldehyde]] and melamine formaldehyde resin</small>\n|-\n| <small>Nitriles</small>||<small>[[Acetonitrile]], [[acrylonitrile]], [[ammonium sulfate]], [[hydrogen cyanide]] and [[maleic anhydride]] catalyst</small>\n|-\n| <small>Olefins and Polymers Europe</small>||<small>[[Benzene]], [[1,3-Butadiene|butadiene]], [[ethylene]], [[High-density polyethylene|HDPE]], [[Low-density polyethylene|LDPE compounds]], [[Low-density polyethylene|LDPE]], [[Linear low-density polyethylene|LLDPE]], polymerisation Ziegler catalysts, [[polypropylene]], [[propylene]] and [[toluene]]</small>\n|-\n| <small>Olefins and Polymers USA</small>||<small>[[1,3-Butadiene|Butadiene]], [[butane]], crude [[benzene]], ethane/propane mix, [[ethylene]], [[fuel oil]], [[High-density polyethylene|HDPE]], mixed [[butene]]s, other bottoms liquids, [[polypropylene]], [[propane]], and propylene</small>\n|-\n| <small>Oligomers</small>||<small>[[diisobutylene|DIB]], the [[dimer (chemistry)|dimer]] of [[isobutylene]] (isoolefins/isoparafins), IA (isoamylene/TAME), [[linear alpha olefin]]s, [[Polyalpha-olefins|poly alpha olefins]], [[Butyl rubber|polyisobutene]], Technikum (cyclopentane, CP70, methylpropadiene)</small>\n|-\n| <small>Oxide</small>||<small>[[Acetate]], acetate esters, alkoxilates, alkoxylates, ENB & [[glycol ethers]], [[ethanolamine|EOA]]s, [[ethyl acetate]], [[ethylene glycol]], [[ethylene oxide]], glycol ethers, [[oxo alcohols]], [[propylene glycol]], and [[propylene oxide]]</small>\n|-\n| <small>Paraform *</small>||<small>[[Cyanate]]s, [[dimethoxymethane]], [[formaldehyde]], [[hexamethylenetetramine]], [[paraformaldehyde]], and triallylcyanurate</small>\n|-\n| <small>Phenol</small>||<small>[[Acetone]], [[alpha-methylstyrene]] (AMS), [[cumene]] and [[phenol]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Salt *</small>\n|<small>Granular salt, pure dried vacuum salt, salt tablets, and undried vacuum salt</small>\n|-\n|<small>Solvents *</small>\n|<small>[[Diisopropyl ether]], [[ethanol]], [[isopropyl alcohol]], [[methyl ethyl ketone]], and [[2-Butanol|''s''-butyl alcohol]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Styrolution</small>\n|<small>ABS, AMSAN, ASA Resin, compounded grades, [[ethylbenzene]], general purpose polystyrene, high impact polystyrene, NAS, polyethylbenzene, polystyrene polymers - HIPS,  SAN, SBC (StyroFlex), specialty compounding, [[styrene]], and [[styrene monomer]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Sulphur Chemicals *</small>\n|<small>[[Sulfur dioxide]], [[sulfur trioxide]], [[sulfuric acid]], and ultra pure acid</small>\n|-\n| <small>Technologies</small> || <small>Licenses world class petrochemical technology for: [[polyethylene]], [[polystyrene]], [[vinyls]], [[polypropylene]], [[acrylonitrile]], chlor-alkali</small>\n|-\n|<small>Trading and Shipping</small>\n|<small>Trades and supplies petrochemical [[feedstock]]s, [[hydrocarbon]]s, [[energy]] and [[carbon credit]]s for both internal and external customers</small>\n|-\n|<small>Upsteam Shale</small>\n|<small>[[Natural gas]], exploration and production of natural gas from on-shore shale deposits. Produces UK gas on the national grid.</small>\n|-\n|<small>Upstream Breagh</small>\n|<small>Supplies [[natural gas]] to one in ten UK households.</small>\n|}\n\n''<small>*Ineos Enterprises consists of the following sub-businesses: ammonia/nitric acid, Baleycourt, chlorotoluenes, compounds, ethanol, melamines, paraform, salt, solvents and sulphur chemicals.</small>''\n\n==Industrial relations controversy==\n===2008===\nIn April 2008 Ineos, which was experiencing adverse economic conditions, was at the centre of an [[industrial relations]] dispute with [[Unite the Union|Unite]] over pension entitlements of the workforce at its [[Grangemouth Refinery]], when the company decided to close the final salary [[pension]] scheme to new employees. Unite claimed the Grangemouth workers were paid \u00a36,000 less than those at comparable facilities.<ref name=obs270408/> The 48-hour strike that followed caused panic buying of petrol throughout the country and the Forties production pipeline, a third of Britain's North Sea oil production, being closed.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\">Sunday Herald 28 July 2013 [http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/political-news/trade-union-threatens-to-shut-scotlands-only-oil-refinery-over-staff-suspension.21710944 Trade union threatened to shut Grangemouth refinery over Falkirk chairman's suspension]</ref> Ineos has been accused by some of buying assets then cutting costs through the introduction of new working practices, lower wages, and terminating pension schemes.<ref name=obs270408>{{cite news   | last = Doward  | first = Jamie  |author2=Gaby Hinsliff |author3=Denis Campbell   | title = Drivers are told not to panic buy as strike at oil refinery starts to bite  | work = [[The Observer]]  | page = 5  | language =   | publisher =   | date = 27 April 2008  | url =   | accessdate = }}</ref> According to Ratcliffe, some 65 per cent of salary costs at Grangemouth related to pensions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usgreentechnology.com/us-green-stories/ineos-financing-on-bioenergy-plant-will-create-almost-400-jobs/ |title=INEOS Financing on Bioenergy Plant Will Create Almost 400 Jobs |publisher=U.S. Green Technology |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref><ref>Telegraph, Sep 2013, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/10292664/Britain-is-not-an-attractive-place-to-manufacture-says-Ineos-chief-Jim-Ratcliffe.html Britain is not an attractive place to manufacture, says Ineos chief Jim Ratcliffe]</ref>\n\n===2013===\nStephen Deans, convener for Unite union at the Grangemouth plant where he worked, and also head of the Falkirk branch of the Labour party, was suspended from his employment at Grangemouth by Ineos in the summer of 2013, while they investigated what they said were accusations he had been using company resources for political campaigning; related to recruitment of Unite members in Ineos workforce to the local Labour branch, where the selection of a new parliamentary candidate was taking place after the de-selection of [[Eric Joyce]]. A Labour Party head office investigation into allegations that people had been made new members without them knowing or signing cleared Deans of the accusations, who had been suspended from the Labour party pending the investigation as well as the Unite candidate he was supporting.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\"/><ref>BBC news Sept 2013 [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24006702 Falkirk row: Unite union vindicated, says Len McCluskey]</ref><ref>Sky News [http://news.sky.com/story/1138181/labour-falkirk-candidate-karie-murphy-quits Labour: Falkirk Candidate Karie Murphy Quits]</ref><ref name=\"ft.com\">FT politic and Policy, [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5406b854-3ca9-11e3-a8c4-00144feab7de.html#axzz2ijxMBhQ7 Old wound threatens to reopen at Grangemouth]</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">BBC News business, 23 October 2013, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24640133 Grangemouth dispute: The key players]</ref>\n\nUnite said Deans was being subjected to \"sinister\" treatment, and in October an overtime ban at Grangemouth plant, which according to Ineos had operated at a loss of \u00a3150 million per year for the previous four years, started in protest.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\"/><ref name=\"ft.com\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>Friday 24 October 2013,[http://www.scotsman.com/news/grangemouth-how-downfall-began-with-bar-room-brawl-1-3153945 Grangemouth: How downfall began with bar-room brawl]</ref> A 48-hour strike was set for 20 October. Ineos announced the plant would be shut down before the strike and put forward a new deal direct to the workforce, warning that the plant might close permanently if it was rejected.  Two-thirds of workers voted against accepting Ineos's proposal, which would have reduced pension, shift pay and redundancy entitlements in addition to a pay freeze. On 23 October Ineos announced the permanent closure of the petrochemical site at Grangemouth.<ref>''Telegraph'', 23 October 2013, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/10398888/Grange mouth-timeline-of-the-dispute.html Grangemouth: timeline of the dispute]</ref> The next day the Unite union reversed its position and agreed to Ineos's proposals, which included an undertaking not to strike for three years.<ref>BBC News, 24 October 2013 [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-24647843 Grangemouth dispute: Hopes rise after Unite accepts survival plan]</ref> Deans resigned from his job at Grangemouth on 28 October 2013 after Ineos presented its findings to his team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/28/grangemouth-unite-official-quits|title=Grangemouth Unite official quits before he gets the boot|first1=Sean|last1=Farrell|first2=Rajeev|last2=Syal|date=28 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>The Courier..com uk,28 October 2013, [http://www.thecourier.co.uk/news/scotland/unite-official-stevie-deans-resigns-from-grangemouth-role-1.146625 Unite official Stevie Deans resigns from Grangemouth role] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031015212/http://www.thecourier.co.uk/news/scotland/unite-official-stevie-deans-resigns-from-grangemouth-role-1.146625 |date=31 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>28 October 2013, Scottish Television News</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn March 2016, Ineos's [[Port of Runcorn]] ChlorVinyls facility was found guilty of releasing [[caustic soda]] into the [[Manchester Ship Canal]]. The company was ordered to pay a fine of \u00a3166,650.<ref name=\"echo\">{{cite web|title=Runcorn chemical giant loses appeal over chemical spill fine|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/runcorn-chemical-giant-loses-appeal-10992836|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Ineos applied for a test core drilling for [[shale gas]] at [[Woodsetts]] (United Kingdom). It was met by protests of residents.<ref>[https://drillordrop.com/2019/06/11/live-news-updates-day-1-of-inquiry-into-ineos-shale-gas-plans-at-woodsetts/ Shale gas opponents protest outside inquiry at Ineos drilling plans]</ref><ref>[https://www.ineos.com/businesses/ineos-shale/news/ineos-shale-disappointed-by-councils-decision-on-woodsetts/ INEOS Shale disappointed by council's decision on Woodsetts]</ref> New plans for drilling at Woodsetts and Harthill had been applied and eventually approved by the Planning Inspectorate.<ref>[https://www.woodsettsagainstfracking.co.uk/single-post/2018/06/07/New-INEOS-plans-for-Woodsetts-and-Harthill-drilling-approved New INEOS plans for Woodsetts and Harthill drilling approved]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Shale gas in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://ineos.com}}\n{{Commons category|INEOS}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n[[Category:Chemical companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Ineos]]\n[[Category:Petrochemical companies]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{short description|Privately owned multinational chemicals company}}\n{{For|the British cycling team|Team Ineos}}\n{{COI|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name       = Ineos\n| logo       = Ineos logo.png\n| type       = [[Private company limited by shares|Private limited company UK]]\n| founder    = [[Jim Ratcliffe|Sir Jim Ratcliffe]]\n| key_people = {{ubl|class=nowrap\n | [[Jim Ratcliffe|Sir Jim Ratcliffe]] | {{small|(Chairman & CEO)}}\n | Andy Currie | {{small|(Director)}}\n | [[John Reece]] | {{small|(Finance Director)}}\n | Jim Dawson | {{small|(Non-Executive Director)}} }}\n| industry   = [[Chemical industry|Chemical]]s\n| products   = [[Chemical substance]]s, [[petrochemical]]s, [[plastic]]s\n| revenue    = [[US$]]  85 billion <small>(2019); <br>[[EBITDA]] = \u20ac4.3 billion</small><ref name=\"ineos.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ineos.com/Company/| title=INEOS is a world class producer of Petrochemicals and speciality chemicals |publisher=INEOS.com |date=1 June 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>\n| num_employees = 22,000<ref name=\"ineos.com\"/>\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1998|df=yes}}\n| location   = {{ubl|[[London]], UK|{{small|(Head office)}}|[[Lyndhurst, Hampshire|Lyndhurst]], Hampshire, UK|{{small|(Registered office)}}}}\n| homepage   = {{url|https://www.ineos.com/|Ineos.com}}\n}}\n'''Ineos''' is a privately owned UK [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] [[chemicals company]] headquartered and registered in [[London]], UK.It is mostly in chemicals and gas having $83 billion by  revenue.\n\nIneos is organised into around 20 standalone business units, each with its own board with the intention of operating almost entirely independently, albeit Ratcliffe, and his associates, still appear to occasionally sit on these boards.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/9318986c-8ec2-11e3-b6f1-00144feab7de.html|title=Jim D. Ratcliffe|first=Sylvia|last=Pfeifer|date=20 November 2014|publisher=|via=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe name Ineos is derived from Inspec Ethylene Oxide Specialities, a previous name of the business.<ref name=ineos>{{Cite web | url = https://www.ineos.com/es/inch-magazine/articles/issue-4/jims-a-leader-in-his-field | title = Jim's a Leader in His Field | publisher = ineos.com}}</ref> It also stems from one [[Latin]] and two [[Greek language|Greek]] words that Ratcliffe, and his two sons, found when searching for a company name. \"Ineo\" is Latin for a new beginning, \"Eos\" is the Greek goddess of dawn, and \"neos\" is Greek something new and innovative. As a result, Ineos states its name represents the \"dawn of something new and innovative\".<ref name=ineos/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Petrochemical plant - geograph.org.uk - 479373.jpg|thumb|Part of the Grangemouth petrochemical plant in Scotland; the site has been an oil refinery since 1924]]\n[[File:2012-05-28 Fotoflug Cuxhaven Wilhelmshaven DSC 3890.jpg|thumb|Part of the Ineos facility in Wilhelmshaven, Germany]]\nIn 1992, Inspec was formed by Sir Jim Ratcliffe, previously a director of the [[United States of America|U.S.]] [[private equity]] group [[Advent International]], and by John Hollowood, for the purpose of executing a [[management buy-in]] of [[BP|British Petroleum]]'s (BP) chemicals arm.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ratcliffe in joint bid for ICI's acrylics arm|last1=Marsh|first1=Virginia|last2=Rivlin|first2=Richard|work=[[Financial Times]]|location=London|date=18 September 1999|page=26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Murray Johnstone Backs Jim Ratcliffe in Ineos Buyout|last=Jury|first=Jennifer|work=UK Venture Capital Journal|date=1 June 1998|page=1}}</ref>  \n\nIn 1995, Inspec bought BP's [[ethylene oxide]], and [[glycol]], businesses for \u00a378 million, to become ''Inspec Ethylene Oxide Specialities''.<ref name=\"mortished\">{{cite news|title=Inspec sells Antwerp to managers|last=Mortished|first=Carl|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=15 April 1998|page=25}}</ref>  \n\nIn 1998, Ratcliffe, then a director of Inspec, established Ineos for the purpose of purchasing Inspec's ethylene oxide facility in [[Antwerp]], Belgium.<ref name=\"taylor\">{{cite news|title=Director to lead \u00a384m buy-out of Inspec arm|last=Taylor|first=Roger|work=[[Financial Times]]|location=London|date=15 April 1998|page=25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icis.com/v2/companies/9145300/ineos/structure.html |title=INEOS &#124; Company Structure Information from |publisher=ICIS |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  The \u00a384 million purchase was funded by three entities: the Scottish investment house [[Aberdeen Asset Management|Murray Johnstone]] (\u00a310 million), Ineos management (\u00a31.5 million), and the [[Investment banking|investment bank]] [[Alex. Brown & Sons|BT Alex Brown]] (\u00a372.5 million, raised through [[High-yield debt|junk bonds]]).<ref name=mortished/><ref name=taylor/><ref>{{cite news|title=Finance sector leads index to another record high|last=Clark|first=Michael|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=15 April 1998|page=26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=EDC in $500m five-year deal|last=Luce|first=Edward|work=[[Financial Times]]|location=London|date=29 April 1998|page=44}}</ref>\n\nThe company grew quickly through the acquisition of commodity chemical businesses from corporate giants such as [[BP]], [[Imperial Chemical Industries|ICI]] and [[BASF]].\n\nThere have been three distinct phases of Ineos's growth.<ref>{{cite web|author=Iain Dey in Geneva |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/business/Industry/article1257966.ece |title=What Jim Ratcliffe did next |publisher=The Sunday Times |date=12 May 2013 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  The first phase spanned over ten years, with Ineos acquiring 22 companies between 1998 and 2008.  The two most notable of these were Innovene, the [[olefin]]s and derivatives and refining subsidiary of [[BP]], in October 2005 for $9 billion,<ref>{{cite web|last=Catan |first=Thomas |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/1fb19d20-3740-11da-af40-00000e2511c8,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F1fb19d20-3740-11da-af40-00000e2511c8.html&_i_referer=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FIneos |title=BP to sell Innovene to Ineos in $9bn deal |publisher=FT.com |date=7 October 2005 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref> and ICI's commodity chemicals business in 2001.  \n\nThe second phase between 2008 and 2010 saw a period of consolidation as the company tackled the impact of the global recession.  As production of consumer goods, cars, and construction fell during this period, the company saw sales and earnings fall.  During this period a major competitor [[LyondellBasell]] filed for bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/01/06/lyondellbasell-us-unit-files-for-bankruptcy/ | work=The New York Times | title=Lyondell Files for Bankruptcy | date=6 January 2009}}</ref> Some predicted a similar fate for Ineos but the company emerged from this period intact. \n\nThe third phase commenced in 2011. In this phase the company has continued to grow through a series of strategic joint ventures.\n\nIn June 2011, the largest of these, Petroineos, was completed. It is a 50:50 joint venture between Ineos and [[PetroChina]]. It combines Ineos's refining interests at [[Grangemouth Refinery|Grangemouth]], [[Scotland]], and at Lav\u00e9ra near [[Martigues]], [[France]] (about 30 miles west of [[Marseille]]),  with PetroChina's access to upstream raw materials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ineoschlorvinyls.com/en/News/Ineos-Group/PetroChina-and-Ineos-announce-plans-for-new-trading-and-refining-JV-in-Europe/?business=Ineos+Group |title=PetroChina and INEOS announce plans for new trading and refining JV in Europe |publisher=INEOSchlorvinyls.com |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn June 2011, Ineos and BASF combined their [[styrene]] businesses to form another 50:50 partnership, [[Styrolution]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basf.com/group/corporate/en_GB/news-and-media-relations/news-releases/news-releases-usa/P-10-0018 |title=and INEOS sign joint venture contract for Styrolution - BASF - The Chemical Company - Corporate Website |publisher=BASF |date=31 May 2011 |accessdate=23 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130823113629/http://www.basf.com/group/corporate/en_GB/news-and-media-relations/news-releases/news-releases-usa/P-10-0018 |archivedate=23 August 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  \n\nIneos's growth has continued through this period, expanding production in the US and China. Most recently Ineos announced a joint venture with [[Solvay (company)|Solvay]] bringing together their European [[polyvinyl chloride]] businesses.<ref name=\"solvay.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.solvay.com/EN/NewsPress/20130507%20Solvay_Ineos.aspx |title=Solvay and INEOS join forces to create a world-class PVC producer |publisher=Solvay.com |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIneos's heritage is in a number of well-known blue chip chemical companies. These include [[Amoco]], [[BASF]], [[Bayer]], [[Borealis AG|Borealis]], [[BP]], [[Degussa]], [[Dow Chemical Company]], Enichem, Erd\u00f6lchemie, Hoechst, [[Imperial Chemical Industries|ICI]], Innovene, [[Lanxess]], [[Monsanto]], [[Norsk Hydro]] and [[Solvay (company)|Solvay]]. The company was formed in 1998 to affect a [[management buyout]] of the former [[BP]] petrochemicals assets in [[Antwerp]], Belgium.<ref>{{cite news|author=Migration Temp |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/migrationtemp/2813915/Ratcliffe-the-alchemist.html |title=Ratcliffe, the alchemist |publisher=Telegraph |date=12 August 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2013 |location=London}}</ref> Since then, it has expanded by purchasing several other businesses. Several of its divisions formerly belonged to BP, and others that have been divested by large companies such as [[Amoco]], [[BASF]], [[Imperial Chemical Industries|ICI]], [[Dow Chemical]], [[Solvay (company)|Solvay]] and [[UCB (company)|UCB]], as they have looked to focus more closely on their main product lines. In October 2005 Ineos agreed to purchase Innovene, BP's [[olefin]]s and derivatives and refining subsidiary, which had an estimated 2005 turnover of [[US$]]25 billion, for $9 billion.<ref>{{cite web|last=Catan |first=Thomas |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/1fb19d20-3740-11da-af40-00000e2511c8.html |title=BP to sell Innovene to Ineos in $9bn deal |publisher=FT.com |date=7 October 2005 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  The deal, which was completed on 14 December 2005, roughly quadrupled Ineos's turnover, which was previously around $8 billion.\n\nIn 2007 Ineos formed a joint venture with [[Lanxess]] and created Ineos ABS, comprising Lanxess's activities in [[acrylonitrile butadiene styrene]] production, located in [[Tarragona]]. Ineos paid \u20ac35 million in a first tranche.<ref>[http://www.lustran-polymers.com/lup/en/news/content/joint_venture_lustran_polymers_business/] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071105003718/http://www.lustran-polymers.com/lup/en/news/content/joint_venture_lustran_polymers_business/|date=5 November 2007}}</ref> In March 2010 Ineos Healthcare terminated its drug development programme for commercial reasons.\n\nIn February 2011 Ineos Bio broke ground on a landmark advanced [[biofuel]]s facility in Florida.\n\"INEOS Bio\u2019s biorefinery will have the capacity to produce 8 million gallons of [[ethanol]] and 6 megawatts (gross) of electricity per year.\" \"The INEOS Bio process can produce ethanol and [[renewable energy]] from numerous non-food feedstocks, including construction and [[municipal solid waste]], forestry and agricultural waste.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biofuelsdigest.com/bdigest/2011/02/10/ineos-bio-breaks-ground-on-landmark-advanced-biofuels-facility-in-florida/|title=INEOS Bio breaks ground on landmark advanced biofuels facility in Florida|publisher=Biofuels Digest|date=10 February 2011|accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>  In July 2013 Ineos Bio announced that the Florida plant is producing [[cellulosic ethanol]] on a commercial scale and claim to be the first in the world to do so using this new technology.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ineos.com/en/News/INEOS-Group/INEOS-Bio-Produces-Cellulosic-Ethanol-at-Commercial-Scale/ |title=First facility in the world using new advanced bioenergy technology to convert waste to renewable fuel and electricity |date=31 July 2013 |accessdate=19 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925000043/http://www.ineos.com/en/News/INEOS-Group/INEOS-Bio-Produces-Cellulosic-Ethanol-at-Commercial-Scale/ |archivedate=25 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 October 2013 Ineos announced the closure of its petrochemical plant in [[Grangemouth]], Scotland,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-24631342|title=Grangemouth dispute: Ineos says petrochemical plant will close |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=23 October 2013 |accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref> following a dispute with the [[Unite the Union|Unite]] trade union over pensions and an attempt to impose a wage freeze and new contract on the workforce. However, by 25 October 2013 the union gave in to the closure threats, and agreed to all Ineos's demands meaning the plant would stay open and strike-free for three years<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-24640274 |title=Q&A: Grangemouth - What now?|publisher=bbc.co.uk|date=23 October 2013|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref> and in September 2016 the company completed a new headquarters building at Grangemouth as part of a \"site rejuvenation plan\".<ref>{{cite web|title=INEOS completes construction of its new, state of the art Grangemouth Headquarters as part of its site rejuvention plan|url=http://www.ineos.com/sites/grangemouth/news/ineos-completes-construction-of-its-new-grangemouth-headquarters/|publisher=INEOS|location=Grangemouth|date=2016-09-06|accessdate=2017-03-31}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Ineos reached an agreement to buy the [[Forties pipeline system]] in the North Sea from [[BP]] for $250 million. The sale included terminals at [[Dalmeny]] and Kinneil, a site in Aberdeen, and the Forties Unity Platform.<ref>{{cite news|title=BP sells Forties North Sea pipeline to Ineos|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-business-39476674|accessdate=3 April 2017|publisher=BBC News|date=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nTowards the start of 2019, in the wake of [[British MPs]] rejecting [[Theresa May]]'s [[Brexit]] Deal, the company chose to fund a \u20ac3bn investment (\u00a32.6bn) in petrochemical production in [[Antwerp, Belgium]].<ref>[https://www.ft.com/content/8df66d84-18d6-11e9-9e64-d150b3105d21 \"Ineos chooses Antwerp for \u20ac3bn petrochemical investment\"], Financial Times, 16 January 2019</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, during the [[2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic|Coronavirus Outbreak]] Ineos set up new plants to provide hand sanitiser free to hospitals <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theengineer.co.uk/ineos-hand-sanitiser-factory-up-and-running/ |access-date=2020-04-02 |website=The Engineer |title=INEOS hand sanitiser factory up and running |date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/stories-52126847 |access-date=2020-04-02 |website=BBC News |title=Coronavirus: Where has all the hand sanitiser gone?}}</ref>\n\n==Markets==\nIneos provides products for many markets including: Fuels and Lubricants (23.3%), Packaging and Food (18.5%) and Construction (16.1%). Other markets include Automotive & Transport, White Goods & Durables, Pharmaceutical & Agrochemical and Textiles.<ref name=\"http://www.ineos.com/en/Company\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ineos.com/en/Company/ |title=INEOS is a world class producer of Petrochemicals and speciality chemicals |publisher=INEOS.com |date=1 June 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803164239/http://www.ineos.com/en/Company/ |archivedate=3 August 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nThe majority of Ineos's geographic earnings are distributed across Germany (16.8%), USA (16.1%), UK (12.3%), France (11.6%) and Benelux (10.8%).<ref name=\"http://www.ineos.com/en/Company\"/>\n\nIneos is involved in renewable energy and is one of the world's leading pioneers in the development of generating sustainable energy from waste material.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323681904578640450212016598 |title=Florida Plant to Produce Advanced Ethanol - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=31 July 2013 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIneos reportedly runs operations with minimal head office management, feeling that \"work teams\" are better suited for handling of the workflow day to day, without middle-management.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/mar2002/2002-03-06-05.asp |title=Big Cut in UK Firms' Carcinogenic Emissions |publisher=Ens-newswire.com |date=6 March 2002 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Ineos announced plans to invest up to \u00a3640m in [[shale gas]] exploration in the UK. The company plans to use the gas as a raw material for its chemicals plants, including Grangemouth near Falkirk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-30125028|title=Ineos to invest \u00a3640m in UK shale gas exploration - BBC News|publisher=}}</ref>  Ineos CEO, Jim Ratcliffe, has criticized restrictions on [[fracking]] in the UK.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-48125581</ref>\n\n==Joint ventures==\n===Petroineos===\nPetroineos is a refining and trading joint venture between Ineos and [[PetroChina]] formed in 2011. It is Europe's leading independent [[crude oil]] refiner, with a turnover of $15 billion. It has two refineries, one in Lav\u00e9ra (part of [[Martigues]]), France, and one in [[Grangemouth Refinery|Grangemouth]], Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/oilandgas/8614799/PetroChina-completes-1bn-Ineos-deal.html |title=PetroChina completes $1bn Ineos deal |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=23 August 2013 |location=London |date=4 July 2011}}</ref> The value of the Grangemouth chemicals plant, which Ineos had once valued at 400 million pounds was written down to nothing by them in October 2013 during conflict with the union. Later that month it was reported that PetroChina was unhappy with the return on the billion dollars cash they had paid for a 50% stake in the Grangemouth, Scotland and Lavera, France refineries.  According to a Hong Kong business analyst: \"The European refineries are pretty much loss making. In future there won't be any similar investments\".<ref>Singapore (Platts)--21Oct2013 [http://www.platts.com/latest-news/oil/singapore/china-abandons-downstream-investments-on-poor-27541936 China abandons downstream investments on poor returns]</ref>\n\n===Other ventures===\nPQ Corporation is a joint venture between Ineos (31%),  [[CCMP Capital|CCMP]] (58%), and PQ management (11%).  PQ is a global producer of inorganic chemicals, [[catalyst]]s and engineered glass products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccmpcapital.com/news?n=529|title=CCMP :: News|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nMost recently, [[Solvay S.A.|Solvay]] and Ineos are to create a 50:50 joint venture which will see them combine their chlorvinyls sites in Europe.  This joint venture will become the world's third largest producer of [[PVC]].<ref name=\"solvay.com\"/>\n\n== Ineos Automotive ==\n{{see|Ineos Grenadier}}\nIneos Automotive Ltd. was formed in 2017 by Jim Ratcliffe in order to develop and manufacture an [[off-road vehicle|off-road utility vehicle]], intended as a \"spiritual successor\" to the [[Land Rover Defender]], under the codename ''Projekt Grenadier''.<ref name=\"motor\">{{cite web |last1=Vijayenthiran |first1=Viknesh |title=Unofficial Land Rover Defender successor gets a name |url=https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1112769_unofficial-land-rover-defender-successor-gets-a-name-projekt-grenadier |website=Motor Authority |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=19 September 2017}}</ref> In September 2019, it was announced that vehicle, now officially named Ineos Grenadier, would be manufactured in two new factories in [[Estarreja]], [[Portugal]] (chassis and body) and [[Bridgend]], [[South Wales]] (final assembly), with [[powertrain]]s supplied by [[BMW]]. Launch is planned for 2021.<ref name=\"car\">{{cite web | last=Overland | first= Colin |title=Ineos Grenadier: Brit-built \u2018spiritual heir\u2019 to old Defender arrives 2021 |url=https://www.carmagazine.co.uk/car-news/first-official-pictures/ineos-projekt-grenadier-an-old-school-4x4-off-roader-for-2020/ |website=[[Car Magazine]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nIneos manufactures and distributes a wide range of petrochemicals, speciality chemicals and oil products:<ref name=\"http://www.ineos.com/en/Company\"/>\n{| class=\"sortable\"\n|-\n! Business !! Products\n|-\n|<small>Ammonia/nitric acid *</small>\n|<small>[[Ammonia]] and [[nitric acid]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Baleycourt *</small>\n|<small>[[Ester]]s, [[biodiesel]], and chlorinated paraffins</small>\n|-\n|<small>[[Chlorotoluene]]s *</small>\n|<small>[[Benzyl alcohol]], [[benzyl chloride]], [[benzaldehyde]], [[benzoyl chloride]], [[benzotrichloride]], dibenzyloxide, ortho-chlorobenzyl chloride and ortho-chlorobenzaldehyde</small>\n|-\n|<small>Compounds *</small>\n|<small>[[Polyvinyl chloride|PVC]] compounds</small>\n|-\n|<small>Ethanol *</small>\n|<small>[[Ethanol]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Inovyn</small>\n|<small>[[Brine]], [[Sodium hydroxide|caustic soda]], [[Organochloride|chlorinated solvents]], chlorine derivatives, [[chlorine]], [[Ethylene dichloride|EDC]], [[ethylene]], [[propylene]], [[Polyvinyl chloride|PVC]], Recycled PVC and VCM</small>\n|-\n| <small>Melamines *</small>|| <small>[[Formaldehyde]] and melamine formaldehyde resin</small>\n|-\n| <small>Nitriles</small>||<small>[[Acetonitrile]], [[acrylonitrile]], [[ammonium sulfate]], [[hydrogen cyanide]] and [[maleic anhydride]] catalyst</small>\n|-\n| <small>Olefins and Polymers Europe</small>||<small>[[Benzene]], [[1,3-Butadiene|butadiene]], [[ethylene]], [[High-density polyethylene|HDPE]], [[Low-density polyethylene|LDPE compounds]], [[Low-density polyethylene|LDPE]], [[Linear low-density polyethylene|LLDPE]], polymerisation Ziegler catalysts, [[polypropylene]], [[propylene]] and [[toluene]]</small>\n|-\n| <small>Olefins and Polymers USA</small>||<small>[[1,3-Butadiene|Butadiene]], [[butane]], crude [[benzene]], ethane/propane mix, [[ethylene]], [[fuel oil]], [[High-density polyethylene|HDPE]], mixed [[butene]]s, other bottoms liquids, [[polypropylene]], [[propane]], and propylene</small>\n|-\n| <small>Oligomers</small>||<small>[[diisobutylene|DIB]], the [[dimer (chemistry)|dimer]] of [[isobutylene]] (isoolefins/isoparafins), IA (isoamylene/TAME), [[linear alpha olefin]]s, [[Polyalpha-olefins|poly alpha olefins]], [[Butyl rubber|polyisobutene]], Technikum (cyclopentane, CP70, methylpropadiene)</small>\n|-\n| <small>Oxide</small>||<small>[[Acetate]], acetate esters, alkoxilates, alkoxylates, ENB & [[glycol ethers]], [[ethanolamine|EOA]]s, [[ethyl acetate]], [[ethylene glycol]], [[ethylene oxide]], glycol ethers, [[oxo alcohols]], [[propylene glycol]], and [[propylene oxide]]</small>\n|-\n| <small>Paraform *</small>||<small>[[Cyanate]]s, [[dimethoxymethane]], [[formaldehyde]], [[hexamethylenetetramine]], [[paraformaldehyde]], and triallylcyanurate</small>\n|-\n| <small>Phenol</small>||<small>[[Acetone]], [[alpha-methylstyrene]] (AMS), [[cumene]] and [[phenol]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Salt *</small>\n|<small>Granular salt, pure dried vacuum salt, salt tablets, and undried vacuum salt</small>\n|-\n|<small>Solvents *</small>\n|<small>[[Diisopropyl ether]], [[ethanol]], [[isopropyl alcohol]], [[methyl ethyl ketone]], and [[2-Butanol|''s''-butyl alcohol]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Styrolution</small>\n|<small>ABS, AMSAN, ASA Resin, compounded grades, [[ethylbenzene]], general purpose polystyrene, high impact polystyrene, NAS, polyethylbenzene, polystyrene polymers - HIPS,  SAN, SBC (StyroFlex), specialty compounding, [[styrene]], and [[styrene monomer]]</small>\n|-\n|<small>Sulphur Chemicals *</small>\n|<small>[[Sulfur dioxide]], [[sulfur trioxide]], [[sulfuric acid]], and ultra pure acid</small>\n|-\n| <small>Technologies</small> || <small>Licenses world class petrochemical technology for: [[polyethylene]], [[polystyrene]], [[vinyls]], [[polypropylene]], [[acrylonitrile]], chlor-alkali</small>\n|-\n|<small>Trading and Shipping</small>\n|<small>Trades and supplies petrochemical [[feedstock]]s, [[hydrocarbon]]s, [[energy]] and [[carbon credit]]s for both internal and external customers</small>\n|-\n|<small>Upsteam Shale</small>\n|<small>[[Natural gas]], exploration and production of natural gas from on-shore shale deposits. Produces UK gas on the national grid.</small>\n|-\n|<small>Upstream Breagh</small>\n|<small>Supplies [[natural gas]] to one in ten UK households.</small>\n|}\n\n''<small>*Ineos Enterprises consists of the following sub-businesses: ammonia/nitric acid, Baleycourt, chlorotoluenes, compounds, ethanol, melamines, paraform, salt, solvents and sulphur chemicals.</small>''\n\n==Industrial relations controversy==\n===2008===\nIn April 2008 Ineos, which was experiencing adverse economic conditions, was at the centre of an [[industrial relations]] dispute with [[Unite the Union|Unite]] over pension entitlements of the workforce at its [[Grangemouth Refinery]], when the company decided to close the final salary [[pension]] scheme to new employees. Unite claimed the Grangemouth workers were paid \u00a36,000 less than those at comparable facilities.<ref name=obs270408/> The 48-hour strike that followed caused panic buying of petrol throughout the country and the Forties production pipeline, a third of Britain's North Sea oil production, being closed.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\">Sunday Herald 28 July 2013 [http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/political-news/trade-union-threatens-to-shut-scotlands-only-oil-refinery-over-staff-suspension.21710944 Trade union threatened to shut Grangemouth refinery over Falkirk chairman's suspension]</ref> Ineos has been accused by some of buying assets then cutting costs through the introduction of new working practices, lower wages, and terminating pension schemes.<ref name=obs270408>{{cite news   | last = Doward  | first = Jamie  |author2=Gaby Hinsliff |author3=Denis Campbell   | title = Drivers are told not to panic buy as strike at oil refinery starts to bite  | work = [[The Observer]]  | page = 5  | language =   | publisher =   | date = 27 April 2008  | url =   | accessdate = }}</ref> According to Ratcliffe, some 65 per cent of salary costs at Grangemouth related to pensions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usgreentechnology.com/us-green-stories/ineos-financing-on-bioenergy-plant-will-create-almost-400-jobs/ |title=INEOS Financing on Bioenergy Plant Will Create Almost 400 Jobs |publisher=U.S. Green Technology |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref><ref>Telegraph, Sep 2013, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/10292664/Britain-is-not-an-attractive-place-to-manufacture-says-Ineos-chief-Jim-Ratcliffe.html Britain is not an attractive place to manufacture, says Ineos chief Jim Ratcliffe]</ref>\n\n===2013===\nStephen Deans, convener for Unite union at the Grangemouth plant where he worked, and also head of the Falkirk branch of the Labour party, was suspended from his employment at Grangemouth by Ineos in the summer of 2013, while they investigated what they said were accusations he had been using company resources for political campaigning; related to recruitment of Unite members in Ineos workforce to the local Labour branch, where the selection of a new parliamentary candidate was taking place after the de-selection of [[Eric Joyce]]. A Labour Party head office investigation into allegations that people had been made new members without them knowing or signing cleared Deans of the accusations, who had been suspended from the Labour party pending the investigation as well as the Unite candidate he was supporting.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\"/><ref>BBC news Sept 2013 [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24006702 Falkirk row: Unite union vindicated, says Len McCluskey]</ref><ref>Sky News [http://news.sky.com/story/1138181/labour-falkirk-candidate-karie-murphy-quits Labour: Falkirk Candidate Karie Murphy Quits]</ref><ref name=\"ft.com\">FT politic and Policy, [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5406b854-3ca9-11e3-a8c4-00144feab7de.html#axzz2ijxMBhQ7 Old wound threatens to reopen at Grangemouth]</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">BBC News business, 23 October 2013, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24640133 Grangemouth dispute: The key players]</ref>\n\nUnite said Deans was being subjected to \"sinister\" treatment, and in October an overtime ban at Grangemouth plant, which according to Ineos had operated at a loss of \u00a3150 million per year for the previous four years, started in protest.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\"/><ref name=\"ft.com\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>Friday 24 October 2013,[http://www.scotsman.com/news/grangemouth-how-downfall-began-with-bar-room-brawl-1-3153945 Grangemouth: How downfall began with bar-room brawl]</ref> A 48-hour strike was set for 20 October. Ineos announced the plant would be shut down before the strike and put forward a new deal direct to the workforce, warning that the plant might close permanently if it was rejected.  Two-thirds of workers voted against accepting Ineos's proposal, which would have reduced pension, shift pay and redundancy entitlements in addition to a pay freeze. On 23 October Ineos announced the permanent closure of the petrochemical site at Grangemouth.<ref>''Telegraph'', 23 Oct 2013, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/10398888/Grange mouth-timeline-of-the-dispute.html Grangemouth: timeline of the dispute]</ref> The next day the Unite union reversed its position and agreed to Ineos's proposals, which included an undertaking not to strike for three years.<ref>BBC News, 24 October 2013 [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-24647843 Grangemouth dispute: Hopes rise after Unite accepts survival plan]</ref> Deans resigned from his job at Grangemouth on 28 October 2013 after Ineos presented its findings to his team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/28/grangemouth-unite-official-quits|title=Grangemouth Unite official quits before he gets the boot|first1=Sean|last1=Farrell|first2=Rajeev|last2=Syal|date=28 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>The Courier..com uk,28 October 2013, [http://www.thecourier.co.uk/news/scotland/unite-official-stevie-deans-resigns-from-grangemouth-role-1.146625 Unite official Stevie Deans resigns from Grangemouth role] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031015212/http://www.thecourier.co.uk/news/scotland/unite-official-stevie-deans-resigns-from-grangemouth-role-1.146625 |date=31 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>28 October 2013, Scottish Television News</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn March 2016, Ineos's [[Port of Runcorn]] ChlorVinyls facility was found guilty of releasing [[caustic soda]] into the [[Manchester Ship Canal]]. The company was ordered to pay a fine of \u00a3166,650.<ref name=\"echo\">{{cite web|title=Runcorn chemical giant loses appeal over chemical spill fine|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/runcorn-chemical-giant-loses-appeal-10992836|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Ineos applied for a test core drilling for [[shale gas]] at [[Woodsetts]] (United Kingdom). It was met by protests of residents.<ref>[https://drillordrop.com/2019/06/11/live-news-updates-day-1-of-inquiry-into-ineos-shale-gas-plans-at-woodsetts/ Shale gas opponents protest outside inquiry at Ineos drilling plans]</ref><ref>[https://www.ineos.com/businesses/ineos-shale/news/ineos-shale-disappointed-by-councils-decision-on-woodsetts/ INEOS Shale disappointed by council's decision on Woodsetts]</ref> New plans for drilling at Woodsetts and Harthill had been applied and eventually approved by the Planning Inspectorate.<ref>[https://www.woodsettsagainstfracking.co.uk/single-post/2018/06/07/New-INEOS-plans-for-Woodsetts-and-Harthill-drilling-approved New INEOS plans for Woodsetts and Harthill drilling approved]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Shale gas in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://ineos.com}}\n{{Commons category|INEOS}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n[[Category:Chemical companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Ineos]]\n[[Category:Petrochemical companies]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ineos"}
{"title_page": "Logan Marshall-Green", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor and director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Logan Marshall-Green\n| image              = Logan Marshall Green (7448966622) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Marshall-Green in 2012\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1976|11|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Charleston, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| education   = [[University of Tennessee, Knoxville]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br />[[Tisch School of the Arts|New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| occupation  = {{flatlist|\n* Actor\n* filmmaker}}\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Diane Gaeta|December 12, 2012|2019|end={{abbr|sep.|separated}}}}\n| children           = 2\n| yearsactive        = 2003\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Logan Marshall-Green''' (born November 1, 1976) is an American actor and director. He is known for his roles in the television series ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'', ''[[The O.C.]]'', ''[[Traveler (TV series)|Traveler]]'', ''[[Dark Blue (TV series)|Dark Blue]]'' and ''[[Quarry (TV series)|Quarry]]'', as well as his roles in the films ''[[Prometheus (2012 film)|Prometheus]]'', ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]'' and ''[[Upgrade (film)|Upgrade]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nMarshall-Green was born in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], to teacher parents. He was raised by his mother, Lowry Marshall, in [[Cranston, Rhode Island]], while she taught theatre at [[Brown University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatermania.com/new-york/news/rising-stars_6282.html|title=Rising Stars|website=theatermania.com|first=Michael|last=Portantiere|date=July 7, 2005}}</ref> He has a twin brother named Taylor. They both attended [[Barrington High School (Barrington, Rhode Island)|Barrington High School]] in the early 1990s. He did his undergraduate studies at the [[University of Tennessee, Knoxville]], where he also wrote for the school newspaper, ''[[The Daily Beacon]]'', as an entertainment writer covering the bar, music, and theater scene.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nHe attended the [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center#National Theater Institute|National Theater Institute]] in [[Waterford, Connecticut]], and then went on to earn his Master's in Fine Arts from [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts#Graduate Acting Program|Graduate Acting Program]] at the [[Tisch School of the Arts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gradacting.tisch.nyu.edu/object/ga_alumbios.html|title=NYU Graduate Acting Alumni|year=2011|accessdate=December 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMarshall-Green appeared in both ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' in 2003 and ''[[Law & Order]]'' in 2004, before landing recurring roles on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s ''[[The O.C.]]'' and ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatermania.com/content/news.cfm/story/6282|title=Theater News Interview|publisher=Theatermania.com|date=July 7, 2005|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMarshall-Green received a [[Drama Desk Award]] for his performance in [[Neil LaBute]]'s play ''The Distance from Here'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dramadesk.org/awards?field_nomination_year_value%5Bvalue%5D%5Byear%5D=2004&field_nominee_full_name_value=&field_show_value=&field_award_value=All|title=Nominees and Recipients - Drama Desk - 2004|work=Drama Desk|accessdate=October 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 he performed in three separate productions: in June he played an anthropomorphic shark in Adam Bock's ''Swimming in the Shallows''; in August he appeared as Bo Decker in a production of [[William Inge]]'s classic ''[[Bus Stop (play)|Bus Stop]]''; and in December he was Beethoven in the [[Peanuts]] spoof ''[[Dog Sees God: Confessions of a Teenage Blockhead]]'' (for which he received a [[Lucille Lortel Award]] for Outstanding Featured Actor nomination).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatermania.com/content/news.cfm/story/6260|title=Theater News Review of '&#39;Swimming in the Shallows'&#39;|publisher=Theatermania.com|date=June 29, 2005|accessdate=June 11, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081025075847/http://www.theatermania.com/content/news.cfm/story/6260|archive-date=October 25, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>https://www.lortelaward.com/2006-nominees</ref>\n\nHe played the villainous [[Edmund (King Lear)|Edmund]] in the [[Public Theater]] production of ''[[King Lear]]'' starring [[Kevin Kline]] in the title role and directed by [[James Lapine]]. For his performance in ''King Lear'' and ''Pig Farm'',<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/28/theater/reviews/28pig.html</ref> he was nominated for a [[Drama League Award]] for Distinguished Performance.<ref>https://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/2007-drama-league-award-winners-announced_10744.html</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Marshall-Green appeared in the film ''[[Alchemy (film)|Alchemy]]''. That same year he also appeared in the Miramax film ''[[The Great Raid]]''. Marshall-Green portrayed Tyler Fog in the 2007 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] series ''[[Traveler (TV series)|Traveler]]''. He appeared as Paco in the 2007 film ''[[Across the Universe (film)|Across the Universe]]''. He featured as Dean Bendis, an undercover police officer, in a [[black ops]] group of the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]] headed by [[Dylan McDermott]] in the TNT series ''[[Dark Blue (TV series)|Dark Blue]]''. He played a young rookie cop the 2010 criminal drama ''[[Brooklyn's Finest]]'' directed by [[Antoine Fuqua]], and had a lead role in the horror film ''[[Devil (2010 film)|Devil]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/38512/universal-debuts-one-devil-a-trailer|title=Universal Debuts One Devil of a Trailer|publisher=Dreadcentral.com|date=July 13, 2010|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in the 2012 [[Ridley Scott]] film ''[[Prometheus (2012 film)|Prometheus]]'' as Holloway, a crew member aboard Prometheus.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prometheus Movie Image|url=http://collider.com/wp-content/uploads/prometheus-movie-image1.jpg}}</ref> He also portrayed Will in [[Karyn Kusama]]'s 2015 horror-thriller ''[[The Invitation (2015 film)|The Invitation]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/sxsw-15-exclusive-photos-from-karyn-kusamas-the-invitation|title=The Invitation|magazine=Fangoria|date=March 10, 2015|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Marshall-Green starred as the lead in [[Leigh Whannell]] and [[Blumhouse Productions|Blumhouse]]'s science fiction [[body horror]] film ''[[Upgrade (film)|Upgrade]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/prometheus-star-logan-marshall-green-stem-1201943796/|title=\u2018Prometheus\u2019 Actor Logan Marshall-Green to Star in Sci-Fi Movie \u2018Stem\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=December 15, 2016|accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMarshall-Green made his directorial debut with the drama film ''[[Adopt a Highway (film)|Adopt a Highway]]'', which was released in March 2019. The film starred [[Ethan Hawke]] and [[Betty Gabriel]], and was produced by [[Jason Blum]] through Blumhouse Productions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/adopt-a-highway-review-1203160864/|title=SXSW Film Review: \u2018Adopt a Highway\u2019|last=Harvey|first=Dennis|last2=Harvey|first2=Dennis|date=2019-03-12|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> The actor appeared in an episode of ''[[When They See Us]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/05/you-cannot-look-away-from-when-they-see-us.html|title=You Cannot Look Away from the Masterful When They See Us|website=pastemagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> and starred in the video game ''[[Telling Lies (video game)|Telling Lies]]'', which was released in August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/08/16/narrative-title-telling-lies-releases-later-this-month|title=Narrative Title Telling Lies Releases Later This Month|last=Khan|first=Imran|website=Game Informer|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBetween 2008 and 2012, Marshall-Green was in a relationship with actress [[Marisa Tomei]]. They were rumored to be engaged, but a representative for Tomei denied this.<ref name=logan>{{cite web|last2=Bromley|first2=Melanie|last1=Finn|first1=Natalie|title=Marisa Tomei Not Engaged to Prometheus Hunk Logan Marshall-Green|date=24 January 2013|publisher=[[E!]]|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/381608/marisa-tomei-not-engaged-to-prometheus-hunk-logan-marshall-green|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe married actress Diane Gaeta in 2012.<ref name=\"Divorce\">{{cite magazine|url=https://people.com/tv/logan-marshall-green-wife-diane-gaeta-announces-divorce/|title=The O.C. Star Logan Marshall Green's Wife Denounces 'Cheating,' Announces She's Divorcing Him|magazine=People|first=Helen|last=Murphy|date=April 6, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref> The couple has a son (born 2014).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/ca/news/531567/logan-marshall-green-welcomes-baby-boy-tennessee-see-pics-of-his-newborn-son|title=Logan Marshall-Green Welcomes Baby Boy Tennessee\u2014See Pics of His Newborn Son!|publisher=eonline.com|date=April 14, 2014|accessdate=September 26, 2016}}</ref> Marshall-Green is also a stepfather to his wife's daughter (born 2010), whose father was actor [[Johnny Lewis]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.lamag.com/longform/the-secret-life-of-johnny-lewis/|title=The Secret Life of Johnny Lewis|date=January 30, 2014|magazine=[[Los Angeles (magazine)|Los Angeles]]|accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> Gaeta filed for divorce from Marshall-Green on April 5, 2019.<ref name=\"Divorce\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''{{sortname|The|Kindness of Strangers|nolink=1}}''\n| Ray\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Alchemy (film)|Alchemy]]''\n| Martin\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''{{sortname|The|Great Raid}}''\n| Lt. Paul Colvin\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Across the Universe (film)|Across the Universe]]''\n| Paco\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Brooklyn's Finest]]''\n| Melvin Panton\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Devil (2010 film)|Devil]]''\n| Mechanic (Anthony \"Tony\" Janekowski)\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Prometheus (2012 film)|Prometheus]]''\n| Charlie Holloway \n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[As I Lay Dying (film)|As I Lay Dying]]''\n| Jewel\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Cold Comes the Night]]''\n| Billy\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Madame Bovary (2014 film)|Madame Bovary]]''\n| The Marquis\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''{{sortname|The|Invitation|dab=2015 film}}''\n| Will\n| Nominated {{ndash}} [[Fangoria Chainsaw Award for Best Actor]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Never mind Oscar, here\u2019s the 2017 FANGORIA Chainsaw Awards Nominees Ballot!|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/never-mind-oscar-heres-the-2017-fangoria-chainsaw-awards-nominees-ballot/|website=FANGORIA\u00ae|accessdate=February 14, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Snowden (film)|Snowden]]''\n| Male Drone Pilot\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Black Dog, Red Dog''\n| Stephen\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Sand Castle (film)|Sand Castle]]''\n| Sergeant Harper\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''\n| [[Montana (comics)|Jackson Brice / Shocker #1]]\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Upgrade (film)|Upgrade]]''\n|Grey Trace\n|Nominated {{ndash}} [[Fangoria Chainsaw Award for Best Actor]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/01/22/fangoria-chainsaw-awards/ |title=Halloween, Hereditary, and A Quiet Place nominated for Best Movie...at Fangoria Awards |last=Collis |first=Clark |date=January 22, 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Adopt a Highway (film)|Adopt a Highway]]''\n|\n|Writer and director\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Mitch Wilkens, aka Max Van Horn\n| Episode: \"[[Soulless (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|Soulless]]\"\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Law & Order]]''\n| Kyle Mellors\n| Episode: \"Evil Breeds\"\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]''\n| [[List of minor characters in 24#24: Season 4 3|Richard Heller]]\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''{{sortname|The|O.C.}}''\n| [[Trey Atwood]]\n| 9 episodes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Traveler (TV series)|Traveler]]''\n| Tyler Fog\n| Main cast; 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\u201310\n| ''[[Dark Blue (TV series)|Dark Blue]]''\n| Dean Bendis\n| Main cast; 20 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Quarry (TV series)|Quarry]]''\n| Mac Conway\n| Main cast; 8 episodes\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|''[[Damnation (TV series)|Damnation]]''\n|Creeley Turner\n|Main role; 10 episodes\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[When They See Us]]''\n|Roberts\n|Miniseries; Episode: \"Part Four\"\n|}\n\n===Other media===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2019\n|[[Telling Lies (video game)|''Telling Lies'']]\n|David Smith\n|Won \u2013 [[Golden Joystick Award]] for Best Performer<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesradar.com/Golden-Joystick-awards-2019-winners/ | title = Here's every winner from this year's Golden Joystick Awards, including the Ultimate Game of the Year | author = GamesRadar staff | date = 15 November 2019 | accessdate = 16 November 2019 | work = [[GamesRadar+]]}}</ref><br>Nominated \u2013 New York Game Award for Best Acting in a Game<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bleedingcool.com/2020/01/02/the-new-york-game-awards-announces-2020-nominees/ | title = The New York Game Awards Announces 2020 Nominees | first = Gavin | last = Sheehan | date = 2 January 2020 | accessdate = 4 January 2020 | work = [[Bleeding Cool]]}}</ref><br>Nominated \u2013 [[NAVGTR Award]] for Performance in a Drama, Lead<ref>{{cite web | url = https://navgtr.org/2019-nominees/ | title = 2019 Nominees | date = January 13, 2020 | accessdate = January 22, 2020 | work = [[NAVGTR Awards|National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]]}}</ref><br>Nominated \u2013 [[British Academy Games Award for Performer|British Academy Games Award for Performer in a Leading Role]]<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/2020-bafta-games-awards-full-list-nominees-1282264</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1334869}}\n* {{iobdb name|24439}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marshall-Green, Logan}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:People from Barrington, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Cranston, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n[[Category:University of Tennessee alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor and director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Logan Marshall-Green\n| image              = Logan Marshall Green (7448966622) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Marshall-Green in 2012\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1976|11|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Charleston, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| education   = [[University of Tennessee, Knoxville]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br />[[Tisch School of the Arts|New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| occupation  = {{flatlist|\n* Actor\n* filmmaker}}\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Diane Gaeta|December 12, 2012|2019|end={{abbr|sep.|separated}}}}\n| children           = 2\n| yearsactive        = 2003\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Logan Marshall-Green''' (born November 1, 1976) is an American actor and director. He is known for his roles in the television series ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'', ''[[The O.C.]]'', ''[[Traveler (TV series)|Traveler]]'', ''[[Dark Blue (TV series)|Dark Blue]]'' and ''[[Quarry (TV series)|Quarry]]'', as well as his roles in the films ''[[Prometheus (2012 film)|Prometheus]]'', ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]'' and ''[[Upgrade (film)|Upgrade]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nMarshall-Green was born in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], to teacher parents. He was raised by his mother, Lowry Marshall, in [[Cranston, Rhode Island]], while she taught theatre at [[Brown University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatermania.com/new-york/news/rising-stars_6282.html|title=Rising Stars|website=theatermania.com|first=Michael|last=Portantiere|date=July 7, 2005}}</ref> He has a twin brother named Taylor. They both attended [[Barrington High School (Barrington, Rhode Island)|Barrington High School]] in the early 1990s. He did his undergraduate studies at the [[University of Tennessee, Knoxville]], where he also wrote for the school newspaper, ''[[The Daily Beacon]]'', as an entertainment writer covering the bar, music, and theater scene.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nHe attended the [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center#National Theater Institute|National Theater Institute]] in [[Waterford, Connecticut]], and then went on to earn his Master's in Fine Arts from [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts#Graduate Acting Program|Graduate Acting Program]] at the [[Tisch School of the Arts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gradacting.tisch.nyu.edu/object/ga_alumbios.html|title=NYU Graduate Acting Alumni|year=2011|accessdate=December 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMarshall-Green appeared in both ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' in 2003 and ''[[Law & Order]]'' in 2004, before landing recurring roles on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s ''[[The O.C.]]'' and ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatermania.com/content/news.cfm/story/6282|title=Theater News Interview|publisher=Theatermania.com|date=July 7, 2005|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMarshall-Green received a [[Drama Desk Award]] for his performance in [[Neil LaBute]]'s play ''The Distance from Here'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dramadesk.org/awards?field_nomination_year_value%5Bvalue%5D%5Byear%5D=2004&field_nominee_full_name_value=&field_show_value=&field_award_value=All|title=Nominees and Recipients - Drama Desk - 2004|work=Drama Desk|accessdate=October 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 he performed in three separate productions: in June he played an anthropomorphic shark in Adam Bock's ''Swimming in the Shallows''; in August he appeared as Bo Decker in a production of [[William Inge]]'s classic ''[[Bus Stop (play)|Bus Stop]]''; and in December he was Beethoven in the [[Peanuts]] spoof ''[[Dog Sees God: Confessions of a Teenage Blockhead]]'' (for which he received a [[Lucille Lortel Award]] for Outstanding Featured Actor nomination).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatermania.com/content/news.cfm/story/6260|title=Theater News Review of '&#39;Swimming in the Shallows'&#39;|publisher=Theatermania.com|date=June 29, 2005|accessdate=June 11, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081025075847/http://www.theatermania.com/content/news.cfm/story/6260|archive-date=October 25, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>https://www.lortelaward.com/2006-nominees</ref>\n\nHe played the villainous [[Edmund (King Lear)|Edmund]] in the [[Public Theater]] production of ''[[King Lear]]'' starring [[Kevin Kline]] in the title role and directed by [[James Lapine]]. For his performance in ''King Lear'' and ''Pig Farm'',<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/28/theater/reviews/28pig.html</ref> he was nominated for a [[Drama League Award]] for Distinguished Performance.<ref>https://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/2007-drama-league-award-winners-announced_10744.html</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Marshall-Green appeared in the film ''[[Alchemy (film)|Alchemy]]''. That same year he also appeared in the Miramax film ''[[The Great Raid]]''. Marshall-Green portrayed Tyler Fog in the 2007 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] series ''[[Traveler (TV series)|Traveler]]''. He appeared as Paco in the 2007 film ''[[Across the Universe (film)|Across the Universe]]''. He featured as Dean Bendis, an undercover police officer, in a [[black ops]] group of the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]] headed by [[Dylan McDermott]] in the TNT series ''[[Dark Blue (TV series)|Dark Blue]]''. He played a young rookie cop the 2010 criminal drama ''[[Brooklyn's Finest]]'' directed by [[Antoine Fuqua]], and had a lead role in the horror film ''[[Devil (2010 film)|Devil]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/38512/universal-debuts-one-devil-a-trailer|title=Universal Debuts One Devil of a Trailer|publisher=Dreadcentral.com|date=July 13, 2010|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in the 2012 [[Ridley Scott]] film ''[[Prometheus (2012 film)|Prometheus]]'' as Holloway, a crew member aboard Prometheus.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prometheus Movie Image|url=http://collider.com/wp-content/uploads/prometheus-movie-image1.jpg}}</ref> He also portrayed Will in [[Karyn Kusama]]'s 2015 horror-thriller ''[[The Invitation (2015 film)|The Invitation]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/sxsw-15-exclusive-photos-from-karyn-kusamas-the-invitation|title=The Invitation|magazine=Fangoria|date=March 10, 2015|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Marshall-Green starred as the lead in [[Leigh Whannell]] and [[Blumhouse Productions|Blumhouse]]'s science fiction [[body horror]] film ''[[Upgrade (film)|Upgrade]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/prometheus-star-logan-marshall-green-stem-1201943796/|title=\u2018Prometheus\u2019 Actor Logan Marshall-Green to Star in Sci-Fi Movie \u2018Stem\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=December 15, 2016|accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMarshall-Green made his directorial debut with the drama film ''[[Adopt a Highway (film)|Adopt a Highway]]'', which was released in March 2019. The film starred [[Ethan Hawke]] and [[Betty Gabriel]], and was produced by [[Jason Blum]] through Blumhouse Productions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/adopt-a-highway-review-1203160864/|title=SXSW Film Review: \u2018Adopt a Highway\u2019|last=Harvey|first=Dennis|last2=Harvey|first2=Dennis|date=2019-03-12|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> The actor appeared in an episode of ''[[When They See Us]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/05/you-cannot-look-away-from-when-they-see-us.html|title=You Cannot Look Away from the Masterful When They See Us|website=pastemagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> and starred in the video game ''[[Telling Lies (video game)|Telling Lies]]'', which was released in August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/08/16/narrative-title-telling-lies-releases-later-this-month|title=Narrative Title Telling Lies Releases Later This Month|last=Khan|first=Imran|website=Game Informer|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBetween 2008 and 2012, Marshall-Green was in a relationship with actress [[Marisa Tomei]]. They were rumored to be engaged, but a representative for Tomei denied this.<ref name=logan>{{cite web|last2=Bromley|first2=Melanie|last1=Finn|first1=Natalie|title=Marisa Tomei Not Engaged to Prometheus Hunk Logan Marshall-Green|date=24 January 2013|publisher=[[E!]]|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/381608/marisa-tomei-not-engaged-to-prometheus-hunk-logan-marshall-green|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe married actress Diane Gaeta in 2012.<ref name=\"Divorce\">{{cite magazine|url=https://people.com/tv/logan-marshall-green-wife-diane-gaeta-announces-divorce/|title=The O.C. Star Logan Marshall Green's Wife Denounces 'Cheating,' Announces She's Divorcing Him|magazine=People|first=Helen|last=Murphy|date=April 6, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref> The couple has a son (born 2014).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/ca/news/531567/logan-marshall-green-welcomes-baby-boy-tennessee-see-pics-of-his-newborn-son|title=Logan Marshall-Green Welcomes Baby Boy Tennessee\u2014See Pics of His Newborn Son!|publisher=eonline.com|date=April 14, 2014|accessdate=September 26, 2016}}</ref> Marshall-Green is also a stepfather to his wife's daughter (born 2010), whose father was actor [[Johnny Lewis]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.lamag.com/longform/the-secret-life-of-johnny-lewis/|title=The Secret Life of Johnny Lewis|date=January 30, 2014|magazine=[[Los Angeles (magazine)|Los Angeles]]|accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> Gaeta filed for divorce from Marshall-Green on April 5, 2019.<ref name=\"Divorce\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''{{sortname|The|Kindness of Strangers|nolink=1}}''\n| Ray\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Alchemy (film)|Alchemy]]''\n| Martin\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''{{sortname|The|Great Raid}}''\n| Lt. Paul Colvin\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Across the Universe (film)|Across the Universe]]''\n| Paco\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Brooklyn's Finest]]''\n| Melvin Panton\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Devil (2010 film)|Devil]]''\n| Mechanic (Anthony \"Tony\" Janekowski)\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Prometheus (2012 film)|Prometheus]]''\n| Charlie Holloway \n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[As I Lay Dying (film)|As I Lay Dying]]''\n| Jewel\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Cold Comes the Night]]''\n| Billy\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Madame Bovary (2014 film)|Madame Bovary]]''\n| The Marquis\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''{{sortname|The|Invitation|dab=2015 film}}''\n| Will\n| Nominated {{ndash}} [[Fangoria Chainsaw Award for Best Actor]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Never mind Oscar, here\u2019s the 2017 FANGORIA Chainsaw Awards Nominees Ballot!|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/never-mind-oscar-heres-the-2017-fangoria-chainsaw-awards-nominees-ballot/|website=FANGORIA\u00ae|accessdate=February 14, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Snowden (film)|Snowden]]''\n| Male Drone Pilot\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Black Dog, Red Dog''\n| Stephen\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Sand Castle (film)|Sand Castle]]''\n| Sergeant Harper\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''\n| [[Montana (comics)|Jackson Brice / Shocker #1]]\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Upgrade (film)|Upgrade]]''\n|Grey Trace\n|Nominated {{ndash}} [[Fangoria Chainsaw Award for Best Actor]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/01/22/fangoria-chainsaw-awards/ |title=Halloween, Hereditary, and A Quiet Place nominated for Best Movie...at Fangoria Awards |last=Collis |first=Clark |date=January 22, 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Adopt a Highway (film)|Adopt a Highway]]''\n|\n|Writer and director\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Mitch Wilkens, aka Max Van Horn\n| Episode: \"[[Soulless (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|Soulless]]\"\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Law & Order]]''\n| Kyle Mellors\n| Episode: \"Evil Breeds\"\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]''\n| [[List of minor characters in 24#24: Season 4 3|Richard Heller]]\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''{{sortname|The|O.C.}}''\n| [[Trey Atwood]]\n| 9 episodes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Traveler (TV series)|Traveler]]''\n| Tyler Fog\n| Main cast; 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\u201310\n| ''[[Dark Blue (TV series)|Dark Blue]]''\n| Dean Bendis\n| Main cast; 20 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Quarry (TV series)|Quarry]]''\n| Mac Conway\n| Main cast; 8 episodes\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|''[[Damnation (TV series)|Damnation]]''\n|Creeley Turner\n|Main role; 10 episodes\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[When They See Us]]''\n|Roberts\n|Miniseries; Episode: \"Part Four\"\n|}\n\n===Other media===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2019\