{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of the viral pandemic in Tamil Nadu, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n| image           = Corona Lockdown Tirupur, Tamil Nadu (2).jpg\n| width           = \n| caption         = Empty store shelves in [[Tiruppur]] due to panic buying prior to lockdown\n| map1            = TN COVID-19 cases in districts.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 2 April)\n{{legend|#d45500ff|30+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ff9955ff|10\u201329 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffe6d5ff|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Chennai]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 309<ref name=\"TNHFW\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/index.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Home|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n| active_cases    = 302<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 6<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| deaths          = 1<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| territories     = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#District-wise cases|26 districts]] including [[Chennai district|Chennai]], [[Coimbatore district|Coimbatore]], [[Erode district|Erode]], [[Madurai district|Madurai]], [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]], [[Theni district|Theni]] and [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]]\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/}}\n| youtube         = \n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]] was confirmed on 7 March 2020. The state has confirmed a total of 309 cases, including 1 death and 6 recoveries, as of 2 April 2020.<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n\n264 (85%) of all reported cases were from one cluster linked to an Islamic religious congregation event ''Tablighi Jamaat'' that took place in [[Delhi]].<ref name=\"MB_april02\">{{cite web |title=Media Bulletin April 02 |url=http://www.stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_02_04_20_COVID_19_6_PM.pdf |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-covid-19-count-jumps-by-110-in-1-day/articleshow/74940428.cms|title=Coronavirus in Tamil Nadu: Tamil Nadu Covid-19 count jumps by 110 in 1 day {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|last2=Menon|first2=Jaya|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=N|first3=Durgesh|last4=Apr 2|first4=an Jha {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last5=2020|last6=Ist|first6=10:28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulte.com/news/83733/More-Than-330-Cases-Linked-to-Delhi-Mosque|title=More Than 330 Cases Linked to Delhi Mosque|last=13|date=2020-04-02|website=Gulte|language=english|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The state government has created containment zones in 16 affected districts to screen residents for checking community spread and to prevent more infections.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|title=Tamil Nadu Prepares for Stage Two of Coronavirus Outbreak With More Home Quarantines, Surveillance|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329134259/https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"containmentDH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-74-nizamuddin-link-to-a-chunk-of-it-surfaces-819633.html|title=Tamil Nadu coronavirus cases rises to 74, Nizamuddin link to a chunk of it surfaces|date=2020-03-31|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== March ===\nThe first case of coronavirus was confirmed on 7 March in a resident from [[Kanchipuram]] in [[Chennai]]. He had returned from [[Oman]] and started developing symptoms including fever and cough.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-patient-quarantined-in-government-hospital-in-chennai/articleshow/74529929.cms?from=mdr|title=Tamil Nadu reports first case of Coronavirus; patient quarantined in Chennai Government Hospital|date=2020-03-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He was isolated in [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]. Later, on 10 March, he recovered and tested negative.<ref name=\"TNrecovered\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-no-fresh-covid-19-cases-in-tamil-nadu-812479.html?utm_campaign=fullarticle&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=inshorts|title=Coronavirus: No fresh COVID-19 cases in Tamil Nadu|date=10 March 2020|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a week without new cases, on 18 March, the second person who had travelled by train from Delhi to Chennai confirmed positive. He did not have any history of foreign travel and was described as a domestic case by the state health minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Nadu's 2nd Coronavirus patient raises community transmission fears|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319193205/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a 21-year-old student who returned from [[Ireland]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|title=Coronavirus LIVE: India's death toll rises to four|website=Business Standard|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319161417/https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a further three were confirmed positive - A Chennai man who had travelled from [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|title=Three more COVID-19 cases in State, one with no travel history|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324184127/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and two [[Thailand]] nationals in [[Erode]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-17-fresh-coronavirus-cases-tally-now-67-819262.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 17 fresh coronavirus cases; tally now 67|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> They were admitted to IRT Hospital in Perundurai in Erode. More than 300 people who had come in contact with the three patients were quarantined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-7th-positive-coronavirus-case-816543.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 7th positive coronavirus case|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first virus-related death in the state was reported after a 54-year-old man in [[Madurai]] died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf : 54 \u0bb5\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd {{!}} Patrikai - Tamil Daily - latest online local breaking news & reviews - Tamilnadu, India & World - politics, cinema, cricket, video & cartoon|date=2020-03-25|website=Tamil News patrikai {{!}} Tamil news online {{!}} latest tamil news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328044912/https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Five others were infected - four Indonesians and their travel guide from Chennai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-tally-goes-up-to-23/articleshow/74810591.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports five new coronavirus cases; tally goes up to 23|author=|newspaper=Economic Times|date = 26 March 2020}}</ref> The five were in quarantine since 22 March in Salem Medical College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-reports-5-new-cases-covid-19-includes-4-indonesian-travellers-and-1-chennai-man-121103|title=TN reports 5 new cases of COVID-19, includes 4 Indonesian travellers and 1 Chennai man|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a 21-year-old youth who had just returned from a trip to [[Dublin]], Ireland was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-positive-tamil-nadu-man-with-travel-history-to-ireland-recovers-120032800122_1.html|title=Covid-19 positive Tamil Nadu man with travel history to Ireland recovers|author=|date=28 March 2020|newspaper=Business Standard India|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new cases - one each in [[Kumbakonam]] and [[Katpadi]] were reported. With this, the total number of confirmed cases had reached 40 in the state.<ref name=\"28Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328125841/https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the state reported eight more cases (four each from Coimbatore and Erode), all of which were linked to the two [[Thailand|Thai]] nationals and their group who had tested positive. The eight included a 10-month-old baby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|title=10-month-old baby and 7 more test positive for COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu; state's tally rises to 50|date=29 March 2020|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329142751/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|archive-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases reached 50.<ref name=\"29Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070556/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, 17 new cases were reported, highest till date in the state<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> - 10 male patients from [[Erode]], all of whom have travelled to Delhi were in contact with the Thailand tourists, 5 in Chennai and 1 each in [[Karur]] and [[Madurai]].<ref name=\"30MarchBulletinOld\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, 57 new cases were reported, all with a history of travel predominately to [[Delhi]], bringing the total to 124.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-reports-57-new-covid-19-cases-in-one-day-79-attended-tablighi-jamaat-state-tally-at-124-1661904-2020-03-31|title=Tamil Nadu reports 57 new Covid-19 cases in one day, 79% attended Tablighi Jamaat. State tally at 124|date=|work=India Today|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the highest single day rise till date. 50 of these cases were from [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]] (18), [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] (22), [[Kanyakumari district|Kanyakumari]] (4) [[Viluppuram|Villupuram]] (3), [[Madurai district|Madurai]] (2) and [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]] (1), all had travel history to Delhi.<ref name=\"31MarBulletin2\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070737/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Officials had discovered that at least 80 out of 124 confirmed cases (79 per cent) in Tamil Nadu were from one cluster as they are direct or indirect contact of the two Thai nationals who had tested positive for on 21 March.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /><ref name=\"Hindu-31March\" /> The Thai nationals, identified as patients 5 and 6 were part of a large group from countries including [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], etc. who had visited the state for an annual pilgrimage.<ref name=\"Hindu-31March\">{{Cite news|last=M|first=Serena Josephine|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|title=25 of 67 patients directly or indirectly linked to Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331163219/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This group had also attended a 3-day religious congregation event known as ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in [[New Delhi]] in early March.<ref name=\"March31-DH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-25-out-of-67-in-tamil-nadu-have-contact-or-travel-history-with-thai-nationals-819372.html|title=Coronavirus: 25 out of 67 in Tamil Nadu have contact or travel history with Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was estimated that more than 1,500 people from the state had participated in this event.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|title=Coimbatore, Erode Stare at Crisis as Tamil Nadu Govt Races to Trace Scores Back from Nizamuddin Event|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401020556/https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials also confirmed that the 54-year-old patient who had died the previous week had also participated in the gathering.  Of 1,500 people who were in the gathering, 1,130 had returned to the state. The government had identified and isolated 515 of the 1,130 people.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> It faced difficulty while trying to map the rest. It had urged people who attended the gathering to step forward and get tested.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Coronavirus update: Tamil Nadu reports 50 more Covid-19 cases {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mar 31|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=23:31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331211819/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nOn 1 April, the state reported 110 new cases, all attended the Delhi Nizamuddin event. The total became 234.<ref name=\"April1-IT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-new-coronavirus-cases-linked-nizamuddin-event-tabligh-1662243-2020-04-01|title=Tamil Nadu reports 110 new coronavirus cases, all linked to Nizamuddin event|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|title=110 more cases in Tamil Nadu on Wednesday, all attended Delhi Jamaat conference|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402005422/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|archive-date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Health Secretary Beela Rajesh said that 1103  out of 1500 attendees of the event had been traced and isolated. 658 of their samples had been tested of which,190 tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu witnesses steep rise in cases|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401210601/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some of the participants approached officials themselves after government's request.<ref name=\":2\" /> Family members and close contacts were either taken to quarantine facilities or home quarantined.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/special-containment-plan-for-tj-group/articleshow/74939483.cms|title=Tamil Nadu: Special containment plan for Tablighi Jamaat group {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=08:57}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 75 new cases were reported, of which 74 of them attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB_april02\"/>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe data below are based on Health and Family Welfare Department of Tamil Nadu daily reports.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases chart}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases}}\n\n== Testing ==\nAs of 31 March, the state had 17 laboratories (11 government and 6 private) to handle testing for the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|title=List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070313/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|title=Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070405/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Initially, it had four government labs.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|title=Why Kerala has done more coronavirus tests than Tamil Nadu \u2013 and why this must change|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328121533/https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n===Sample testing facilities===\n====Public====\n#[[King Institute of Preventive Medicine and Research|King Institute of Preventive Medicine & Research, Chennai]]\n#[[Madras Medical College|Madras Medical College, Chennai]]\n#[[Theni Medical College|Govt. Theni Medical College, Theni]]\n#[[Tirunelveli Medical College|Tirunelveli Medical College, Tirunelveli]]\n# Govt. Medical College, Thiruvarur\n# Kumar Mangalam Govt. Medical College, Salem\n#[[Coimbatore Medical College|Coimbatore Medical College, Coimbatore]]\n# Govt. Medical College, Villupuram\n#[[Madurai Medical College|Madurai Medical College, Madurai]]\n#[[K.A.P. Viswanatham Government Medical College|Govt. Medical College, Trichy]]\n#[[Stanley Medical College|Stanley Medical College, Chennai]] <sup>\u00a7</sup>\n\n====Private====\n#[[Christian Medical College & Hospital, Vellore|Dept. of Clinical Virology, CMC, Vellore.]]\n# Department of Laboratory Services, Apollo Hospitals Enterprise Ltd, Chennai \n# Neuberg  Ehrlich  Lab  Pvt  Ltd,  46-48  Masilamani  Road,  Balaji Nagar, Chennai \n#[[Sri Ramachandra Institute of Higher Education and Research|Sri Ramachandra Medical College & Research Institute, Porur, Chennai]]\n# Microbiology Lab, Veerakeralam Road, Coimbatore \n#[[YRG Care|YRG Care, Chennai]]\n\n<small>'''Note:''' \u00a7 Approved, but not supported by ICMR</small>\n\nThe government started screening passengers arriving at the airports in January. It had screened 2,10,538 passengers as of 1 April.\n\nDuring the first half of March, the state faced criticism for the low number of tests. By 16 March, it had only tested 90 samples while neighbouring Kerala and Karnataka had tested more than 1500 and 750 samples.<ref name=\"Testing-TOI\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|title=Coronavirus Tamil Nadu Updates: In Tamil Nadu, patients &amp; doctors call for increased tests on coronavirus {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=16 March 2020|agency=TNN|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321071302/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The director of Public Health defended the state's low number of tests saying that Kerala saw more travel from coronavirus-affected countries which is why it had detected more cases.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"/> The Public Health department has also said that the state follows test protocols established by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Health Ministry]].<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"/><ref name=\"Testing-TOI\" />\n\nIn order to test community transmission, as of 16 March, the state had tested 22 random samples of people with influenza and severe acute respiratory infection for coronavirus as per [[Indian Council of Medical Research|ICMR]] guidelines. All tested negative.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"/>\n\nFollowing the Delhi Nizamuddin event, authorities said that families of 1103 identified participants will be tested whether or not they show symptoms.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAs of 1 April, 2726 samples have been tested of which, 234 were positive.<ref name=\"TNHFW\" />\n\n== Containment measures ==\nStickers announcing that \"COVID-19/Do not Visit/Home under quarantine,\" were pasted on the doors of houses of foreign returnees to warn the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/27/54000-people-who-landed-from-overseas-to-be-home-quarantined-2122007.html|title=54,000 people who landed from overseas to be home quarantined|access-date=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401214313/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/27/54000-people-who-landed-from-overseas-to-be-home-quarantined-2122007.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Authorities had also marked their arms with home quarantine stamps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|title=Tamil Nadu goes under lockdown; home quarantine stickers pasted on doors of foreign returnees|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326175649/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Government launched a mobile application to allow people under home quarantine to interact healthcare professionals for getting medical advice and counselling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-launches-app-to-provide-advice-to-those-under-home-quarantine-816562.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu launches app to provide advice to those under home quarantine|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, government announced plans for creating containment zones to stop the community spread. The containment zones of 5&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> radius around the residences of infected across 16 districts were set up. It is ringed by an additional 3&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> buffer zone.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-screens-households-in-vulnerable-areas-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread-819999.html|title=Tamil Nadu screens households in vulnerable areas to prevent coronavirus spread|date=2020-04-01|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=\"containmentDH\" /><ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /> Active surveillance inside these zones along with passive surveillance outside of it to trace the contacts of the infected has been initiated. People found infected are quarantined and the area where they lived is added into the containment plan.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\" /><ref name=\"CM-News18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/politics/over-2-lakh-passengers-screened-43000-in-home-quarantine-tamil-nadu-cm-assures-state-ready-to-battle-covid-19-2559869.html|title='Over 2 Lakh Passengers Screened, 43,000 in Home Quarantine': Tamil Nadu CM Assures State Ready to Battle Covid-19|date=2020-04-01|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nFrom 29 March, as part of its containment plan, the government had screened 3,96,147 people in their houses inside containment zones of 16 affected districts for fever and other symptoms. It was carried out by over 2,000 personnel.<ref name=\"containmentDH\" /><ref name=\"CM-News18\" /> It was in process of screening up to 7 lakh persons.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\" />\n\nAs of 31 March, 74,533 passengers who had returned from affected countries are being monitored under 28 day home quarantine. 3470 have completed this quarantine. 79 are currently in institutional quarantine facilities across the state.<ref name=\"Daily30Mar\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|title=Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070449/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Governmental response ==\nThe [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] was among the first to launch measures against COVID-19.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /> On 30 January, it had put 78 people who arrived from China under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNborder\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Tamil Nadu closes borders, constitutes task force|work=Business Standard India|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323121451/https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|archive-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The state government had announced a {{INRConvert|3280|c|year=2020}} relief package on 24 March. It included financial support of {{INRConvert|1000|year=2020}} to all ration card holders, free rice and other essential commodities in the wake of [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]]. It also provided registered [[Hawker (trade)|street vendors]], autorickshaw drivers, migrant labourers and construction workers in the state with similar provisions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|title=TN announces \u20b93,280-crore relief package|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325143624/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It had also announced extension periods of three months to make loan and tax payments for all citizens, and one month to pay house rent for workers including migrants across the state.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-govt-announces-one-month-rent-freeze-action-can-be-taken-if-house-owners-disobey-121552|title=TN govt announces one month rent freeze for workers, including migrants|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Loans-BS\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/covid-19-tamil-nadu-gives-3-month-extension-for-payment-of-taxes-loans-120033101318_1.html|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu gives 3-month extension for payment of taxes, loans|date=31 March 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEarlier, it had allocated sum of {{INRConvert|60|c}} from disaster relief fund to deal with the crisis. It had also taken steps to provide medicines for the next two months to patients with hypertension, diabetes mellitus, HIV and TB while also monitoring pregnant women who are due within that time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Palaniswami|first=Edappadi K.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|title=Tamil Nadu CM writes on how the State is stopping the pandemic in its tracks|date=2020-04-01|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401124254/https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|title=Pregnant women to be monitored|date=2020-03-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326171940/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNewly built [[Tamil Nadu Government Multi Super Speciality Hospital|Omandurar Government Multispeciality Hospital]] in Chennai was converted with 500 beds to exclusively treat COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kannan|first=Ramya|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|title=Tamil Nadu announces dedicated hospital for COVID-19 patients|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328230331/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 27 March, the government issued appointment order to recruit 530 doctors, 1,000 nurses and 1,508 lab technicians with immediate effect due to the situation. Orders for 200 new ambulances in the state have also been placed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|title=Tamil Nadu recruits 530 doctors, 1508 lab technicians, 1000 nurses to contain coronavirus COVID-19 outbreak: CM K Palaniswami|date=2020-03-27|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327100522/https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CM-News18\" />\n\nOn 31 March, it announced that house rent cannot be taken from workers, including migrant workers, for a period of one month.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\" /> It also extended the time to make payments including loans and taxes by three months.<ref name=\"Loans-BS\" />\n\nThe government has established helplines for public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/whomtocontact.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Contact Information|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It also released an app for officials to monitor people under home quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tn-tracks-movements-of-home-quarantine-people-through-a-mobile-app-817853.html|title=Coronavirus: TN tracks movements of home quarantine people through a mobile app|date=2020-03-26|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspensions and closedowns ===\nOn 15 March, Chief minister [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami|Edappadi K Palaniswami]] ordered closure of primary schools throughout the state while shutting theatres, commercial complexes and malls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|title=Tamil Nadu govt to release Rs 60 crore disaster relief fund to tackle coronavirus, shuts primary schools|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316010520/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> He had also ordered to close state borders with [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]] on March 20 until March 31 and constituted a task force to closely monitor the preventive measures against the viral outbreak.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|title=TN closes border roads, movement of essentials allowed|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323121451/https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, the Class 10 SSLC board exams were postponed to beyond April 14, which were due to begin from March 27.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu's Class 10 board exams postponed|accessdate=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322145203/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Students of class 1\u20139 in the state will be promoted automatically considering the closure of schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|title=Class 1-9 students will be promoted in Tamil Nadu due to closure of schools: CM|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325135110/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the state government extended '[[Janata Curfew|''Janata curfew'']]' to Monday morning 5 am.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-govt-extends-janata-curfew-till-monday-morning/articleshow/74758800.cms|title=Tamil Nadu govt extends 'Janata curfew' till Monday morning|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The next day, it announced that prohibitory orders under [[Unlawful assembly|Section 144]] will start from 24 March 6 pm until March 31 which prohibits gatherings of more than 5 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|title=TN imposes Section 144 for a week, no gatherings of more than 5 people|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323102039/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] announced a [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|nationwide lockdown]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India places millions under lockdown to fight coronavirus|author1=Helen Regan|author2=Esha Mitra|author3=Swati Gupta|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325053856/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the nationwide lockdown, Chennai suspended delivery of cooked food from services like [[Swiggy]] and [[Zomato]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shrivastava|first=Aditi|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/chennai-bans-delivery-of-cooked-food/articleshow/74837380.cms?from=mdr|title=Chennai bans delivery of cooked food|date=2020-03-27|work=The Economic Times|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|title=Swiggy and Zomato not allowed to deliver in Tamil Nadu|last=Upadhyay|first=Harsh|date=26 March 2020|website=Entrackr|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327081146/https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The services were allowed by the government after imposing some regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu allows Swiggy, Zomato, other apps to home deliver cooked food {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Sundaram|first=Ram|date=27 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329135126/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Tamil Nadu}}\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India by state or union territory|Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2020s in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Health in Tamil Nadu]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of the viral pandemic in Tamil Nadu, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n| image           = Corona Lockdown Tirupur, Tamil Nadu (2).jpg\n| width           = \n| caption         = Empty store shelves in [[Tiruppur]] due to panic buying prior to lockdown\n| map1            = TN COVID-19 cases in districts.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 2 April)\n{{legend|#d45500ff|30+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ff9955ff|10\u201329 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffe6d5ff|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Chennai]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 309<ref name=\"TNHFW\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/index.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Home|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n| active_cases    = 302<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 6<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| deaths          = 1<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| territories     = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#District-wise cases|26 districts]] including [[Chennai district|Chennai]], [[Coimbatore district|Coimbatore]], [[Erode district|Erode]], [[Madurai district|Madurai]], [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]], [[Theni district|Theni]] and [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]]\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/}}\n| youtube         = \n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]] was confirmed on 7 March 2020. The state has confirmed a total of 309 cases, including 1 death and 6 recoveries, as of 2 April 2020.<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n\n264 (85%) of all reported cases were from one cluster linked to an Islamic religious congregation event ''Tablighi Jamaat'' that took place in [[Delhi]].<ref name=\"MB_april02\">{{cite web |title=Media Bulletin April 02 |url=http://www.stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_02_04_20_COVID_19_6_PM.pdf |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-covid-19-count-jumps-by-110-in-1-day/articleshow/74940428.cms|title=Coronavirus in Tamil Nadu: Tamil Nadu Covid-19 count jumps by 110 in 1 day {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|last2=Menon|first2=Jaya|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=N|first3=Durgesh|last4=Apr 2|first4=an Jha {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last5=2020|last6=Ist|first6=10:28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulte.com/news/83733/More-Than-330-Cases-Linked-to-Delhi-Mosque|title=More Than 330 Cases Linked to Delhi Mosque|last=13|date=2020-04-02|website=Gulte|language=english|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The state government has created containment zones in 16 affected districts to screen residents for checking community spread and to prevent more infections.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|title=Tamil Nadu Prepares for Stage Two of Coronavirus Outbreak With More Home Quarantines, Surveillance|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329134259/https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"containmentDH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-74-nizamuddin-link-to-a-chunk-of-it-surfaces-819633.html|title=Tamil Nadu coronavirus cases rises to 74, Nizamuddin link to a chunk of it surfaces|date=2020-03-31|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== March ===\nThe first case of coronavirus was confirmed on 7 March in a resident from [[Kanchipuram]] in [[Chennai]]. He had returned from [[Oman]] and started developing symptoms including fever and cough.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-patient-quarantined-in-government-hospital-in-chennai/articleshow/74529929.cms?from=mdr|title=Tamil Nadu reports first case of Coronavirus; patient quarantined in Chennai Government Hospital|date=2020-03-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He was isolated in [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]. Later, on 10 March, he recovered and tested negative.<ref name=\"TNrecovered\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-no-fresh-covid-19-cases-in-tamil-nadu-812479.html?utm_campaign=fullarticle&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=inshorts|title=Coronavirus: No fresh COVID-19 cases in Tamil Nadu|date=10 March 2020|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a week without new cases, on 18 March, the second person who had travelled by train from Delhi to Chennai confirmed positive. He did not have any history of foreign travel and was described as a domestic case by the state health minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Nadu's 2nd Coronavirus patient raises community transmission fears|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319193205/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a 21-year-old student who returned from [[Ireland]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|title=Coronavirus LIVE: India's death toll rises to four|website=Business Standard|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319161417/https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a further three were confirmed positive - A Chennai man who had travelled from [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|title=Three more COVID-19 cases in State, one with no travel history|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324184127/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and two [[Thailand]] nationals in [[Erode]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-17-fresh-coronavirus-cases-tally-now-67-819262.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 17 fresh coronavirus cases; tally now 67|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> They were admitted to IRT Hospital in Perundurai in Erode. More than 300 people who had come in contact with the three patients were quarantined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-7th-positive-coronavirus-case-816543.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 7th positive coronavirus case|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first virus-related death in the state was reported after a 54-year-old man in [[Madurai]] died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf : 54 \u0bb5\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd {{!}} Patrikai - Tamil Daily - latest online local breaking news & reviews - Tamilnadu, India & World - politics, cinema, cricket, video & cartoon|date=2020-03-25|website=Tamil News patrikai {{!}} Tamil news online {{!}} latest tamil news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328044912/https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Five others were infected - four Indonesians and their travel guide from Chennai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-tally-goes-up-to-23/articleshow/74810591.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports five new coronavirus cases; tally goes up to 23|author=|newspaper=Economic Times|date = 26 March 2020}}</ref> The five were in quarantine since 22 March in Salem Medical College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-reports-5-new-cases-covid-19-includes-4-indonesian-travellers-and-1-chennai-man-121103|title=TN reports 5 new cases of COVID-19, includes 4 Indonesian travellers and 1 Chennai man|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a 21-year-old youth who had just returned from a trip to [[Dublin]], Ireland was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-positive-tamil-nadu-man-with-travel-history-to-ireland-recovers-120032800122_1.html|title=Covid-19 positive Tamil Nadu man with travel history to Ireland recovers|author=|date=28 March 2020|newspaper=Business Standard India|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new cases - one each in [[Kumbakonam]] and [[Katpadi]] were reported. With this, the total number of confirmed cases had reached 40 in the state.<ref name=\"28Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328125841/https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the state reported eight more cases (four each from Coimbatore and Erode), all of which were linked to the two [[Thailand|Thai]] nationals and their group who had tested positive. The eight included a 10-month-old baby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|title=10-month-old baby and 7 more test positive for COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu; state's tally rises to 50|date=29 March 2020|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329142751/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|archive-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases reached 50.<ref name=\"29Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070556/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, 17 new cases were reported, highest till date in the state<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> - 10 male patients from [[Erode]], all of whom have travelled to Delhi were in contact with the Thailand tourists, 5 in Chennai and 1 each in [[Karur]] and [[Madurai]].<ref name=\"30MarchBulletinOld\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, 57 new cases were reported, all with a history of travel predominately to [[Delhi]], bringing the total to 124.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-reports-57-new-covid-19-cases-in-one-day-79-attended-tablighi-jamaat-state-tally-at-124-1661904-2020-03-31|title=Tamil Nadu reports 57 new Covid-19 cases in one day, 79% attended Tablighi Jamaat. State tally at 124|date=|work=India Today|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the highest single day rise till date. 50 of these cases were from [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]] (18), [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] (22), [[Kanyakumari district|Kanyakumari]] (4) [[Viluppuram|Villupuram]] (3), [[Madurai district|Madurai]] (2) and [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]] (1), all had travel history to Delhi.<ref name=\"31MarBulletin2\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070737/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Officials had discovered that at least 80 out of 124 confirmed cases (79 per cent) in Tamil Nadu were from one cluster as they are direct or indirect contact of the two Thai nationals who had tested positive for on 21 March.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /><ref name=\"Hindu-31March\" /> The Thai nationals, identified as patients 5 and 6 were part of a large group from countries including [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], etc. who had visited the state for an annual pilgrimage.<ref name=\"Hindu-31March\">{{Cite news|last=M|first=Serena Josephine|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|title=25 of 67 patients directly or indirectly linked to Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331163219/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This group had also attended a 3-day religious congregation event known as ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in [[New Delhi]] in early March.<ref name=\"March31-DH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-25-out-of-67-in-tamil-nadu-have-contact-or-travel-history-with-thai-nationals-819372.html|title=Coronavirus: 25 out of 67 in Tamil Nadu have contact or travel history with Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was estimated that more than 1,500 people from the state had participated in this event.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|title=Coimbatore, Erode Stare at Crisis as Tamil Nadu Govt Races to Trace Scores Back from Nizamuddin Event|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401020556/https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials also confirmed that the 54-year-old patient who had died the previous week had also participated in the gathering.  Of 1,500 people who were in the gathering, 1,130 had returned to the state. The government had identified and isolated 515 of the 1,130 people.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> It faced difficulty while trying to map the rest. It had urged people who attended the gathering to step forward and get tested.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Coronavirus update: Tamil Nadu reports 50 more Covid-19 cases {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mar 31|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=23:31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331211819/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nOn 1 April, the state reported 110 new cases, all attended the Delhi Nizamuddin event. The total became 234.<ref name=\"April1-IT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-new-coronavirus-cases-linked-nizamuddin-event-tabligh-1662243-2020-04-01|title=Tamil Nadu reports 110 new coronavirus cases, all linked to Nizamuddin event|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|title=110 more cases in Tamil Nadu on Wednesday, all attended Delhi Jamaat conference|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402005422/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|archive-date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Health Secretary Beela Rajesh said that 1103  out of 1500 attendees of the event had been traced and isolated. 658 of their samples had been tested of which,190 tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu witnesses steep rise in cases|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401210601/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some of the participants approached officials themselves after government's request.<ref name=\":2\" /> Family members and close contacts were either taken to quarantine facilities or home quarantined.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/special-containment-plan-for-tj-group/articleshow/74939483.cms|title=Tamil Nadu: Special containment plan for Tablighi Jamaat group {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=08:57}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 75 new cases were reported, of which 74 of them attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB_april02\"/>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe data below are based on Health and Family Welfare Department of Tamil Nadu daily reports.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases chart}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases}}\n\n== Testing ==\nAs of 31 March, the state had 17 laboratories (11 government and 6 private) to handle testing for the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|title=List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070313/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|title=Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070405/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Initially, it had four government labs.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|title=Why Kerala has done more coronavirus tests than Tamil Nadu \u2013 and why this must change|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328121533/https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n===Sample testing facilities===\n====Public====\n#[[King Institute of Preventive Medicine and Research|King Institute of Preventive Medicine & Research, Chennai]]\n#[[Madras Medical College|Madras Medical College, Chennai]]\n#[[Theni Medical College|Govt. Theni Medical College, Theni]]\n#[[Tirunelveli Medical College|Tirunelveli Medical College, Tirunelveli]]\n# Govt. Medical College, Thiruvarur\n# Kumar Mangalam Govt. Medical College, Salem\n#[[Coimbatore Medical College|Coimbatore Medical College, Coimbatore]]\n# Govt. Medical College, Villupuram\n#[[Madurai Medical College|Madurai Medical College, Madurai]]\n#[[K.A.P. Viswanatham Government Medical College|Govt. Medical College, Trichy]]\n#[[Stanley Medical College|Stanley Medical College, Chennai]] <sup>\u00a7</sup>\n\n====Private====\n#[[Christian Medical College & Hospital, Vellore|Dept. of Clinical Virology, CMC, Vellore.]]\n# Department of Laboratory Services, Apollo Hospitals Enterprise Ltd, Chennai \n# Neuberg  Ehrlich  Lab  Pvt  Ltd,  46-48  Masilamani  Road,  Balaji Nagar, Chennai \n#[[Sri Ramachandra Institute of Higher Education and Research|Sri Ramachandra Medical College & Research Institute, Porur, Chennai]]\n# Microbiology Lab, Veerakeralam Road, Coimbatore \n#[[YRG Care|YRG Care, Chennai]]\n\n<small>'''Note:''' \u00a7 Approved, but not supported by ICMR</small>\n\nThe government started screening passengers arriving at the airports in January. It had screened 2,10,538 passengers as of 1 April.\n\nDuring the first half of March, the state faced criticism for the low number of tests. By 16 March, it had only tested 90 samples while neighbouring Kerala and Karnataka had tested more than 1500 and 750 samples.<ref name=\"Testing-TOI\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|title=Coronavirus Tamil Nadu Updates: In Tamil Nadu, patients &amp; doctors call for increased tests on coronavirus {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=16 March 2020|agency=TNN|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321071302/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The director of Public Health defended the state's low number of tests saying that Kerala saw more travel from coronavirus-affected countries which is why it had detected more cases.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"/> The Public Health department has also said that the state follows test protocols established by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Health Ministry]].<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"/><ref name=\"Testing-TOI\" />\n\nIn order to test community transmission, as of 16 March, the state had tested 22 random samples of people with influenza and severe acute respiratory infection for coronavirus as per [[Indian Council of Medical Research|ICMR]] guidelines. All tested negative.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"/>\n\nFollowing the Delhi Nizamuddin event, authorities said that families of 1103 identified participants will be tested whether or not they show symptoms.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAs of 1 April, 2726 samples have been tested of which, 234 were positive.<ref name=\"TNHFW\" />\n\n== Containment measures ==\nStickers announcing that \"COVID-19/Do not Visit/Home under quarantine,\" were pasted on the doors of houses of foreign returnees to warn the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/27/54000-people-who-landed-from-overseas-to-be-home-quarantined-2122007.html|title=54,000 people who landed from overseas to be home quarantined|access-date=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401214313/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/27/54000-people-who-landed-from-overseas-to-be-home-quarantined-2122007.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Authorities had also marked their arms with home quarantine stamps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|title=Tamil Nadu goes under lockdown; home quarantine stickers pasted on doors of foreign returnees|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326175649/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Government launched a mobile application to allow people under home quarantine to interact healthcare professionals for getting medical advice and counselling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-launches-app-to-provide-advice-to-those-under-home-quarantine-816562.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu launches app to provide advice to those under home quarantine|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, government announced plans for creating containment zones to stop the community spread. The containment zones of 5&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> radius around the residences of infected across 16 districts were set up. It is ringed by an additional 3&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> buffer zone.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-screens-households-in-vulnerable-areas-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread-819999.html|title=Tamil Nadu screens households in vulnerable areas to prevent coronavirus spread|date=2020-04-01|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=\"containmentDH\" /><ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /> Active surveillance inside these zones along with passive surveillance outside of it to trace the contacts of the infected has been initiated. People found infected are quarantined and the area where they lived is added into the containment plan.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\" /><ref name=\"CM-News18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/politics/over-2-lakh-passengers-screened-43000-in-home-quarantine-tamil-nadu-cm-assures-state-ready-to-battle-covid-19-2559869.html|title='Over 2 Lakh Passengers Screened, 43,000 in Home Quarantine': Tamil Nadu CM Assures State Ready to Battle Covid-19|date=2020-04-01|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nFrom 29 March, as part of its containment plan, the government had screened 3,96,147 people in their houses inside containment zones of 16 affected districts for fever and other symptoms. It was carried out by over 2,000 personnel.<ref name=\"containmentDH\" /><ref name=\"CM-News18\" /> It was in process of screening up to 7 lakh persons.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\" />\n\nAs of 31 March, 74,533 passengers who had returned from affected countries are being monitored under 28 day home quarantine. 3470 have completed this quarantine. 79 are currently in institutional quarantine facilities across the state.<ref name=\"Daily30Mar\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|title=Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070449/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Governmental response ==\nThe [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] was among the first to launch measures against COVID-19.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /> On 30 January, it had put 78 people who arrived from China under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNborder\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Tamil Nadu closes borders, constitutes task force|work=Business Standard India|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323121451/https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|archive-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The state government had announced a {{INRConvert|3280|c|year=2020}} relief package on 24 March. It included financial support of {{INRConvert|1000|year=2020}} to all ration card holders, free rice and other essential commodities in the wake of [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]]. It also provided registered [[Hawker (trade)|street vendors]], autorickshaw drivers, migrant labourers and construction workers in the state with similar provisions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|title=TN announces \u20b93,280-crore relief package|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325143624/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It had also announced extension periods of three months to make loan and tax payments for all citizens, and one month to pay house rent for workers including migrants across the state.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-govt-announces-one-month-rent-freeze-action-can-be-taken-if-house-owners-disobey-121552|title=TN govt announces one month rent freeze for workers, including migrants|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Loans-BS\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/covid-19-tamil-nadu-gives-3-month-extension-for-payment-of-taxes-loans-120033101318_1.html|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu gives 3-month extension for payment of taxes, loans|date=31 March 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEarlier, it had allocated sum of {{INRConvert|60|c}} from disaster relief fund to deal with the crisis. It had also taken steps to provide medicines for the next two months to patients with hypertension, diabetes mellitus, HIV and TB while also monitoring pregnant women who are due within that time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Palaniswami|first=Edappadi K.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|title=Tamil Nadu CM writes on how the State is stopping the pandemic in its tracks|date=2020-04-01|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401124254/https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|title=Pregnant women to be monitored|date=2020-03-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326171940/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNewly built [[Tamil Nadu Government Multi Super Speciality Hospital|Omandurar Government Multispeciality Hospital]] in Chennai was converted with 500 beds to exclusively treat COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kannan|first=Ramya|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|title=Tamil Nadu announces dedicated hospital for COVID-19 patients|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328230331/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 27 March, the government issued appointment order to recruit 530 doctors, 1,000 nurses and 1,508 lab technicians with immediate effect due to the situation. Orders for 200 new ambulances in the state have also been placed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|title=Tamil Nadu recruits 530 doctors, 1508 lab technicians, 1000 nurses to contain coronavirus COVID-19 outbreak: CM K Palaniswami|date=2020-03-27|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327100522/https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CM-News18\" />\n\nOn 31 March, it announced that house rent cannot be taken from workers, including migrant workers, for a period of one month.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\" /> It also extended the time to make payments including loans and taxes by three months.<ref name=\"Loans-BS\" />\n\nThe government has established helplines for public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/whomtocontact.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Contact Information|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It also released an app for officials to monitor people under home quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tn-tracks-movements-of-home-quarantine-people-through-a-mobile-app-817853.html|title=Coronavirus: TN tracks movements of home quarantine people through a mobile app|date=2020-03-26|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspensions and closedowns ===\nOn 15 March, Chief minister [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami|Edappadi K Palaniswami]] ordered closure of primary schools throughout the state while shutting theatres, commercial complexes and malls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|title=Tamil Nadu govt to release Rs 60 crore disaster relief fund to tackle coronavirus, shuts primary schools|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316010520/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> He had also ordered to close state borders with [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]] on March 20 until March 31 and constituted a task force to closely monitor the preventive measures against the viral outbreak.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|title=TN closes border roads, movement of essentials allowed|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323121451/https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, the Class 10 SSLC board exams were postponed to beyond April 14, which were due to begin from March 27.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu's Class 10 board exams postponed|accessdate=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322145203/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Students of class 1\u20139 in the state will be promoted automatically considering the closure of schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|title=Class 1-9 students will be promoted in Tamil Nadu due to closure of schools: CM|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325135110/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the state government extended '[[Janata Curfew|''Janata curfew'']]' to Monday morning 5 am.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-govt-extends-janata-curfew-till-monday-morning/articleshow/74758800.cms|title=Tamil Nadu govt extends 'Janata curfew' till Monday morning|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The next day, it announced that prohibitory orders under [[Unlawful assembly|Section 144]] will start from 24 March 6 pm until March 31 which prohibits gatherings of more than 5 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|title=TN imposes Section 144 for a week, no gatherings of more than 5 people|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323102039/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] announced a [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|nationwide lockdown]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India places millions under lockdown to fight coronavirus|author1=Helen Regan|author2=Esha Mitra|author3=Swati Gupta|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325053856/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the nationwide lockdown, Chennai suspended delivery of cooked food from services like [[Swiggy]] and [[Zomato]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shrivastava|first=Aditi|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/chennai-bans-delivery-of-cooked-food/articleshow/74837380.cms?from=mdr|title=Chennai bans delivery of cooked food|date=2020-03-27|work=The Economic Times|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|title=Swiggy and Zomato not allowed to deliver in Tamil Nadu|last=Upadhyay|first=Harsh|date=26 March 2020|website=Entrackr|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327081146/https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The services were allowed by the government after imposing some regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu allows Swiggy, Zomato, other apps to home deliver cooked food {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Sundaram|first=Ram|date=27 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329135126/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\u200e{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Tamil Nadu}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India by state or union territory|Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2020s in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Health in Tamil Nadu]]\n", "name_user": "Tholme", "label": "safe", "comment": "lintfix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Tamil_Nadu"}
{"title_page": "Ta\u00edno", "text_new": "{{about|the Ta\u00edno people|the language|Ta\u00edno language|other uses|Ta\u00edno (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|The indigenous people of the Caribbean}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Ta\u00edno\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = Estatua de Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 II, El Bravo, en el Parque Monumento a Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 II, El Bravo, en Ponce, Puerto Rico (DSC02672C).jpg\n| caption = [[Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 El Bravo (statue)|Statue of Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 II, \"El Bravo\"]]<br />in [[Ponce, Puerto Rico]]<ref>Eli D. Oquendo-Rodr\u00edguez. Pablo L. Crespo-Vargas, editor. ''A Orillas del Mar Caribe: Boceto hist\u00f3rico de la Playa de Ponce - Desde sus primeros habitantes hasta principios del siglo XX.'' First edition. June, 2017. Editorial Akelarre. Centro de Estudios e Investigaciones del Sur Oeste de Puerto Rico (CEISCO). Lajas, Puerto Rico. Page 15. {{ISBN|978-1547284931}}</ref>\n| regions = [[Cuba]], [[Dominican Republic]], [[Haiti]], [[Jamaica]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Bahamas]]\n| ref3 = \n| languages = [[English language|English]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Creole Languages]]<br>[[Ta\u00edno language|Ta\u00edno]] {{small|(historically)}}\n| langs = \n| religions = [[Native American religion]]\n| related_groups = [[Lokono]], [[Island Carib]], [[Garifuna]], [[Igneri]], [[Guanahatabey]], [[Yamaye]]\n| related = \n}}\nThe '''Ta\u00edno''' were an [[indigenous people of the Caribbean]].{{sfn|Rouse|1992|p=161}} At the time of European contact in the late fifteenth century, they were the principal inhabitants of most of [[Cuba]], [[Hispaniola]] (the [[Dominican Republic]] and [[Haiti]]), [[Jamaica]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[The Bahamas]] and the northern [[Lesser Antilles]]. The Ta\u00edno were the first [[New World]] peoples to be encountered by [[Christopher Columbus]] during [[Voyages of Christopher Columbus#first voyage|his 1492 voyage]]. They spoke the [[Ta\u00edno language]], an [[Arawakan language]].<ref name=Britannica>{{cite encyclopedia |title= Taino|encyclopedia= Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|year=2018 }}</ref>\n\nGroups of people currently identify as Ta\u00edno, most notably among the [[Puerto Ricans]], [[Cubans]], [[Jamaicans]], and [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominicans]], both on the islands and on [[United States]] mainland.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|title=What Became of the Ta\u00edno|last=Poole|first=Robert M.|date=October 2011|work=Smithsonian Magazine|access-date=November 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105052216/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|archive-date=November 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Some scholars, such as Jalil Sued Badillo, an ethnohistorian at the [[University of Puerto Rico]], assert that although the official Spanish histories speak of the disappearance of the Ta\u00ednos as an ethnic identification, many survivors left descendants \u2013 usually by intermarrying with other [[ethnic groups]]. Recent research revealed a high percentage of mixed or tri-racial ancestry in Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic. Those claiming Ta\u00edno ancestry also have Spanish ancestry or African ancestry, and often, both.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nTa\u00edno activists have created two unique writing scripts. The scripts are used to write Spanish, not a retained language from pre-Columbian ancestors.<ref>Sherina Feliciano-Santos. 2011. ''An Inconceivable Indigeneity: The Historical, Cultural, and Interactional Dimensions of Puerto Rican Activism''. University of Michigan, doctoral dissertation. [http://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/84542/1/sfelic_1.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424020156/http://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/84542/1/sfelic_1.pdf|date=2012-04-24}}</ref> The organization [[Guaka-k\u00fa]] teaches and uses their script among their own members.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nIn February 2018, a DNA study from an ancient tooth determined that the Ta\u00ednos have living descendants in Puerto Rico, indicating that most Puerto Ricans have a degree of Ta\u00edno ancestry.<ref name=\"Newsweek tooth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/taino-caribbean-indigenous-people-extinct-812729|title=The Ta\u00edno were written off as extinct. Until now.|date=20 February 2018|website=Newsweek.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180508015530/http://www.newsweek.com/taino-caribbean-indigenous-people-extinct-812729|archive-date=2018-05-08|url-status=live|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrank Moya Pons, a Dominican historian, documented that Spanish colonists intermarried with Ta\u00edno women. Over time, some of their mixed descendants intermarried with Africans, creating a tri-racial [[Creole peoples|Creole]] culture. 1514 census records reveal that 40% of Spanish men on the island of Hispaniola had Ta\u00edno wives.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/ | title=What Became of the Ta\u00edno?}}</ref> Ethnohistorian Lynne Guitar writes that the Ta\u00edno were declared extinct in Spanish documents as early as the sixteenth century; however, individual Ta\u00ednos continued to appear in wills and legal records for several decades after the arrival of the Spaniards.{{sfn|Guitar|2000|}}\n\nEvidence suggests that some Ta\u00edno men and African women inter-married and lived in relatively isolated [[Maroon (people)|Maroon]] communities in the interior of the islands, where they developed into a hybrid population of peasants with little or no interference from the Spanish authorities.<ref name=\"History 2019\">{{cite magazine | title=Meet the survivors of a 'paper genocide' | magazine=National Geographic | first=Jorge | last=Baracutei Estevez | date=14 October 2019 | url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2019/10/meet-survivors-taino-tribe-paper-genocide/ | access-date=8 November 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017021929/https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2019/10/meet-survivors-taino-tribe-paper-genocide/ | archive-date=17 October 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} Scholars also note that contemporary rural Dominicans retain elements of Ta\u00edno culture: linguistic features, agricultural practices, food ways, [[medicine]], fishing practices, [[technology]], [[architecture]], [[oral history]], and religious views. Often these cultural traits are looked down upon by urbanites as backward, however.{{sfn|Guitar|2000|}} Sixteen \"autosomal\" studies of peoples in the Spanish-speaking Caribbean and its diaspora (mostly Puerto Ricans) have shown that between 10\u201320% of their DNA is indigenous. Some individuals have slightly higher scores and others have lower scores or no indigenous DNA at all.<ref>{{cite book|title=Race, Identity and Indigenous Politics: Puerto Rican Neo-Ta\u00ednos in the Diaspora and the Island|last=Haslip-Viera|first=Gabriel|date=2014|publisher=Latino Studies Press|pages=111\u2013117}}</ref> A recent study of a population in eastern Puerto Rico where the majority of persons tested claimed Ta\u00edno ancestry and pedigree showed that they had 61% mtDNA (distant maternal ancestry) and 0% y-chromosome DNA (distant paternal ancestry) demonstrating as expected that this is a hybrid creole population.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vilar|first=Miguel G.|display-authors=etal|date=July 2014|title=Genetic diversity in Puerto Rico and its implications for the peopling of the island and the Caribbean|journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|volume=155|issue=3|pages=352\u201368|doi=10.1002/ajpa.22569|pmid=25043798}}</ref>\n\nThe ancestors of the Ta\u00edno originated in South America, and the Ta\u00edno culture as documented developed in the Caribbean. Ta\u00edno groups were in conflict with the [[Island Caribs]] of the southern Lesser Antilles. At the time of contact, the Ta\u00edno were divided into several groups. Western Ta\u00edno groups included the [[Lucayans]] of the Bahamas, the [[Ciboney]] of central Cuba, and the inhabitants of Jamaica. The Classic Ta\u00edno lived in Hispaniola and Puerto Rico, while the Eastern Ta\u00edno lived in the northern islands of the Lesser Antilles.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nAt the time of Columbus's arrival in 1492, there were five Ta\u00edno [[chiefdom]]s in Hispaniola, each led by a principal {{lang|tnq|[[Cacique]]}} ([[tribal chief|chief]]), to whom tribute was paid. The Ta\u00edno name for Hispaniola was {{lang|tnq|Ayiti}} (\"land of high mountains\"), which is the source of the name ''Haiti''. Cuba was divided into 29 chiefdoms, many of which have given their name to modern cities, including [[Havana]], [[Bataban\u00f3, Cuba|Bataban\u00f3]], [[Camag\u00fcey]], [[Baracoa]], and [[Bayamo]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PEE9oipDYksC&pg=PA25|title=Art and Archaeology of Pre-Columbian Cuba|first1=Ramon Dacal|last1=Moure|first2=Manuel Rivero De La|last2=Calle|date=15 February 1997|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Pre|accessdate=19 May 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9780822990703|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230131750/https://books.google.com/books?id=PEE9oipDYksC&pg=PA25|archive-date=30 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Ta\u00edno communities ranged from small settlements to larger centers of up to 3,000 people. They may have numbered 2 million at the time of contact,<ref name=Britannica/> and almost 3 million at the end of the 15th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|title=What Became of the Ta\u00edno?|website=Smithsonian|language=en|access-date=2019-10-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014143641/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|archive-date=2019-10-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Columbus was surprised by the civility of the Ta\u00edno people. Columbus stated, \"They will give all that they do possess for anything that is given to them, exchanging things even for bits of broken crockery,\" he noted upon meeting them in the Bahamas in 1492. \"They were very well built, with very handsome bodies and very good faces....They do not carry arms or know them....They should be good servants.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Spanish conquered various Ta\u00edno chiefdoms during the late fifteenth and early sixteenth century. According to [[The Black Legend]] and some contemporary scholars such as [[Andr\u00e9s Res\u00e9ndez]], [[war]]fare and harsh enslavement by the colonists decimated the population.{{sfn|Chrisp|2006|p=34}}<ref name=\"Res\u00e9ndez\">{{cite book|last=Res\u00e9ndez|first=Andr\u00e9s|date=2016|title=The Other Slavery: The Uncovered Story of Indian Enslavement in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z2gpCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PA17#v=onepage&q&f=false|location=|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|page=17|isbn=978-0547640983|author-link=Andr\u00e9s Res\u00e9ndez|access-date=2019-06-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014143643/https://books.google.com/books?id=Z2gpCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PA17#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=2019-10-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Men were forced to work on colonial plantations and gold mines, as a result, there was no Ta\u00edno left to cultivate their own crops and feed their population.<ref name=\":0\" /> Conversely, most scholars believe that European diseases caused the majority of deaths.  A [[smallpox]] epidemic in Hispaniola in 1518\u20131519 killed almost 90% of the surviving Ta\u00edno.{{sfn|Abbot|2010}}<ref>Alfred W. Crosby, ''The Columbian Exchange'' Westport, 1972, p. 47.</ref> The remaining Ta\u00edno were intermarried with Europeans and Africans, and were incorporated into the Spanish colonies. The Ta\u00edno were considered extinct at the end of the century. However, since about 1840, there have been attempts to create a quasi-indigenous Ta\u00edno identity in rural areas of Cuba, the Dominican Republic, and Puerto Rico. This trend accelerated among Puerto Rican communities in the mainland United States in the 1960s.<ref name=Aikhenvald>Alexandra Aikhenvald (2012) ''Languages of the Amazon'', Oxford University Press</ref> At the 2010 U.S. census, 1,098 people in Puerto Rico identified themselves as \"Puerto Rican Indian\", 1,410 identified as \"Spanish American Indian\", and 9,399 identified as \"Ta\u00edno\". In total, 35,856 Puerto Ricans considered themselves Native American.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2010/cph-t/cph-t-6.html|title=American Indian and Alaska Native Tribes in the United States and Puerto Rico: 2010 (CPH-T-6)|last=|first=|date=2010|website=Census.gov|publisher=Census bureau|access-date=September 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004223420/https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2010/cph-t/cph-t-6.html|archive-date=October 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\n[[File:Reconstruction of Taino village, Cuba.JPG|thumb|right|Reconstruction of a Ta\u00edno village in Cuba]]\n\nA direct translation of the word \"Ta\u00edno\" signified \"men of the good\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Rethinking Columbus \u2013 The Ta\u00ednos: \"Men of the Good\"|last=Barreiro|first=Jos\u00e9|publisher=Rethinking Schools, Ltd.|year=1998|isbn=978-0-942961-20-1|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|pages=[https://archive.org/details/rethinkingcolumb0000unse/page/106 106]|url=https://archive.org/details/rethinkingcolumb0000unse/page/106}}</ref> Additionally, the name was used by the indigenous people of Hispaniola to indicate that they were \"relatives\".<ref>Alegr\u00eda, \"Ta\u00ednos\" vol. 1, p. 345.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2019}}  The Ta\u00edno people, or Ta\u00edno culture, has been classified by some authorities as belonging to the Arawak, as their language was considered to belong to the Arawak language family, the languages of which were present throughout the Caribbean, and much of Central and South America.\nThe early ethnohistorian [[Daniel Garrison Brinton]] called the Ta\u00edno people the \"Island Arawak\".<ref name=\"DGB1871\">{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/arawacklanguageo00brinrich |author=Daniel Garrison Brinton |date=1871 |title=The Arawack language of Guiana in its linguistic and ethnological relations |accessdate=22 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160528021215/https://archive.org/details/arawacklanguageo00brinrich |archive-date=28 May 2016 |url-status=live |publisher=Philadelphia, McCalla & Stavely }}</ref> \nNevertheless, contemporary scholars have recognized that the Ta\u00edno had developed a distinct language and culture.\n\nTa\u00edno and Arawak appellations have been used with numerous and contradictory meanings by writers, travelers, historians, linguists, and anthropologists. Often they were used interchangeably; \"Ta\u00edno\" has been applied to the Greater Antillean nation only, or including the Bahamian nations, or adding the [[Leeward Islands]] nations, or all those excluding the Puerto Rican and Leeward nations. Similarly, \"Island Ta\u00edno\" has been used to refer to those living in the [[Windward Islands]] only, to the northern Caribbean inhabitants only, as well as to the population of the entire Caribbean.\n\nModern historians, linguists and anthropologists now hold that the term Ta\u00edno should refer to all the Ta\u00edno/Arawak nations, except for the [[Island Caribs|Caribs]], who are not seen to belong to the same people. Linguists continue to debate whether the Carib language is an Arawakan [[dialect]] or [[creole language]], or perhaps an individual language, with an Arawakan [[pidgin]] used for communication purposes.\n\nRouse classifies as Ta\u00edno all inhabitants of the Greater Antilles (except the western tip of Cuba), the Bahamian [[archipelago]], and the northern Lesser Antilles. He subdivides the Ta\u00edno into three main groups: Classic Ta\u00edno, mostly from Haiti, Puerto Rico, and the Dominican Republic; Western Ta\u00edno, or sub-Ta\u00edno, for population from Jamaica, Cuba (except for the western tip), and the Bahamian archipelago; and Eastern Ta\u00edno for those from the [[Virgin Islands]] to [[Montserrat]].{{sfn|Rouse|1992|p=7}}\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Ta\u00ednos.svg|right|thumb|The Guanahatabey region in relation to Ta\u00edno and [[Island Carib]] groups]]\nTwo schools of thought have emerged regarding the origin of the indigenous people of the Caribbean.\n\n* One group of scholars contends that the ancestors of the Ta\u00edno came from the center of the [[Amazon Basin]], and are related to the [[Yanomama]]. This is indicated by linguistic, cultural and ceramic evidence. They migrated to the [[Orinoco]] valley on the north coast. From there they reached the Caribbean by way of what is now [[Guyana]] and [[Venezuela]] into [[Trinidad]], proceeding along the Lesser Antilles to Cuba and the Bahamian archipelago. Evidence that supports this theory includes the tracing of the ancestral cultures of these people to the Orinoco Valley and their languages to the Amazon Basin.<ref name=Origins>Rouse, pp. 30\u201348.</ref><ref name=\"native\">{{cite journal | date = Aug 2001 | title = Mitochondrial DNA analysis reveals substantial Native American ancestry in Puerto Rico | url = | journal = Hum. Biol. | volume = 73 | issue = 4| pages = 491\u2013511 | pmid = 11512677  | last1 = Mart\u00ednez-Cruzado | first1 = JC | last2 = Toro-Labrador | first2 = G | last3 = Ho-Fung | first3 = V |display-authors=etal | doi=10.1353/hub.2001.0056}}</ref><ref name=\"Madrigal\">{{cite book|last=Lorena Madrigal|first=Madrigal|title=Human biology of Afro-Caribbean populations|publisher=Cambridge University Press, 2006 |page=121|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ddnkIaZRHxEC&pg=PA121|isbn=978-0-521-81931-2|year=2006}}</ref>\n* The alternate theory, known as the circum-Caribbean theory, contends that the ancestors of the Ta\u00edno diffused from the [[Andean Region of Colombia|Colombian Andes]]. [[Julian H. Steward]], who originated this concept, suggests a migration from the Andes to the Caribbean and a parallel migration into [[Central America]] and into the [[Guianas]], Venezuela, and the Amazon Basin of South America.<ref name=Origins/>\n\nTa\u00edno culture as documented is believed to have developed in the Caribbean. The Ta\u00edno creation story says that they emerged from caves in a sacred mountain on present-day Hispaniola.<ref>Rouse, p. 16.</ref> In Puerto Rico, 21st century studies have shown a high proportion of people having [[Amerindian]] [[MtDNA]]. Of the two major [[haplotypes]] found, one does not exist in the Ta\u00edno ancestral group, so other Native American people are also part of this genetic ancestry.<ref name=\"native\"/><ref name=\"Young_2011_Nature\">{{cite journal |last1=Young |first1=Susan |title=Rebuilding the genome of a hidden ethnicity |journal=Nature |date=October 17, 2011 |url=https://www.nature.com/news/2011/111014/full/news.2011.592.html |access-date=2019-01-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901134845/http://www.nature.com/news/2011/111014/full/news.2011.592.html |archive-date=2018-09-01 |url-status=live |doi=10.1038/news.2011.592 }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Duho.jpg|thumb|right|''Dujo'', a wooden ceremonial chair crafted by Ta\u00ednos]]\nTa\u00edno society was divided into two classes: ''naborias'' (commoners) and ''nita\u00ednos'' (nobles). These were governed by male chiefs known as ''[[cacique]]s'', who inherited their position through their mother's noble line. The nita\u00ednos functioned as sub-caciques in villages, overseeing naborias work. Caciques were advised by priests/healers known as ''bohiques''. Caciques enjoyed the privilege of wearing golden pendants called ''guan\u00edn'', living in square ''boh\u00edos,'' instead of the round ones of ordinary villagers, and sitting on wooden stools to be above the guests they received.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmuseo.org/taino/caciques.html |title=Caciques, nobles and their regalia |accessdate=2006-11-09 |website= |publisher=elmuseo.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061009090513/http://elmuseo.org/taino/caciques.html  |archivedate = 2006-10-09}}</ref> Bohiques were extolled for their healing powers and ability to speak with deities. They were consulted and granted the Ta\u00edno permission to engage in important tasks. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe Ta\u00edno had a [[matrilineal]] system of [[kinship]], descent, and inheritance. When a male heir was not present, the inheritance or succession would go to the oldest male child of the sister of the deceased. The Ta\u00edno had [[Avunculism|avunculocal]] post-marital residence, meaning a newly married couple lived in the household of the maternal uncle. He was more important in the lives of his niece's children than their biological father; the uncle introduced the boys to men's societies. Some Ta\u00edno practiced [[polygamy]]. Men, and sometimes women, might have two or three spouses. A few caciques had as many as 30 wives.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nThe Ta\u00edno women were highly skilled in agriculture. The people depended on it, but the men also fished and hunted. They made fishing nets and ropes from [[cotton]] and [[Palm tree|palm]]. Their dugout [[canoe]]s (''kanoa'') were made in various sizes, which could hold from 2 to 150 people. An average-sized canoe would hold about 15\u201320 people. They used bows and arrows for hunting, and developed the use of poisons on their arrowheads.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nTa\u00edno women commonly wore their hair with bangs in front and longer in back, and they occasionally wore gold jewelry, paint, and/or shells. Ta\u00edno men and unmarried women were usually naked. After marriage, women wore a small cotton apron, called a ''nagua''.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Beding|editor1-first=Silvio|title=The Christopher Columbus Encyclopedia|date=1002|publisher=Palgrave MacMillan|isbn=978-1-349-12573-9|page=346|edition=ebook|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gmmMCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA346&dq=Ta%C3%ADno+sometimes+wore+nothing%7Cnaked#v=onepage&q=Ta%C3%ADno%20sometimes%20wore%20nothing%7Cnaked&f=false|accessdate=11 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412063124/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gmmMCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA346&dq=Ta%C3%ADno+sometimes+wore+nothing%7Cnaked&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFk9z24JzTAhUJC8AKHZl5ALkQ6AEIOTAE#v=onepage&q=Ta%C3%ADno%20sometimes%20wore%20nothing%7Cnaked&f=false#v=onepage&q=Ta%C3%ADno%20sometimes%20wore%20nothing%7Cnaked&f=false|archive-date=2017-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe Ta\u00edno lived in settlements called ''yucayeques'', which varied in size depending on the location. Those in Puerto Rico and Hispaniola were the largest, and those in the Bahamas were the smallest. In the center of a typical village was a central plaza, used for various social activities such as games, festivals, religious [[ritual]]s, and public ceremonies. These plazas had many shapes, including oval, rectangular, narrow, and elongated. Ceremonies where the deeds of the ancestors were celebrated, called ''areitos'', were performed here.<ref name=Rouse15>Rouse, p. 15.</ref>\n\nOften, the general population lived in large circular buildings (''bohios''), constructed with wooden poles, woven straw, and palm leaves. These houses, built surrounding the central plaza, could hold 10\u201315 families each.<ref>Alegr\u00eda, \"Tainos\" p. 346.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2019}} The cacique and his family lived in rectangular buildings (''caney'') of similar construction, with wooden porches. Ta\u00edno home furnishings included cotton hammocks (''hamaca''), sleeping and sitting mats made of palms, wooden chairs ([[dujo]] or duho) with woven seats, platforms, and cradles for children.\n\n[[File:Parco Cerimoniale Indigeno di Caguana.jpg|thumb|left|Caguana Ceremonial ball court (''batey''), outlined with stones]]\nThe Ta\u00edno played a ceremonial ball game called ''[[batey (game)|batey]]''. Opposing teams had 10 to 30 players per team and used a solid [[rubber]] ball. Normally, the teams were composed of men, but occasionally women played the game as well.<ref name=Alegr\u00eda1951p348>Alegr\u00eda (1951), p.348.</ref> The Classic Ta\u00edno played in the village's center plaza or on especially designed rectangular ball courts called ''batey''. Games on the ''batey'' are believed to have been used for conflict resolution between communities. The most elaborate ball courts are found at chiefdom boundaries.<ref name=Rouse15/> Often, chiefs made wagers on the possible outcome of a game.<ref name=Alegr\u00eda1951p348/>\n\nTa\u00edno spoke an [[Arawakan language]] and used an early form of writing [[Proto-writing]] in the form of [[petroglyph]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tainoage.com/meaning.html|title=Taino Symbol Meanings|website=Tainoage.com|accessdate=19 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705233343/http://www.tainoage.com/meaning.html|archive-date=2018-07-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSome words that they used, such as ''barbacoa'' (\"barbecue\"), ''hamaca'' (\"hammock\"), ''kanoa'' (\"canoe\"), ''tabaco'' (\"tobacco\"), ''[[cassava|yuca]]'', ''batata'' (\"sweet potato\"), and ''[[jurac\u00e1n]]'' (\"hurricane\"), have been incorporated into Spanish and English.\n\nFor warfare, the men made wooden war clubs, which they called a ''[[macana]].'' It was about one inch thick and was similar to the [[coco macaque]].\n\n== Cacicazgo/society ==\n[[File:Smithsonian 1901 map of Puerto Rico caciques.png|300px|right|Smithsonian 1901 map of Puerto Rico caciques]]\nThe Ta\u00edno were the most culturally advanced of the [[Arawak]] Group to settle in what is now [[Puerto Rico]].<ref name=Wagenheim12>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico: an interpretive history from pre-columbian times to 1900|last=Jimenez de Wagenheim, Olga|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761225|location=|page=12|oclc=1025952187}}</ref> Individuals and [[kinship]] groups that previously had some prestige and rank in the [[tribe]] began to occupy the hierarchical position that would give way to the ''[[cacicazgo]]''.<ref name=enciclopediapr>{{Cite web|url=https://enciclopediapr.org/encyclopedia/el-desarrollo-del-cacicazgo-en-las-sociedades-tardias-de-puerto-rico/|website=enciclopediapr.org|access-date=2019-05-10|title=El desarrollo del cacicazgo en las sociedades tard\u00edas de Puerto Rico -|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527232443/https://enciclopediapr.org/encyclopedia/el-desarrollo-del-cacicazgo-en-las-sociedades-tardias-de-puerto-rico/|archive-date=2019-05-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The Ta\u00edno founded [[Human settlement|settlements]] around [[village]]s and organized their chiefdoms, or ''cacicazgos'', into a confederation.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico : an interpretive history from pre-Columbian times to 1900|last=Wagenheim, Olga Jim\u00e9nez de|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761217|location=Princeton, N.J.|pages=12|oclc=37457914}}</ref> The Taino society, as described by the chroniclers, was composed of four social classes: the ''[[cacique]]'', the ''nita\u00ednos'', the ''behiques,'' and the ''naborias''.<ref name=enciclopediapr/> According to archeological evidence, the Ta\u00edno islands were able to support an enormous number of people for approximately 1,500 years.<ref name=Rethinking>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H7FMDztgSfkC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rethinking Columbus: The Next 500 Years|last=Bigelow|first=Bill|last2=Peterson|first2=Bob|date=1998|publisher=Rethinking Schools|isbn=9780942961201|language=en}}</ref> Every individual living in the Ta\u00edno society had a task to do. For the Ta\u00ednos, it was very important that everyone living in their islands ate properly.<ref name=Rethinking/> They followed a very efficient nature harvesting and agricultural production system.<ref name=Rethinking/> Either people were hunting, searching for food, or doing other productive tasks.<ref name=Rethinking/>\n\nTribal groups settled in villages under a [[Tribal chief|chieftain]], known as ''cacique'', or ''cacica'' if the ruler was a woman. Many women the [[Spaniards]] called ''cacicas'' were not always rulers in their own right, but were mistakenly recognized as such because they were the [[Wife|wives]] of caciques.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}} Chiefs were chosen from the ''nita\u00ednos'' and generally obtained their power from the [[Matrilineality|maternal]] line. Male rulers were more likely to be succeeded by his sister's children than his own, unless their mother's lineage allowed them to succeed in their own right.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico: an interpretive history from pre-columbian times to 1900|last=Jimenez de Wagenheim, Olga|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761225|location=|pages=12\u201313|oclc=1025952187}}</ref>\n\nThe chiefs had both temporal and spiritual functions. They were expected to ensure the welfare of the tribe and to protect it from harm from both natural and supernatural forces.<ref name=Wagenheim13>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico: an interpretive history from pre-columbian times to 1900|last=Jimenez de Wagenheim, Olga|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761225|location=|page=13|oclc=1025952187}}</ref> They were also expected to direct and manage the production process. The caciques power came from the number of villages he controlled and was based on a network of alliances related to [[family]], matrimonial and ceremonial ties. These alliances showed unity of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] communities in a territory<ref name=\"Smithsonian 1901\">{{cite web | title=Bulletin : Smithsonian Institution. Bureau of American Ethnology | website=Internet Archive | date=23 October 1901 | url=https://archive.org/details/bulletin14341948smit | access-date=7 November 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518212909/https://archive.org/details/bulletin14341948smit | archive-date=18 May 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> that would get together as a defensive strategy to face external threats, like the attacks by the [[Island Caribs|Caribs]] on communities in Puerto Rico.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rodr\u00edguez Ramos|first=Reniel|chapter=Current Perspectives in the Precolonial Archaeology of Puerto Rico|date=2019-02-25|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199366439|doi=10.1093/acrefore/9780199366439.013.620|title=Oxford Research Encyclopedia of Latin American History}}</ref> [[Polygamy]] allowed the cacique to have women in different localities, thus extending his power. The cacique carried, as a symbol of his [[hierarchy]], a [[guan\u00edn]] of South American origin made of an alloy of gold and copper. This symbolized the first Ta\u00edno mythical cacique Anacacuya that means star of the center or central spirit. In addition to the guan\u00edn, the cacique used other artifacts and adornments that served to identify it. Some examples are tunics of [[cotton]] and [[feather]]s, crowns and masks or \"guaizas\" of cotton with feathers; colored stones, shells or gold;cotton woven belts; and necklaces of snail beads or stones with small masks of gold or other material.<ref name=enciclopediapr/>\n\n[[File:Copia de Cacicazgos de la Hispaniola.png|thumb|275x275px|Cacicazgos of Hispaniola|alt=|left]]\nUnder the ''cacique'' there social organization was composed of two tiers: The ''nita\u00ednos'' at the top and the ''naborias'' at the bottom.<ref name=Wagenheim12/> The ''nita\u00ednos'' were considered the [[Nobility|nobles]] of the tribes. They were the [[warrior]]s and family of the cacique.<ref name=proyectosalonhogar>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proyectosalonhogar.com/enciclopedia_ilustrada/indios_tainos.htm|title=Indios Tainos|website=www.proyectosalonhogar.com|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114051729/http://www.proyectosalonhogar.com/enciclopedia_ilustrada/indios_Tainos.htm|archive-date=2016-01-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Advisers that assisted in the mundane matters of assigning and supervising communal work, planting and [[harvest]]ing crops, and keeping peace among the village's inhabitants, were selected from among the ''nita\u00ednos''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico: an interpretive history from pre-columbian times to 1900|last=Jimenez de Wagenheim, Olga|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761225|oclc=1025952187}}</ref> The ''naborias'' were simply working peasants of the lower class.<ref name=proyectosalonhogar/>\n\nThe ''behiques'' were [[priest]]s who represented religious beliefs.<ref name=proyectosalonhogar/> Behiques dealt with negotiating with angry or indifferent gods as the accepted lords of the spiritual world. The behiques were expected to communicate with the [[Deity|gods]], to soothe them when they were angry, and to intercede on the tribe's behalf. It was their duty to cure the sick, heal the wounded, and interpret the will of the gods in ways that would satisfy the expectations of the tribe. Before carrying out these functions, the behiques performed certain cleansing and purifying [[ritual]]s, such as fasting for several days and inhaling sacred tobacco snuff.<ref name=Wagenheim13/>\n\n==Food and agriculture==\n\n[[File:Manihot esculenta dsc07325.jpg|thumb|right|[[Cassava]], starchy (''yuca'') roots, the Ta\u00ednos' main crop]]\nTa\u00edno staples included vegetables, fruit, meat, and fish. There were no large animals native to the Caribbean, but they captured and ate small animals, such as [[hutia]]s and other mammals, [[earthworms]], [[lizards]], [[turtles]], and [[birds]]. [[Manatees]] were speared and fish were caught in nets, speared, trapped in [[weir]]s, or caught with hook and line. Wild [[parrots]] were decoyed with domesticated birds, and [[iguanas]] were taken from trees and other [[vegetation]]. The Ta\u00edno stored live animals until they were ready to be consumed: fish and turtles were stored in weirs, hutias and dogs were stored in corrals.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.13\">Rouse, p. 13.</ref>\n[[File:Piedra Escrita in Jayuya, Puerto Rico.jpg|thumb|Piedra Escrita on [[R\u00edo Saliente|River Saliente]] in Jayuya, Puerto Rico]]\n\nBecause of the lack of large game, the Ta\u00edno people became very skilled [[fishermen]]. One method was to hook a [[remora]], also known as a suckerfish, to a line secured to a canoe and wait for the fish to attach itself to a larger fish or even a sea turtle. Once this happened, some of the Ta\u00edno would dive into the water to assist in retrieving the catch. Another method used by the Ta\u00ednos was to shred the stems and roots of poisonous [[senna (plant)|senna]] plants and throw them into nearby streams or rivers. Upon eating the bait, the fish were stunned, allowing boys time enough to collect them. This toxin did not affect the edibility of the fish. The Ta\u00edno also collected [[mussel]]s and [[oyster]]s in shallow waters within the exposed [[mangrove]] roots.<ref name=\"Jacobs1992\">{{cite book|author=Francine Jacobs|title=The Tainos: The People who Welcomed Columbus|url=https://archive.org/details/tainospeoplewhow00jaco|url-access=registration|year=1992|publisher=G.P. Putnam's Sons|isbn=978-0-399-22116-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/tainospeoplewhow00jaco/page/26 26]}}</ref> Some young boys hunted waterfowl from flocks that \"darkened the sun\", according to Christopher Columbus.<ref name=Rethinking/>\n\nTa\u00edno groups in the more developed islands, such as Puerto Rico, Hispaniola, and Jamaica, relied more on agriculture (farming and other jobs). Fields for important [[root crops]], such as the staple [[Cassava|yuca]], were prepared by heaping up mounds of soil, called ''conucos''. This improved soil drainage and fertility as well as delaying erosion, allowed for longer storage of crops in the ground. Less important crops such as corn were raised in simple clearings created by [[slash and burn]] technique. Typically, ''conucos'' were three feet high and nine feet in circumference and were arranged in rows.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.12\">Rouse, p.12.</ref> The primary root crop was yuca or [[cassava]], a woody [[shrub]] cultivated for its edible and [[starch]]y [[tuberous root]]. It was planted using a ''coa'', a kind of [[hoe (tool)|hoe]] made completely from wood. Women processed the poisonous variety of cassava by squeezing it to extract the toxic juices. Then they would grind the roots into flour for baking bread. ''Batata'' ([[sweet potato]]) was the next most important root crop.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.12\"/>\n\nContrary to mainland practices, corn was not ground into flour and baked into bread, but was cooked and eaten off the cob. Corn bread becomes moldy faster than cassava bread in the high humidity of the Caribbean. Corn also was used to make an alcoholic beverage known as [[chicha]].<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://www.academia.edu/423889 |last=Duke |first=Guy S. |title=Identity Crisis: Archaeological Perspectives on Social Identity |chapter=Continuity, Cultural Dynamics, and Alcohol: The Reinterpretation of Identity through Chicha in the Andes |website=Academia.edu |access-date=2017-12-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210124529/http://www.academia.edu/423889/Continuity_Cultural_Dynamics_and_Alcohol_The_Reinterpretation_of_Identity_through_Chicha_in_the_Andes |archive-date=2018-12-10 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Ta\u00edno grew [[Squash (fruit)|squash]], [[beans]], [[capsicum|peppers]], [[peanut]]s, and [[pineapple]]s. [[Tobacco]], [[calabash]]es (West Indian pumpkins), and [[cotton]] were grown around the houses. Other fruits and vegetables, such as [[Arecaceae|palm nuts]], [[guava]]s, and ''[[Zamia]]'' roots, were collected from the wild.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.12\"/>\n\n==Spirituality==\n[[File:Taino - Zemi - Walters 20056 - Left Side.jpg|thumb|Ta\u00edno zem\u00ed sculpture<br />''[[Walters Art Museum]]'']]\nTa\u00edno spirituality centered on the worship of [[Zemi|zem\u00eds]]. A zem\u00ed is a spirit or ancestor. The major Ta\u00edno zemis are [[Atabey (goddess)|Atabey]] and her son, [[Y\u00facahu]]. Atabey, was the zemi of the [[moon]], fresh waters, and fertility. Other names for her include Atabei, Atabeyra, Atabex, and Guimazoa.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} The Ta\u00ednos of Quisqueya (Dominican Republic) called her son, \"Yucah\u00fa Bagua Maorocot\u00ed\", which means \"White Yuca, great and powerful as the sea and the mountains\". He was the spirit of cassava, the zemi of cassava&nbsp;\u2013 the Ta\u00ednos' main crop&nbsp;\u2013 and the sea.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nGuabancex was the non-nurturing aspect of the zemi Atabey who had control over natural disasters. She is identified as the goddess of the hurricanes or as the zemi of storms. Guabancex had twin sons: Guataub\u00e1, a messenger who created hurricane winds, and Coatrisquie, who created [[flood]]waters.<ref>Rouse, p. 121.</ref>\n\nIguanabo\u00edna was the goddess of the good weather. She also had twin sons: Boinayel, the messenger of rain, y Marohu, the spirit of clear skies.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mitolog\u00eda y religi\u00f3n de los ta\u00ednos|last=Robiu-Lamarche|first=Sebasti\u00e1n|publisher=Edit. Punto y Coma|year=2006|isbn=0-9746236-4-4|location=San Juan, Puerto Rico|pages=69, 84}}</ref>\n\nThe minor Ta\u00edno zemis related to the growing of cassava, the process of life, creation, and death. Baibrama was a minor zemi worshiped for his assistance in growing cassava and curing people from its poisonous juice. Boinayel and his twin brother M\u00e1rohu were the zemis of rain and fair weather, respectively.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.119\">Rouse, p. 119.</ref>\n\nMaquetaurie Guayaba or Maketaori Guayaba was the zemi of Coaybay or Coabey, the land of the dead. Opiyelguabir\u00e1n', a dog-shaped zemi, watched over the dead. Demin\u00e1n Caracaracol, a male cultural hero from whom the Ta\u00edno believed themselves to be descended, was worshipped as a zem\u00ed.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.119\"/> Macocael was a cultural hero worshipped as a zemi, who had failed to guard the mountain from which [[human beings]] arose. He was punished by being turned into stone, or a bird, a [[frog]], or a reptile, depending on interpretation of the [[myth]]. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[File:Lombards Museum 053.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Zem\u00ed, a physical object housing a zemi, spirit, or ancestor<br />''Lombards Museum'']]\nZem\u00ed was also the name the people gave to their physical representations of the Zemis, whether objects or drawings. They were made in many forms and materials and have been found in a variety of settings. The majority of zem\u00eds were crafted from wood, but stone, [[bone]], [[Seashell|shell]], [[pottery]], and cotton were used as well.<ref>Rouse, pp. 13, 118.</ref> Zem\u00ed [[petroglyph]]s were carved on rocks in streams, ball courts, and on [[stalagmite]]s in caves. ''Cem\u00ed'' [[pictograph]]s were found on secular objects such as pottery, and on [[tattoos]]. Yucah\u00fa, the zemi of cassava, was represented with a three-pointed zem\u00ed, which could be found in ''conucos'' to increase the yield of cassava. Wood and stone zem\u00eds have been found in [[caves]] in Hispaniola and Jamaica.<ref>Rouse, p. 118.</ref> ''Cem\u00eds'' are sometimes represented by [[toads]], turtles, fish, [[snakes]], and various abstract and human-like faces. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Taino. Cohoba Spoon, 1200-1500.jpg|thumbnail|right|Cohoba Spoon, 1200\u20131500<br />''[[Brooklyn Museum]]'']]\n[[File:Petroglyph at Caguana.jpg|thumb|right|Rock [[petroglyph]] overlaid with chalk in the Caguana Indigenous Ceremonial Center in Utuado, Puerto Rico]]\nSome zem\u00eds are accompanied by a small table or tray, which is believed to be a receptacle for [[hallucinogen]]ic [[Herbal smokeless tobacco|snuff]] called ''[[cohoba]],'' prepared from the beans of a species of ''[[Piptadenia]]'' tree. These trays have been found with ornately carved snuff tubes. Before certain ceremonies, Ta\u00ednos would purify themselves, either by inducing vomiting (with a swallowing stick) or by [[fasting]].<ref>Rouse, p. 14.</ref> After communal bread was served, first to the zem\u00ed, then to the cacique, and then to the common people, the people would sing the village epic to the accompaniment of [[maraca]] and other instruments.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nOne Ta\u00edno [[oral tradition]] explains that the Sun and Moon come out of caves. Another story tells of people who once lived in caves and only came out at night, because it was believed that the Sun would transform them. The Ta\u00edno believed they were descended from the union of the cultural hero Demin\u00e1n Caracaracol and a female turtle.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} The origin of the oceans is described in the story of a huge flood that occurred when a father murdered his son (who was about to murder the father). The father put his son's bones into a [[gourd]] or [[calabash]]. When the bones turned into fish, the gourd broke, and all the water of the world came pouring out. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nTa\u00ednos believed that Jupias, the souls of the dead, would go to Coaybay, the underworld, and there they rest by day. At night they would assume the form of bats and eat the [[guava]] fruit. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Spaniards and Ta\u00edno==\nColumbus and the crew of his ship were the first [[European ethnic groups|Europeans]] to encounter the Ta\u00edno people, as they landed in The Bahamas on October 12, 1492. After their first interaction, Columbus described the Ta\u00ednos as a physically tall, well-proportioned people, with a noble and kind personality.\n\nIn [[Christopher Columbus's journal|his diary]], Columbus wrote:\n{{quote|They traded with us and gave us everything they had, with good will&nbsp;... they took great delight in pleasing us&nbsp;... They are very gentle and without knowledge of what is evil; nor do they murder or steal...Your highness may believe that in all the world there can be no better people&nbsp;... They love their neighbours as themselves, and they have the sweetest talk in the world, and are gentle and always laughing.<ref>Kirkpatrick Sale, ''The Conquest of Paradise'', p. 100, {{ISBN|0-333-57479-6}}</ref>}}\n\nAt this time, the neighbors of the Ta\u00edno were the [[Guanahatabey]]s in the western tip of Cuba, the Island-Caribs in the Lesser Antilles from [[Guadeloupe]] to [[Grenada]], and the [[Calusa]] and [[Ais (tribe)|Ais]] nations of [[Florida]]. Guanahan\u00ed was the Ta\u00edno name for the island that Columbus renamed as ''San Salvador'' (Spanish for \"Holy Savior\"). Columbus called the Ta\u00edno \"Indians\", a reference that has grown to encompass all the indigenous peoples of the [[Western Hemisphere]]. A group of Ta\u00edno people accompanied Columbus on his return voyage to Spain.<ref>{{cite book |title=North American Exploration: A New World Disclosed. Volume: 1 |author=Allen, John Logan |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |year=1997 |page=13}}</ref>\n\nOn Columbus' second voyage to their culture, he began to require tribute from the Ta\u00edno in Hispaniola. According to [[Kirkpatrick Sale]], each adult over 14 years of age was expected to deliver a hawks bell full of gold every three months, or when this was lacking, twenty-five pounds of spun cotton. If this tribute was not brought, the Spanish cut off the hands of the Ta\u00edno and left them to bleed to death.<ref>Kirkpatrick Sale, \"The Conquest of Paradise\", p. 155, {{ISBN|0-333-57479-6}}</ref> These cruel practices inspired many revolts by the Ta\u00edno and campaigns against the Spanish \u2014 some being successful, some not.\n\nIn 1511, several caciques in Puerto Rico, such as [[Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 II]], [[Arasibo]], [[Hayuya]], [[Jumacao]], [[Urayo\u00e1n]], [[Guarionex]], and [[Orocobix]], allied with the Carib and tried to oust the Spaniards. The revolt was suppressed by the Indio-Spanish forces of Governor [[Juan Ponce de Le\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=three%20thousand%20islanders&f=false | accessdate=31 July 2010 | page=143| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> [[Hatuey]], a Ta\u00edno chieftain who had fled from Hispaniola to Cuba with 400 natives to unite the Cuban natives, was burned at the stake on February 2, 1512.\n\nIn Hispaniola, a Ta\u00edno chieftain named [[Enriquillo]] mobilized more than 3,000 Ta\u00edno in a successful rebellion in the 1520s. These Ta\u00edno were accorded land and a charter from the royal administration. Despite the small Spanish military presence in the region, they often used diplomatic divisions and, with help from powerful native allies, controlled most of the region.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=water%20extreme%20heat&f=false | accessdate=10 July 2010 | page=132| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=onepage&q=concluding&f=false | accessdate=10 July 2010 | page=199| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> In exchange for a seasonal salary, religious and language education, the Ta\u00edno were required to work for Spanish and Indian land owners. This system of labor was part of the ''[[encomienda]]''.\n\n==Women==\n\nTa\u00edno society was based on a [[Matrilineality|matrilineal]] system and descent was traced through the mother. Women lived in village groups containing their children. The men lived separately. Because of this Ta\u00edno women had extensive control over their lives, their co-villagers, and their bodies.<ref>Saunders, Nicholas J. Peoples of the Caribbean: An Encyclopedia of Archeology and Traditional Culture. Santa Barbara, CA: ABC-CLIO, 2005. Web.</ref> Since they lived separately from men, they were able to decide when they wanted to participate in sexual contact. This social organization partially shaped the views of [[conquistador]]s who came in contact with Ta\u00edno culture. They reportedly perceived women as \"macha women\" who had strong control over the men. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nAlthough unclear, most historical evidence suggests that Ta\u00edno gender roles were non exclusive regarding most of the activities in their community. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nTa\u00edno women played an important role in intercultural interaction between [[Spaniards]] and the Ta\u00edno people. When Ta\u00edno men were away fighting intervention from other groups, women assumed the roles of primary food producers or ritual specialists.<ref>Dale, Corrine H., and J. H. E. Paine. Women on the Edge: Ethnicity and Gender in Short Stories by American Women. New York: Garland Pub., 1999. Web.</ref> Women seem to have  participated in all levels of the Ta\u00edno political hierarchy, occupying roles as high up as being ''[[cacique|cazicas]]''.<ref>Taylor, Patrick, and Frederick I. Case. The Encyclopedia of Caribbean Religions Volume 1: A-L; Volume 2: M-Z. Baltimore: U of Illinois, 2015. Web. Chapter title Ta\u00ednos.</ref> Potentially, this meant Ta\u00edno women could make important choices for the village and could assign tasks to tribe members.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Deagan | first1 = Kathleen | year = 2004 | title = Reconsidering Taino Social Dynamics after Spanish Conquest: Gender and Class in Culture Contact Studies | url = | journal = American Antiquity | volume = 69 | issue = 4| pages = 597\u2013626 | doi=10.2307/4128440|jstor=4128440}}</ref> There is evidence that suggests that the women who were wealthiest among the tribe collected crafted goods that they would then use for trade or as gifts.\n\nDespite women being seemingly independent in Ta\u00edno society, during the era of contact Spaniards took Ta\u00edno women as an exchange item, putting them in a non-autonomous position. Dr. Chanca, a physician who traveled with [[Christopher Columbus]], reported in a letter that Spaniards took as many women as they possibly could and kept them as [[Concubinage|concubines]].<ref>Hotep, Amon. \"Women.\" Race and History.com | TAINO | Women. N.p., n.d. Web. 29 Nov. 2016.</ref> Some sources report that, despite women being free and powerful before the contact era, they became the first commodities up for Spaniards to trade, or often, steal. This marked the beginning of a lifetime of kidnapping and abuse of Ta\u00edno women.<ref>Sloan, Kathryn A. Women's Roles in Latin America and the Caribbean. Santa Barbara, CA: Greenwood, 2011. Web.</ref>\n\n==Depopulation==\n\nEarly population estimates of Hispaniola, probably the most populous island inhabited by Ta\u00ednos, range from 100,000 to 1,000,000 people. The maximum estimates for Jamaica and Puerto Rico are 600,000 people.{{sfn|Rouse|1992|p=7}} The Spanish priest and defender of the Ta\u00edno, [[Bartolom\u00e9 de las Casas]] (who had lived in [[Santo Domingo]]), wrote in his 1561 multi-volume ''History of the Indies'':<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.interamerdeminst.org/H8.html|title= Endless War of Domination|accessdate= 2007-10-02|work= Student-Employee Assistance Program Against Chemical Dependency|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071016185314/http://interamerdeminst.org/H8.html|archivedate= 2007-10-16}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|There were 60,000 people living on this island [when I arrived in 1508], including the Indians; so that from 1494 to 1508, over three million people had perished from war, [[slavery]] and the mines. Who in future generations will believe this?}}\n\nResearchers today doubt Las Casas' figures for the pre-contact levels of the Ta\u00edno population, considering them an exaggeration. For example, Anderson C\u00f3rdova estimates a maximum of 500,000 people inhabiting the island.<ref>{{cite book |author=Karen Anderson C\u00f3rdova |title=Hispaniola and Puerto Rico: Indian Acculturation and Heterogeneity, 1492\u20131550 |year=1990 |publisher=University Microfilms International |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan |type=PhD dissertation|id= }}</ref> They had no resistance to [[Old World]] diseases, notably [[smallpox]].<ref>Citation Needed</ref> The ''[[encomienda]]'' system brought many Ta\u00edno to work in the fields and mines in exchange for Spanish [[civil disorder|protection]],<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=onepage&q=begged&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=112| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> [[Spanish language|education]], and a seasonal salary.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=cheerfully&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=182| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> Under the pretense of searching for gold and other materials,<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=columbus%20rapacity&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=111| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> many Spaniards took advantage of the regions now under control of the ''[[Indian auxiliaries|anaborios]]'' and Spanish ''encomenderos'' to exploit the native population by seizing their [[land]] and [[wealth]]. Historian [[David Stannard]] characterizes the encomienda as a genocidal system which \"had driven many millions of native peoples in Central and South America to early and agonizing deaths.\"<ref>{{cite book |last= Stannard|first=David E.|date=1993|title=American Holocaust: The Conquest of the New World|url=https://archive.org/details/americanholocaus00stan|url-access= registration|location= |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/americanholocaus00stan/page/139 139] |isbn=978-0195085570|author-link=David Stannard}}</ref> It would take some time before the Ta\u00edno revolted against their oppressors \u2014 both Indian and Spanish alike \u2014 and many military campaigns before [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Charles V]] eradicated the ''encomienda'' system as a form of slavery.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=three%20thousand&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=143| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Columbus and Las Casas: the conquest and Christianization of America, 1492\u20131566 | author=David M. Traboulay | url=https://books.google.com/?id=7Jmi4Wb1DdsC&pg=PA44&dq=enriquillo+revolt#v=onepage&q=enriquillo%20revolt&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=44| isbn=9780819196422 | year=1994 }}</ref>\n\nDiseases obviously had a lot to do with the decimation of the indigenous population, but forced labor was also one of the chief reasons as to why the population decimated.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} The first man to introduce this forced labor among the Ta\u00ednos was leader of the European Colonization of Puerto Rico, Ponce de Le\u00f3n.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} This forced labor eventually led to the Ta\u00edno rebellions, in which the Spaniards responded with violent military expeditions known as \"cabalgadas\".{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} The purpose of the military expedition was to capture the indigenous peoples.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} This violence by the Spaniards was a reason why there was a decline in the Ta\u00edno population since it forced many of these people to emigrate.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn thirty years, between 80% and 90% of the Ta\u00edno population died.<ref>\"La trag\u00e9die des Ta\u00efnos\", in ''[[L'Histoire]]'' n\u00b0322, July\u2013August 2007, p. 16.</ref> Because of the increased number of people (Spanish) on the island, there was a higher demand for food. Ta\u00edno cultivation was converted to Spanish methods. In hopes of frustrating the Spanish, some Ta\u00ednos refused to plant or harvest their crops. The supply of food became so low in 1495 and 1496 that some 50,000 died from the severity of the famine.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=onepage&q=50%2C000&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=108| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> Historians have determined that the massive decline was due more to infectious disease outbreaks than any warfare or direct attacks.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=onepage&q=thirty&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=160| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Arthur C. Aufderheide|author2=Conrado Rodr\u00edguez-Mart\u00edn|author3=Odin Langsjoen|title=The Cambridge encyclopedia of human paleopathology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qubTdDk1H3IC|year=1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-55203-5|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=qubTdDk1H3IC&pg=PA204 204]|access-date=2016-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202055608/https://books.google.com/books?id=qubTdDk1H3IC|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref> By 1507 their numbers had shrunk to 60,000. Scholars believe that [[pandemic|epidemic]] disease ([[smallpox]], [[influenza]], [[measles]], and [[typhus]]) was an overwhelming cause of the population decline of the indigenous people,<ref name=Watts>{{cite book|last=Watts|first=Sheldon|title=Disease and medicine in world history|year=2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-27816-4|pages=86, 91|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nc9Aq8HOVaEC&pg=PA86|access-date=2016-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202055608/https://books.google.com/books?id=Nc9Aq8HOVaEC&pg=PA86|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref> and also attributed a \"large number of Ta\u00edno deaths...to the continuing bondage systems\" that existed.<ref name=Schimmer>{{cite web|last=Schimmer|first=Russell|title=Puerto Rico|url=http://www.yale.edu/gsp/colonial/puerto-rico/index.html|work=Genocide Studies Program|publisher=Yale University|access-date=2011-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110908234849/http://www.yale.edu/gsp/colonial/puerto-rico/index.html|archive-date=2011-09-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Raudzens>{{cite book|last=Raudzens|first=George|title=Technology, Disease, and Colonial Conquests, Sixteenth to Eighteenth Centuries|year=2003|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-0-391-04206-3|pages=41|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_PFSc4kCyxcC&pg=PA41|access-date=2016-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202055608/https://books.google.com/books?id=_PFSc4kCyxcC&pg=PA41|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Academics, such as historian [[Andr\u00e9s Res\u00e9ndez]] of the [[University of California, Davis]], assert that disease alone does not explain the total destruction of indigenous populations of Hispaniola. While the populations of Europe rebounded following the devastating population decline associated with the [[Black Death]], there was no such rebound for the indigenous populations of the Caribbean. He concludes that, even though the Spanish were aware of deadly diseases such as smallpox, there is no mention of them in the New World until 1519, meaning perhaps they didn't spread as fast as initially believed, and that unlike Europeans, the indigenous populations were subjected to slavery, exploitation and forced labor in gold and silver mines on an enormous scale.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-native-american-slavery-20160505-snap-story.html|title=The new book 'The Other Slavery' will make you rethink American history|last=Treuer|first=David|date=May 13, 2016|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=June 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623103420/https://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-native-american-slavery-20160505-snap-story.html|archive-date=June 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Res\u00e9ndez says that \"slavery has emerged as a major killer\" of the indigenous people of the Caribbean.<ref name=\"Res\u00e9ndez\"/> Anthropologist [[Jason Hickel]] of the [[London School of Economics]] estimates that a third of indigenous workers died every six months from lethal forced labor in these mines.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hickel|first=Jason|date=2018 |title=The Divide: A Brief Guide to Global Inequality and its Solutions|url= |location= |publisher=Windmill Books|page=70 |isbn=978-1786090034}}</ref>\n\n== Ta\u00edno descendants today ==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{essay-like|date=December 2019}}\n{{tone|date=December 2019}}\n{{POV section|date=December 2019}}\n}}\nHistories of the Caribbean commonly describe the Taino as extinct, killed off by disease, slavery, and war with the Spaniards. Some present-day residents of the Caribbean self-identify as Taino, and claim that Taino culture and identity have survived into the present.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|title=What Became of the Ta\u00edno?|last=Poole|first=Robert M.|date=October 2011|work=Smithsonian|access-date=13 December 2019}}</ref> Groups advocating this point of view are known as Neo-Ta\u00ednos, and are established in the Puerto Rican communities located in New Jersey and New York, as well. A few Neo-Ta\u00edno groups are pushing not only for recognition, but respect for their cultural assets.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Curet|first=Antonio L.|date=Spring 2015|title=Indigenous Revival, Indigeneity, and the J\u00edbaro in Borik\u00e9n|url=|journal=Centro Journal|volume=27|pages=206\u2013247|via=}}</ref>\n\nA genetic study published in 2018 provided some evidence of a present-day Caribbean population being related to the Ta\u00ednos. DNA was extracted from a tooth of a 1,000-year-old female skeleton found in a cave in [[Lucaya, Bahamas]], and the genetic results show that she is most closely related to present-day Arawakan speakers from northern South America. The study's authors write that this demonstrates continuity between pre-contact populations and present-day Latino populations in the Caribbean.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Origins and genetic legacies of the Caribbean Taino|first1=Hannes|last1=Schroeder|first2=Martin|last2=Sikora|first3=Shyam|last3=Gopalakrishnan|first4=Lara M.|last4=Cassidy|first5=Pierpaolo Maisano|last5=Delser|first6=Marcela Sandoval|last6=Velasco|first7=Joshua G.|last7=Schraiber|first8=Simon|last8=Rasmussen|first9=Julian R.|last9=Homburger|first10=Mar\u00eda C.|last10=\u00c1vila-Arcos|first11=Morten E.|last11=Allentoft|first12=J. V\u00edctor|last12=Moreno-Mayar|first13=Gabriel|last13=Renaud|first14=Alberto|last14=G\u00f3mez-Carballa|first15=Jason E.|last15=Laffoon|first16=Rachel J. A.|last16=Hopkins|first17=Thomas F. G.|last17=Higham|first18=Robert S.|last18=Carr|first19=William C.|last19=Schaffer|first20=Jane S.|last20=Day|first21=Menno|last21=Hoogland|first22=Antonio|last22=Salas|first23=Carlos D.|last23=Bustamante|first24=Rasmus|last24=Nielsen|first25=Daniel G.|last25=Bradley|first26=Corinne L.|last26=Hofman|first27=Eske|last27=Willerslev|date=March 6, 2018|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=115|issue=10|pages=2341\u20132346|doi=10.1073/pnas.1716839115|pmid=29463742|pmc=5877975}}</ref><ref name=\"Genes found\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2018/02/genes-extinct-caribbean-islanders-found-living-people|title=Genes of 'extinct' Caribbean islanders found in living people|date=February 19, 2018|website=Science &#124; AAAS}}</ref> Today, Ta\u00ednos from places such as the diaspora in the United States and the islands, are gathering together.<ref name=\"Guyana\">{{cite magazine |last=Estevez |first=Jorge Baracutei  |date=August 30, 2017 |title=CARIBBEAN TAINO AND GUYANA INDIGENOUS PEOPLES CACIQUE CROWN A SYMBOL OF BROTHERHOOD - CELEBRATING OUR INDIGENOUS HERITAGE THE ART OF FEATHER WORK CACHUCHABANA FEATHER HEADDRESSES OF THE TAINO PEOPLES|url=http://guyfolkfest.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/GCA-SEPT.-2017-E-MAG.ART-FINAL.pdf |magazine=Guyana Folk & Culture |location= US|publisher=Guyana Cultural Association of New York Inc.on-line Magazine |access-date=December 12, 2019|pages=6\u20137}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2006, there were a couple of dozen activist Taino organizations from Florida to Puerto Rico and California to New York with growing memberships numbering in the thousands. These efforts are known as the \"Ta\u00edno restoration\", a revival movement for Ta\u00edno culture that seeks official recognition of the survival of the Ta\u00edno people.<ref name=\"Forte2006\">{{cite book|author1=L. Guitar|author2=P. Ferbel-Azcarate|author3=J. Esteves|editor=Maximilian Christian Forte|title=Indigenous Resurgence in the Contemporary Caribbean: Amerindian Survival and Revival|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qXZeQZMDpgYC&pg=PA62|year=2006|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-7488-5|page=62|chapter=Ocama-Daca Ta\u00edno}}</ref>\n\nIn Puerto Rico, the history of the Ta\u00edno is being taught in schools and children are encouraged to celebrate the culture and identity of Ta\u00edno through dance, costumes and crafts. Mart\u00ednez Cruzado, a geneticist at the [[University of Puerto Rico at Mayag\u00fcez]] said celebrating and learning about their Ta\u00edno roots is helping Puerto Ricans feel connected to one another.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/02/world/americas/02iht-puerto.4.18336408.html|title=Puerto Rico pageant celebrates a vanished native culture|first=Damien|last=Cave|date=December 2, 2008|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nWhile the scholar Yolanda Mart\u00ednez-San Miguel sees the development of the Neo-Taino movement in Puerto Rico as a useful counter to the domination of the island by the United States and the Spanish legacies of island society, she also notes that the Neo-Taino movement in Puerto Rico \"could be seen as a useless anachronistic reinvention of a 'Boricua coqui' identity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mart\u00ednez-San Miguel|first=Yolanda|date=Spring 2011|title=Taino Warriors?: Strategies for Recovering Indigenous Voices in Colonial and Contemporary Hispanic Caribbean Discourses|url=https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/377/37722223008.pdf|journal=Centro Journal|volume=13|pages=211|via=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n* [[Ciboney]] \n* [[Enriquillo]], rebel cacique\n* [[Garifuna]]\n* [[Hupia]], spirit of the dead\n* [[Indigenous Amerindian genetics]]\n* [[Island Caribs]]\n* [[Jurac\u00e1n]], god of chaos\n* [[List of Ta\u00ednos]]\n* [[Pomier Caves]]\n* [[Tibes Indigenous Ceremonial Center]]\n* [[West Indies]]\n* [[Y\u00facahu]], central Ta\u00edno deity\n* [[Yamaye]]{{div col end}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n|last=Abbot\n|first=Elizabeth\n|title=Sugar: A Bitterweet History\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aaxc1WdKmwEC\n|accessdate=5 March 2013\n|date=1 April 2010\n|publisher=Penguin\n|isbn=978-1-59020-772-7\n|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Chrisp\n|first=P.\n|title=DK Discoveries: Christopher Columbus\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=twyVezztw_UC&pg=PA34\n|accessdate=5 March 2013\n|year= 2006\n|publisher=Penguin\n|isbn=978-0-7566-8616-1\n|ref={{sfnref|Chrisp|2006}} }}\n* {{cite journal |author=Ricardo Alegr\u00eda |date=April 1951 |title=The Ball Game Played by the Aborigines of the Antilles |journal=American Antiquity  |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=348\u2013352 |id= |url= |accessdate= |doi=10.2307/276984 |jstor = 276984}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rouse |first=Irving |author-link=Irving Rouse |title=The Tainos: Rise and Decline of the People Who Greeted Columbus |url=https://archive.org/details/tainosrisedeclin00rous |url-access=registration |year=1992 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=0-300-05696-6 |ref=harv }}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite book\n|last1=Accilien\n|first1=C\u00e9cile\n|last2= Adams\n|first2=Jessica\n|last3= M\u00e9l\u00e9ance\n|first3=Elmide\n|others=Paintings by Ulrick Jean-Pierre\n|title=Revolutionary Freedoms: A History of Survival, Strength and Imagination in Haiti\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O-p7qRKl_G0C&pg=PA1\n|accessdate=21 February 2013\n|year=2006\n|publisher=Educa Vision Inc.\n|isbn=978-1-58432-293-1\n|ref= {{sfnref|Accilien et al.|2003}} }}\n\n<!-- L -->\n* {{cite book\n|last= L\u00e9ger\n|first=Jacques Nicolas\n|title=Haiti, Her History and Her Detractors\n|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924079570762\n|accessdate=21 February 2013\n|year=1907\n|publisher=Neale Publishing Company\n|ref=harv}} [[s:Haiti: Her History and Her Detractors|wikisource]]\n\n* {{cite journal |last=Guitar |first=Lynne |date=2000 |title=Criollos: The Birth of a Dynamic New Indo-Afro-European People and Culture on Hispaniola |url=https://archive.org/stream/KacikeJournal_34/LynneGuitar_djvu.txt |journal=Kacike |publisher=Caribbean Amerindian Centrelink |volume= 1 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201317  |issn= 1562-5028  |name-list-format=vanc |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Guitar |first1=Lynne |last2=Ferbel-Azcarate |first2=Pedro |last3=Estevez |first3=Jorge |title=Indigenous Resurgence in the Contemporary Caribbean: Amerindian Survival and Revival |editor1-last=Forte |editor1-first=Maximilian C. |chapter=Ocama-Daca Ta\u00edno (Hear Me, I Am Ta\u00edno): Ta\u00edno Survival on Hispaniola, Focusing on the Dominican Republic |location=New York |publisher=Peter Lang Publishing |year=2006 |isbn=978-0820474885 |chapter-url=http://www.openanthropology.org/resurgence/abstracts.htm |ref=harv }}\n* DeRLAS. [http://www.udel.edu/LASP/Vol1-2MartinezC.html \"Some important research contributions of Genetics to the study of Population History and Anthropology in Puerto Rico\"]. Newark, Delaware: ''Delaware Review of Latin American Studies''. August 15, 2000.\n* \"The Role of Cohoba in Ta\u00edno Shamanism\", [[Constantino Manuel Torres|Constantino M. Torres]] in ''Eleusis'' No. 1 (1998)\n* \"Shamanic Inebriants in South American Archaeology: Recent Investigations\" [[Constantino Manuel Torres|Constantino M. Torres]] in ''Eleusis'' No. 5 (2001)\n* Tinker, T & Freeland, M. 2008. \"Thief, Slave Trader, Murderer: Christopher Columbus and Caribbean Population Decline\". ''Wicazo Sa Review'', Vol. 23, No. 1, Spring, 2008: 25\u201350. Retrieved from Academic Search Premier Database on 23 Sept. 2008.\n* {{cite journal|last= Guitar |first=Lynne |title=Documenting the Myth of Ta\u00edno Extinction |journal=Kacike}}\n*{{cite book | title= ''The art heritage of Puerto Rico, pre-Columbian to present'' | location=New York | publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art and El Museo del Barrio| year=1973| url= http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/ref/collection/p15324coll10/id/211362}} (Chapter 1: \"The Art of the Taino Indians of Puerto Rico\")\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ta\u00edno}}\n* [http://cronkite.asu.edu/buffett/puertorico/identity.html ''Statehood Issue Stirs Passions About Puerto Rican Identity.'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060624114357/http://www.pem.org/island/ ''Island Thresholds''], Peabody Essex Museum's interactive feature, showcases the work of Caribbean artists and their exploration of culture and identity.\n* [https://www.amstardmc.com/blog/the-cave-of-wonders-in-la-romana/ The Cave of Wonders - Taino Cave Art in La Romana]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071013032642/http://www.taino-tribe.org/terms1.htm ''Ta\u00edno Diccionary''], A dictionary of words of the indigenous peoples of caribbean from the encyclopedia \"Cl\u00e1sicos de Puerto Rico, second edition, publisher, Ediciones Latinoamericanas. S.A., 1972\" compiled by Puerto Rican historian Dr. Cayetano Coll y Toste of the \"Real Academia de la Historia\".\n* [http://www.smithsonianmag.com/people-places/What-Became-of-the-Taino.html 2011 ''Smithsonian'' article on Ta\u00edno culture remnant in the Dominican Republic]\n\n{{pre-Columbian}}\n{{Indigenous peoples by continent}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taino}}\n[[Category:Ta\u00edno| ]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples of the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Cultural history of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Extinct Native American peoples]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples in Cuba]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Haiti]]\n[[Category:History of the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Native American tribes]]\n[[Category:Pre-Columbian cultures]]\n[[Category:Social history of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Spanish West Indies]]\n[[Category:Extinct ethnic groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Ta\u00edno people|the language|Ta\u00edno language|other uses|Ta\u00edno (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|The indigenous people of the Caribbean}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Ta\u00edno\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = Estatua de Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 II, El Bravo, en el Parque Monumento a Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 II, El Bravo, en Ponce, Puerto Rico (DSC02672C).jpg\n| caption = [[Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 El Bravo (statue)|Statue of Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 II, \"El Bravo\"]]<br />in [[Ponce, Puerto Rico]]<ref>Eli D. Oquendo-Rodr\u00edguez. Pablo L. Crespo-Vargas, editor. ''A Orillas del Mar Caribe: Boceto hist\u00f3rico de la Playa de Ponce - Desde sus primeros habitantes hasta principios del siglo XX.'' First edition. June, 2017. Editorial Akelarre. Centro de Estudios e Investigaciones del Sur Oeste de Puerto Rico (CEISCO). Lajas, Puerto Rico. Page 15. {{ISBN|978-1547284931}}</ref>\n| regions = [[Cuba]], [[Dominican Republic]], [[Haiti]], [[Jamaica]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Bahamas]]\n| ref3 = \n| languages = [[English language|English]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Creole Languages]]<br>[[Ta\u00edno language|Ta\u00edno]] {{small|(historically)}}\n| langs = \n| religions = [[Native American religion]]\n| related_groups = [[Lokono]], [[Island Carib]], [[Garifuna]], [[Igneri]], [[Guanahatabey]], [[Yamaye]]\n| related = \n}}\nThe '''Ta\u00edno''' were an [[indigenous people of the Caribbean]].{{sfn|Rouse|1992|p=161}} At the time of European contact in the late fifteenth century, they were the principal inhabitants of most of [[Cuba]], [[Hispaniola]] (the [[Dominican Republic]] and [[Haiti]]), [[Jamaica]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[The Bahamas]] and the northern [[Lesser Antilles]]. The Ta\u00edno were the first [[New World]] peoples to be encountered by [[Christopher Columbus]] during [[Voyages of Christopher Columbus#first voyage|his 1492 voyage]]. They spoke the [[Ta\u00edno language]], an [[Arawakan language]].<ref name=Britannica>{{cite encyclopedia |title= Taino|encyclopedia= Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|year=2018 }}</ref>\n\nGroups of people currently identify as Ta\u00edno, most notably among the [[Puerto Ricans]], [[Cubans]], [[Jamaicans]], and [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominicans]], both on the islands and on [[United States]] mainland.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|title=What Became of the Ta\u00edno|last=Poole|first=Robert M.|date=October 2011|work=Smithsonian Magazine|access-date=November 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105052216/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|archive-date=November 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Some scholars, such as Jalil Sued Badillo, an ethnohistorian at the [[University of Puerto Rico]], assert that although the official Spanish histories speak of the disappearance of the Ta\u00ednos as an ethnic identification, many survivors left descendants \u2013 usually by intermarrying with other [[ethnic groups]]. Recent research revealed a high percentage of mixed or tri-racial ancestry in Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic. Those claiming Ta\u00edno ancestry also have Spanish ancestry or African ancestry, and often, both.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nTa\u00edno activists have created two unique writing scripts. The scripts are used to write Spanish, not a retained language from pre-Columbian ancestors.<ref>Sherina Feliciano-Santos. 2011. ''An Inconceivable Indigeneity: The Historical, Cultural, and Interactional Dimensions of Puerto Rican Activism''. University of Michigan, doctoral dissertation. [http://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/84542/1/sfelic_1.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424020156/http://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/84542/1/sfelic_1.pdf|date=2012-04-24}}</ref> The organization [[Guaka-k\u00fa]] teaches and uses their script among their own members.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nIn February 2018, a DNA study from an ancient tooth determined that the Ta\u00ednos have living descendants in Puerto Rico, indicating that most Puerto Ricans have a degree of Ta\u00edno ancestry.<ref name=\"Newsweek tooth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/taino-caribbean-indigenous-people-extinct-812729|title=The Ta\u00edno were written off as extinct. Until now.|date=20 February 2018|website=Newsweek.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180508015530/http://www.newsweek.com/taino-caribbean-indigenous-people-extinct-812729|archive-date=2018-05-08|url-status=live|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrank Moya Pons, a Dominican historian, documented that Spanish colonists intermarried with Ta\u00edno women. Over time, some of their mixed descendants intermarried with Africans, creating a tri-racial [[Creole peoples|Creole]] culture. 1514 census records reveal that 40% of Spanish men on the island of Hispaniola had Ta\u00edno wives.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/ | title=What Became of the Ta\u00edno?}}</ref> Ethnohistorian Lynne Guitar writes that the Ta\u00edno were declared extinct in Spanish documents as early as the sixteenth century; however, individual Ta\u00ednos continued to appear in wills and legal records for several decades after the arrival of the Spaniards.{{sfn|Guitar|2000|}}\n\nEvidence suggests that some Ta\u00edno men and African women inter-married and lived in relatively isolated [[Maroon (people)|Maroon]] communities in the interior of the islands, where they developed into a hybrid population of peasants with little or no interference from the Spanish authorities.<ref name=\"History 2019\">{{cite magazine | title=Meet the survivors of a 'paper genocide' | magazine=National Geographic | first=Jorge | last=Baracutei Estevez | date=14 October 2019 | url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2019/10/meet-survivors-taino-tribe-paper-genocide/ | access-date=8 November 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017021929/https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2019/10/meet-survivors-taino-tribe-paper-genocide/ | archive-date=17 October 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} Scholars also note that contemporary rural Dominicans retain elements of Ta\u00edno culture: linguistic features, agricultural practices, food ways, [[medicine]], fishing practices, [[technology]], [[architecture]], [[oral history]], and religious views. Often these cultural traits are looked down upon by urbanites as backward, however.{{sfn|Guitar|2000|}} Sixteen \"autosomal\" studies of peoples in the Spanish-speaking Caribbean and its diaspora (mostly Puerto Ricans) have shown that between 10\u201320% of their DNA is indigenous. Some individuals have slightly higher scores and others have lower scores or no indigenous DNA at all.<ref>{{cite book|title=Race, Identity and Indigenous Politics: Puerto Rican Neo-Ta\u00ednos in the Diaspora and the Island|last=Haslip-Viera|first=Gabriel|date=2014|publisher=Latino Studies Press|pages=111\u2013117}}</ref> A recent study of a population in eastern Puerto Rico where the majority of persons tested claimed Ta\u00edno ancestry and pedigree showed that they had 61% mtDNA (distant maternal ancestry) and 0% y-chromosome DNA (distant paternal ancestry) demonstrating as expected that this is a hybrid creole population.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vilar|first=Miguel G.|display-authors=etal|date=July 2014|title=Genetic diversity in Puerto Rico and its implications for the peopling of the island and the Caribbean|journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|volume=155|issue=3|pages=352\u201368|doi=10.1002/ajpa.22569|pmid=25043798}}</ref>\n\nThe ancestors of the Ta\u00edno originated in South America, and the Ta\u00edno culture as documented developed in the Caribbean. Ta\u00edno groups were in conflict with the [[Island Caribs]] of the southern Lesser Antilles. At the time of contact, the Ta\u00edno were divided into several groups. Western Ta\u00edno groups included the [[Lucayans]] of the Bahamas, the [[Ciboney]] of central Cuba, and the inhabitants of Jamaica. The Classic Ta\u00edno lived in Hispaniola and Puerto Rico, while the Eastern Ta\u00edno lived in the northern islands of the Lesser Antilles.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nAt the time of Columbus's arrival in 1492, there were five Ta\u00edno [[chiefdom]]s in Hispaniola, each led by a principal {{lang|tnq|[[Cacique]]}} ([[tribal chief|chief]]), to whom tribute was paid. The Ta\u00edno name for Hispaniola was {{lang|tnq|Ayiti}} (\"land of high mountains\"), which is the source of the name ''Haiti''. Cuba was divided into 29 chiefdoms, many of which have given their name to modern cities, including [[Havana]], [[Bataban\u00f3, Cuba|Bataban\u00f3]], [[Camag\u00fcey]], [[Baracoa]], and [[Bayamo]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PEE9oipDYksC&pg=PA25|title=Art and Archaeology of Pre-Columbian Cuba|first1=Ramon Dacal|last1=Moure|first2=Manuel Rivero De La|last2=Calle|date=15 February 1997|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Pre|accessdate=19 May 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9780822990703|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230131750/https://books.google.com/books?id=PEE9oipDYksC&pg=PA25|archive-date=30 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Ta\u00edno communities ranged from small settlements to larger centers of up to 3,000 people. They may have numbered 2 million at the time of contact,<ref name=Britannica/> and almost 3 million at the end of the 15th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|title=What Became of the Ta\u00edno?|website=Smithsonian|language=en|access-date=2019-10-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014143641/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|archive-date=2019-10-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Columbus was surprised by the civility of the Ta\u00edno people. Columbus stated, \"They will give all that they do possess for anything that is given to them, exchanging things even for bits of broken crockery,\" he noted upon meeting them in the Bahamas in 1492. \"They were very well built, with very handsome bodies and very good faces....They do not carry arms or know them....They should be good servants.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Spanish conquered various Ta\u00edno chiefdoms during the late fifteenth and early sixteenth century. According to [[The Black Legend]] and some contemporary scholars such as [[Andr\u00e9s Res\u00e9ndez]], [[war]]fare and harsh enslavement by the colonists decimated the population.{{sfn|Chrisp|2006|p=34}}<ref name=\"Res\u00e9ndez\">{{cite book|last=Res\u00e9ndez|first=Andr\u00e9s|date=2016|title=The Other Slavery: The Uncovered Story of Indian Enslavement in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z2gpCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PA17#v=onepage&q&f=false|location=|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|page=17|isbn=978-0547640983|author-link=Andr\u00e9s Res\u00e9ndez|access-date=2019-06-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014143643/https://books.google.com/books?id=Z2gpCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PA17#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=2019-10-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Men were forced to work on colonial plantations and gold mines, as a result, there was no Ta\u00edno left to cultivate their own crops and feed their population.<ref name=\":0\" /> Conversely, most scholars believe that European diseases caused the majority of deaths.  A [[smallpox]] epidemic in Hispaniola in 1518\u20131519 killed almost 90% of the surviving Ta\u00edno.{{sfn|Abbot|2010}}<ref>Alfred W. Crosby, ''The Columbian Exchange'' Westport, 1972, p. 47.</ref> The remaining Ta\u00edno were intermarried with Europeans and Africans, and were incorporated into the Spanish colonies. The Ta\u00edno were considered extinct at the end of the century. However, since about 1840, there have been attempts to create a quasi-indigenous Ta\u00edno identity in rural areas of Cuba, the Dominican Republic, and Puerto Rico. This trend accelerated among Puerto Rican communities in the mainland United States in the 1960s.<ref name=Aikhenvald>Alexandra Aikhenvald (2012) ''Languages of the Amazon'', Oxford University Press</ref> At the 2010 U.S. census, 1,098 people in Puerto Rico identified themselves as \"Puerto Rican Indian\", 1,410 identified as \"Spanish American Indian\", and 9,399 identified as \"Ta\u00edno\". In total, 35,856 Puerto Ricans considered themselves Native American.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2010/cph-t/cph-t-6.html|title=American Indian and Alaska Native Tribes in the United States and Puerto Rico: 2010 (CPH-T-6)|last=|first=|date=2010|website=Census.gov|publisher=Census bureau|access-date=September 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004223420/https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2010/cph-t/cph-t-6.html|archive-date=October 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\n[[File:Reconstruction of Taino village, Cuba.JPG|thumb|right|Reconstruction of a Ta\u00edno village in Cuba]]\n\nA direct translation of the word \"Ta\u00edno\" signified \"men of the good\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Rethinking Columbus \u2013 The Ta\u00ednos: \"Men of the Good\"|last=Barreiro|first=Jos\u00e9|publisher=Rethinking Schools, Ltd.|year=1998|isbn=978-0-942961-20-1|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|pages=[https://archive.org/details/rethinkingcolumb0000unse/page/106 106]|url=https://archive.org/details/rethinkingcolumb0000unse/page/106}}</ref> Additionally, the name was used by the indigenous people of Hispaniola to indicate that they were \"relatives\".<ref>Alegr\u00eda, \"Ta\u00ednos\" vol. 1, p. 345.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2019}}  The Ta\u00edno people, or Ta\u00edno culture, has been classified by some authorities as belonging to the Arawak, as their language was considered to belong to the Arawak language family, the languages of which were present throughout the Caribbean, and much of Central and South America.\nThe early ethnohistorian [[Daniel Garrison Brinton]] called the Ta\u00edno people the \"Island Arawak\".<ref name=\"DGB1871\">{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/arawacklanguageo00brinrich |author=Daniel Garrison Brinton |date=1871 |title=The Arawack language of Guiana in its linguistic and ethnological relations |accessdate=22 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160528021215/https://archive.org/details/arawacklanguageo00brinrich |archive-date=28 May 2016 |url-status=live |publisher=Philadelphia, McCalla & Stavely }}</ref> \nNevertheless, contemporary scholars have recognized that the Ta\u00edno had developed a distinct language and culture.\n\nTa\u00edno and Arawak appellations have been used with numerous and contradictory meanings by writers, travelers, historians, linguists, and anthropologists. Often they were used interchangeably; \"Ta\u00edno\" has been applied to the Greater Antillean nation only, or including the Bahamian nations, or adding the [[Leeward Islands]] nations, or all those excluding the Puerto Rican and Leeward nations. Similarly, \"Island Ta\u00edno\" has been used to refer to those living in the [[Windward Islands]] only, to the northern Caribbean inhabitants only, as well as to the population of the entire Caribbean.\n\nModern historians, linguists and anthropologists now hold that the term Ta\u00edno should refer to all the Ta\u00edno/Arawak nations, except for the [[Island Caribs|Caribs]], who are not seen to belong to the same people. Linguists continue to debate whether the Carib language is an Arawakan [[dialect]] or [[creole language]], or perhaps an individual language, with an Arawakan [[pidgin]] used for communication purposes.\n\nRouse classifies as Ta\u00edno all inhabitants of the Greater Antilles (except the western tip of Cuba), the Bahamian [[archipelago]], and the northern Lesser Antilles. He subdivides the Ta\u00edno into three main groups: Classic Ta\u00edno, mostly from Haiti, Puerto Rico, and the Dominican Republic; Western Ta\u00edno, or sub-Ta\u00edno, for population from Jamaica, Cuba (except for the western tip), and the Bahamian archipelago; and Eastern Ta\u00edno for those from the [[Virgin Islands]] to [[Montserrat]].{{sfn|Rouse|1992|p=7}}\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Ta\u00ednos.svg|right|thumb|The Guanahatabey region in relation to Ta\u00edno and [[Island Carib]] groups]]\nTwo schools of thought have emerged regarding the origin of the indigenous people of the Caribbean.\n\n* One group of scholars contends that the ancestors of the Ta\u00edno came from the center of the [[Amazon Basin]], and are related to the [[Yanomama]]. This is indicated by linguistic, cultural and ceramic evidence. They migrated to the [[Orinoco]] valley on the north coast. From there they reached the Caribbean by way of what is now [[Guyana]] and [[Venezuela]] into [[Trinidad]], proceeding along the Lesser Antilles to Cuba and the Bahamian archipelago. Evidence that supports this theory includes the tracing of the ancestral cultures of these people to the Orinoco Valley and their languages to the Amazon Basin.<ref name=Origins>Rouse, pp. 30\u201348.</ref><ref name=\"native\">{{cite journal | date = Aug 2001 | title = Mitochondrial DNA analysis reveals substantial Native American ancestry in Puerto Rico | url = | journal = Hum. Biol. | volume = 73 | issue = 4| pages = 491\u2013511 | pmid = 11512677  | last1 = Mart\u00ednez-Cruzado | first1 = JC | last2 = Toro-Labrador | first2 = G | last3 = Ho-Fung | first3 = V |display-authors=etal | doi=10.1353/hub.2001.0056}}</ref><ref name=\"Madrigal\">{{cite book|last=Lorena Madrigal|first=Madrigal|title=Human biology of Afro-Caribbean populations|publisher=Cambridge University Press, 2006 |page=121|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ddnkIaZRHxEC&pg=PA121|isbn=978-0-521-81931-2|year=2006}}</ref>\n* The alternate theory, known as the circum-Caribbean theory, contends that the ancestors of the Ta\u00edno diffused from the [[Andean Region of Colombia|Colombian Andes]]. [[Julian H. Steward]], who originated this concept, suggests a migration from the Andes to the Caribbean and a parallel migration into [[Central America]] and into the [[Guianas]], Venezuela, and the Amazon Basin of South America.<ref name=Origins/>\n\nTa\u00edno culture as documented is believed to have developed in the Caribbean. The Ta\u00edno creation story says that they emerged from caves in a sacred mountain on present-day Hispaniola.<ref>Rouse, p. 16.</ref> In Puerto Rico, 21st century studies have shown a high proportion of people having [[Amerindian]] [[MtDNA]]. Of the two major [[haplotypes]] found, one does not exist in the Ta\u00edno ancestral group, so other Native American people are also part of this genetic ancestry.<ref name=\"native\"/><ref name=\"Young_2011_Nature\">{{cite journal |last1=Young |first1=Susan |title=Rebuilding the genome of a hidden ethnicity |journal=Nature |date=October 17, 2011 |url=https://www.nature.com/news/2011/111014/full/news.2011.592.html |access-date=2019-01-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901134845/http://www.nature.com/news/2011/111014/full/news.2011.592.html |archive-date=2018-09-01 |url-status=live |doi=10.1038/news.2011.592 }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Duho.jpg|thumb|right|''Dujo'', a wooden ceremonial chair crafted by Ta\u00ednos]]\nTa\u00edno society was divided into two classes: ''naborias'' (commoners) and ''nita\u00ednos'' (nobles). These were governed by male chiefs known as ''[[cacique]]s'', who inherited their position through their mother's noble line. The nita\u00ednos functioned as sub-caciques in villages, overseeing naborias work. Caciques were advised by priests/healers known as ''bohiques''. Caciques enjoyed the privilege of wearing golden pendants called ''guan\u00edn'', living in square ''boh\u00edos,'' instead of the round ones of ordinary villagers, and sitting on wooden stools to be above the guests they received.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmuseo.org/taino/caciques.html |title=Caciques, nobles and their regalia |accessdate=2006-11-09 |website= |publisher=elmuseo.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061009090513/http://elmuseo.org/taino/caciques.html  |archivedate = 2006-10-09}}</ref> Bohiques were extolled for their healing powers and ability to speak with deities. They were consulted and granted the Ta\u00edno permission to engage in important tasks. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe Ta\u00edno had a [[matrilineal]] system of [[kinship]], descent, and inheritance. When a male heir was not present, the inheritance or succession would go to the oldest male child of the sister of the deceased. The Ta\u00edno had [[Avunculism|avunculocal]] post-marital residence, meaning a newly married couple lived in the household of the maternal uncle. He was more important in the lives of his niece's children than their biological father; the uncle introduced the boys to men's societies. Some Ta\u00edno practiced [[polygamy]]. Men, and sometimes women, might have two or three spouses. A few caciques had as many as 30 wives.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nThe Ta\u00edno women were highly skilled in agriculture. The people depended on it, but the men also fished and hunted. They made fishing nets and ropes from [[cotton]] and [[Palm tree|palm]]. Their dugout [[canoe]]s (''kanoa'') were made in various sizes, which could hold from 2 to 150 people. An average-sized canoe would hold about 15\u201320 people. They used bows and arrows for hunting, and developed the use of poisons on their arrowheads.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nTa\u00edno women commonly wore their hair with bangs in front and longer in back, and they occasionally wore gold jewelry, paint, and/or shells. Ta\u00edno men and unmarried women were usually naked. After marriage, women wore a small cotton apron, called a ''nagua''.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Beding|editor1-first=Silvio|title=The Christopher Columbus Encyclopedia|date=1002|publisher=Palgrave MacMillan|isbn=978-1-349-12573-9|page=346|edition=ebook|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gmmMCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA346&dq=Ta%C3%ADno+sometimes+wore+nothing%7Cnaked#v=onepage&q=Ta%C3%ADno%20sometimes%20wore%20nothing%7Cnaked&f=false|accessdate=11 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412063124/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gmmMCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA346&dq=Ta%C3%ADno+sometimes+wore+nothing%7Cnaked&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFk9z24JzTAhUJC8AKHZl5ALkQ6AEIOTAE#v=onepage&q=Ta%C3%ADno%20sometimes%20wore%20nothing%7Cnaked&f=false#v=onepage&q=Ta%C3%ADno%20sometimes%20wore%20nothing%7Cnaked&f=false|archive-date=2017-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe Ta\u00edno lived in settlements called ''yucayeques'', which varied in size depending on the location. Those in Puerto Rico and Hispaniola were the largest, and those in the Bahamas were the smallest. In the center of a typical village was a central plaza, used for various social activities such as games, festivals, religious [[ritual]]s, and public ceremonies. These plazas had many shapes, including oval, rectangular, narrow, and elongated. Ceremonies where the deeds of the ancestors were celebrated, called ''areitos'', were performed here.<ref name=Rouse15>Rouse, p. 15.</ref>\n\nOften, the general population lived in large circular buildings (''bohios''), constructed with wooden poles, woven straw, and palm leaves. These houses, built surrounding the central plaza, could hold 10\u201315 families each.<ref>Alegr\u00eda, \"Tainos\" p. 346.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2019}} The cacique and his family lived in rectangular buildings (''caney'') of similar construction, with wooden porches. Ta\u00edno home furnishings included cotton hammocks (''hamaca''), sleeping and sitting mats made of palms, wooden chairs ([[dujo]] or duho) with woven seats, platforms, and cradles for children.\n\n[[File:Parco Cerimoniale Indigeno di Caguana.jpg|thumb|left|Caguana Ceremonial ball court (''batey''), outlined with stones]]\nThe Ta\u00edno played a ceremonial ball game called ''[[batey (game)|batey]]''. Opposing teams had 10 to 30 players per team and used a solid [[rubber]] ball. Normally, the teams were composed of men, but occasionally women played the game as well.<ref name=Alegr\u00eda1951p348>Alegr\u00eda (1951), p.348.</ref> The Classic Ta\u00edno played in the village's center plaza or on especially designed rectangular ball courts called ''batey''. Games on the ''batey'' are believed to have been used for conflict resolution between communities. The most elaborate ball courts are found at chiefdom boundaries.<ref name=Rouse15/> Often, chiefs made wagers on the possible outcome of a game.<ref name=Alegr\u00eda1951p348/>\n\nTa\u00edno spoke an [[Arawakan language]] and used an early form of writing [[Proto-writing]] in the form of [[petroglyph]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tainoage.com/meaning.html|title=Taino Symbol Meanings|website=Tainoage.com|accessdate=19 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705233343/http://www.tainoage.com/meaning.html|archive-date=2018-07-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSome words that they used, such as ''barbacoa'' (\"barbecue\"), ''hamaca'' (\"hammock\"), ''kanoa'' (\"canoe\"), ''tabaco'' (\"tobacco\"), ''[[cassava|yuca]]'', ''batata'' (\"sweet potato\"), and ''[[jurac\u00e1n]]'' (\"hurricane\"), have been incorporated into Spanish and English.\n\nFor warfare, the men made wooden war clubs, which they called a ''[[macana]].'' It was about one inch thick and was similar to the [[coco macaque]].\n\n== Cacicazgo/society ==\n[[File:Smithsonian 1901 map of Puerto Rico caciques.png|300px|right|Smithsonian 1901 map of Puerto Rico caciques]]\nThe Ta\u00edno were the most culturally advanced of the [[Arawak]] Group to settle in what is now [[Puerto Rico]].<ref name=Wagenheim12>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico: an interpretive history from pre-columbian times to 1900|last=Jimenez de Wagenheim, Olga|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761225|location=|page=12|oclc=1025952187}}</ref> Individuals and [[kinship]] groups that previously had some prestige and rank in the [[tribe]] began to occupy the hierarchical position that would give way to the ''[[cacicazgo]]''.<ref name=enciclopediapr>{{Cite web|url=https://enciclopediapr.org/encyclopedia/el-desarrollo-del-cacicazgo-en-las-sociedades-tardias-de-puerto-rico/|website=enciclopediapr.org|access-date=2019-05-10|title=El desarrollo del cacicazgo en las sociedades tard\u00edas de Puerto Rico -|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527232443/https://enciclopediapr.org/encyclopedia/el-desarrollo-del-cacicazgo-en-las-sociedades-tardias-de-puerto-rico/|archive-date=2019-05-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The Ta\u00edno founded [[Human settlement|settlements]] around [[village]]s and organized their chiefdoms, or ''cacicazgos'', into a confederation.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico : an interpretive history from pre-Columbian times to 1900|last=Wagenheim, Olga Jim\u00e9nez de|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761217|location=Princeton, N.J.|pages=12|oclc=37457914}}</ref> The Taino society, as described by the chroniclers, was composed of four social classes: the ''[[cacique]]'', the ''nita\u00ednos'', the ''behiques,'' and the ''naborias''.<ref name=enciclopediapr/> According to archeological evidence, the Ta\u00edno islands were able to support an enormous number of people for approximately 1,500 years.<ref name=Rethinking>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H7FMDztgSfkC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rethinking Columbus: The Next 500 Years|last=Bigelow|first=Bill|last2=Peterson|first2=Bob|date=1998|publisher=Rethinking Schools|isbn=9780942961201|language=en}}</ref> Every individual living in the Ta\u00edno society had a task to do. For the Ta\u00ednos, it was very important that everyone living in their islands ate properly.<ref name=Rethinking/> They followed a very efficient nature harvesting and agricultural production system.<ref name=Rethinking/> Either people were hunting, searching for food, or doing other productive tasks.<ref name=Rethinking/>\n\nTribal groups settled in villages under a [[Tribal chief|chieftain]], known as ''cacique'', or ''cacica'' if the ruler was a woman. Many women the [[Spaniards]] called ''cacicas'' were not always rulers in their own right, but were mistakenly recognized as such because they were the [[Wife|wives]] of caciques.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}} Chiefs were chosen from the ''nita\u00ednos'' and generally obtained their power from the [[Matrilineality|maternal]] line. Male rulers were more likely to be succeeded by his sister's children than his own, unless their mother's lineage allowed them to succeed in their own right.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico: an interpretive history from pre-columbian times to 1900|last=Jimenez de Wagenheim, Olga|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761225|location=|pages=12\u201313|oclc=1025952187}}</ref>\n\nThe chiefs had both temporal and spiritual functions. They were expected to ensure the welfare of the tribe and to protect it from harm from both natural and supernatural forces.<ref name=Wagenheim13>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico: an interpretive history from pre-columbian times to 1900|last=Jimenez de Wagenheim, Olga|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761225|location=|page=13|oclc=1025952187}}</ref> They were also expected to direct and manage the production process. The caciques power came from the number of villages he controlled and was based on a network of alliances related to [[family]], matrimonial and ceremonial ties. These alliances showed unity of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] communities in a territory<ref name=\"Smithsonian 1901\">{{cite web | title=Bulletin : Smithsonian Institution. Bureau of American Ethnology | website=Internet Archive | date=23 October 1901 | url=https://archive.org/details/bulletin14341948smit | access-date=7 November 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518212909/https://archive.org/details/bulletin14341948smit | archive-date=18 May 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> that would get together as a defensive strategy to face external threats, like the attacks by the [[Island Caribs|Caribs]] on communities in Puerto Rico.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rodr\u00edguez Ramos|first=Reniel|chapter=Current Perspectives in the Precolonial Archaeology of Puerto Rico|date=2019-02-25|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199366439|doi=10.1093/acrefore/9780199366439.013.620|title=Oxford Research Encyclopedia of Latin American History}}</ref> [[Polygamy]] allowed the cacique to have women in different localities, thus extending his power. The cacique carried, as a symbol of his [[hierarchy]], a [[guan\u00edn]] of South American origin made of an alloy of gold and copper. This symbolized the first Ta\u00edno mythical cacique Anacacuya that means star of the center or central spirit. In addition to the guan\u00edn, the cacique used other artifacts and adornments that served to identify it. Some examples are tunics of [[cotton]] and [[feather]]s, crowns and masks or \"guaizas\" of cotton with feathers; colored stones, shells or gold;cotton woven belts; and necklaces of snail beads or stones with small masks of gold or other material.<ref name=enciclopediapr/>\n\n[[File:Copia de Cacicazgos de la Hispaniola.png|thumb|275x275px|Cacicazgos of Hispaniola|alt=|left]]\nUnder the ''cacique'' there social organization was composed of two tiers: The ''nita\u00ednos'' at the top and the ''naborias'' at the bottom.<ref name=Wagenheim12/> The ''nita\u00ednos'' were considered the [[Nobility|nobles]] of the tribes. They were the [[warrior]]s and family of the cacique.<ref name=proyectosalonhogar>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proyectosalonhogar.com/enciclopedia_ilustrada/indios_tainos.htm|title=Indios Tainos|website=www.proyectosalonhogar.com|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114051729/http://www.proyectosalonhogar.com/enciclopedia_ilustrada/indios_Tainos.htm|archive-date=2016-01-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Advisers that assisted in the mundane matters of assigning and supervising communal work, planting and [[harvest]]ing crops, and keeping peace among the village's inhabitants, were selected from among the ''nita\u00ednos''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Puerto Rico: an interpretive history from pre-columbian times to 1900|last=Jimenez de Wagenheim, Olga|date=1998|publisher=Markus Wiener Publishers|isbn=1558761225|oclc=1025952187}}</ref> The ''naborias'' were simply working peasants of the lower class.<ref name=proyectosalonhogar/>\n\nThe ''behiques'' were [[priest]]s who represented religious beliefs.<ref name=proyectosalonhogar/> Behiques dealt with negotiating with angry or indifferent gods as the accepted lords of the spiritual world. The behiques were expected to communicate with the [[Deity|gods]], to soothe them when they were angry, and to intercede on the tribe's behalf. It was their duty to cure the sick, heal the wounded, and interpret the will of the gods in ways that would satisfy the expectations of the tribe. Before carrying out these functions, the behiques performed certain cleansing and purifying [[ritual]]s, such as fasting for several days and inhaling sacred tobacco snuff.<ref name=Wagenheim13/>\n\n==Food and agriculture==\n\n[[File:Manihot esculenta dsc07325.jpg|thumb|right|[[Cassava]], starchy (''yuca'') roots, the Ta\u00ednos' main crop]]\nTa\u00edno staples included vegetables, fruit, meat, and fish. There were no large animals native to the Caribbean, but they captured and ate small animals, such as [[hutia]]s and other mammals, [[earthworms]], [[lizards]], [[turtles]], and [[birds]]. [[Manatees]] were speared and fish were caught in nets, speared, trapped in [[weir]]s, or caught with hook and line. Wild [[parrots]] were decoyed with domesticated birds, and [[iguanas]] were taken from trees and other [[vegetation]]. The Ta\u00edno stored live animals until they were ready to be consumed: fish and turtles were stored in weirs, hutias and dogs were stored in corrals.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.13\">Rouse, p. 13.</ref>\n[[File:Piedra Escrita in Jayuya, Puerto Rico.jpg|thumb|Piedra Escrita on [[R\u00edo Saliente|River Saliente]] in Jayuya, Puerto Rico]]\n\nBecause of the lack of large game, the Ta\u00edno people became very skilled [[fishermen]]. One method was to hook a [[remora]], also known as a suckerfish, to a line secured to a canoe and wait for the fish to attach itself to a larger fish or even a sea turtle. Once this happened, some of the Ta\u00edno would dive into the water to assist in retrieving the catch. Another method used by the Ta\u00ednos was to shred the stems and roots of poisonous [[senna (plant)|senna]] plants and throw them into nearby streams or rivers. Upon eating the bait, the fish were stunned, allowing boys time enough to collect them. This toxin did not affect the edibility of the fish. The Ta\u00edno also collected [[mussel]]s and [[oyster]]s in shallow waters within the exposed [[mangrove]] roots.<ref name=\"Jacobs1992\">{{cite book|author=Francine Jacobs|title=The Tainos: The People who Welcomed Columbus|url=https://archive.org/details/tainospeoplewhow00jaco|url-access=registration|year=1992|publisher=G.P. Putnam's Sons|isbn=978-0-399-22116-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/tainospeoplewhow00jaco/page/26 26]}}</ref> Some young boys hunted waterfowl from flocks that \"darkened the sun\", according to Christopher Columbus.<ref name=Rethinking/>\n\nTa\u00edno groups in the more developed islands, such as Puerto Rico, Hispaniola, and Jamaica, relied more on agriculture (farming and other jobs). Fields for important [[root crops]], such as the staple [[Cassava|yuca]], were prepared by heaping up mounds of soil, called ''conucos''. This improved soil drainage and fertility as well as delaying erosion, allowed for longer storage of crops in the ground. Less important crops such as corn were raised in simple clearings created by [[slash and burn]] technique. Typically, ''conucos'' were three feet high and nine feet in circumference and were arranged in rows.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.12\">Rouse, p.12.</ref> The primary root crop was yuca or [[cassava]], a woody [[shrub]] cultivated for its edible and [[starch]]y [[tuberous root]]. It was planted using a ''coa'', a kind of [[hoe (tool)|hoe]] made completely from wood. Women processed the poisonous variety of cassava by squeezing it to extract the toxic juices. Then they would grind the roots into flour for baking bread. ''Batata'' ([[sweet potato]]) was the next most important root crop.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.12\"/>\n\nContrary to mainland practices, corn was not ground into flour and baked into bread, but was cooked and eaten off the cob. Corn bread becomes moldy faster than cassava bread in the high humidity of the Caribbean. Corn also was used to make an alcoholic beverage known as [[chicha]].<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://www.academia.edu/423889 |last=Duke |first=Guy S. |title=Identity Crisis: Archaeological Perspectives on Social Identity |chapter=Continuity, Cultural Dynamics, and Alcohol: The Reinterpretation of Identity through Chicha in the Andes |website=Academia.edu |access-date=2017-12-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210124529/http://www.academia.edu/423889/Continuity_Cultural_Dynamics_and_Alcohol_The_Reinterpretation_of_Identity_through_Chicha_in_the_Andes |archive-date=2018-12-10 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Ta\u00edno grew [[Squash (fruit)|squash]], [[beans]], [[capsicum|peppers]], [[peanut]]s, and [[pineapple]]s. [[Tobacco]], [[calabash]]es (West Indian pumpkins), and [[cotton]] were grown around the houses. Other fruits and vegetables, such as [[Arecaceae|palm nuts]], [[guava]]s, and ''[[Zamia]]'' roots, were collected from the wild.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.12\"/>\n\n==Spirituality==\n[[File:Taino - Zemi - Walters 20056 - Left Side.jpg|thumb|Ta\u00edno zem\u00ed sculpture<br />''[[Walters Art Museum]]'']]\nTa\u00edno spirituality centered on the worship of [[Zemi|zem\u00eds]]. A zem\u00ed is a spirit or ancestor. The major Ta\u00edno zemis are [[Atabey (goddess)|Atabey]] and her son, [[Y\u00facahu]]. Atabey, was the zemi of the [[moon]], fresh waters, and fertility. Other names for her include Atabei, Atabeyra, Atabex, and Guimazoa.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} The Ta\u00ednos of Quisqueya (Dominican Republic) called her son, \"Yucah\u00fa Bagua Maorocot\u00ed\", which means \"White Yuca, great and powerful as the sea and the mountains\". He was the spirit of cassava, the zemi of cassava&nbsp;\u2013 the Ta\u00ednos' main crop&nbsp;\u2013 and the sea.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nGuabancex was the non-nurturing aspect of the zemi Atabey who had control over natural disasters. She is identified as the goddess of the hurricanes or as the zemi of storms. Guabancex had twin sons: Guataub\u00e1, a messenger who created hurricane winds, and Coatrisquie, who created [[flood]]waters.<ref>Rouse, p. 121.</ref>\n\nIguanabo\u00edna was the goddess of the good weather. She also had twin sons: Boinayel, the messenger of rain, y Marohu, the spirit of clear skies.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mitolog\u00eda y religi\u00f3n de los ta\u00ednos|last=Robiu-Lamarche|first=Sebasti\u00e1n|publisher=Edit. Punto y Coma|year=2006|isbn=0-9746236-4-4|location=San Juan, Puerto Rico|pages=69, 84}}</ref>\n\nThe minor Ta\u00edno zemis related to the growing of cassava, the process of life, creation, and death. Baibrama was a minor zemi worshiped for his assistance in growing cassava and curing people from its poisonous juice. Boinayel and his twin brother M\u00e1rohu were the zemis of rain and fair weather, respectively.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.119\">Rouse, p. 119.</ref>\n\nMaquetaurie Guayaba or Maketaori Guayaba was the zemi of Coaybay or Coabey, the land of the dead. Opiyelguabir\u00e1n', a dog-shaped zemi, watched over the dead. Demin\u00e1n Caracaracol, a male cultural hero from whom the Ta\u00edno believed themselves to be descended, was worshipped as a zem\u00ed.<ref name=\"Rouse, p.119\"/> Macocael was a cultural hero worshipped as a zemi, who had failed to guard the mountain from which [[human beings]] arose. He was punished by being turned into stone, or a bird, a [[frog]], or a reptile, depending on interpretation of the [[myth]]. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[File:Lombards Museum 053.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Zem\u00ed, a physical object housing a zemi, spirit, or ancestor<br />''Lombards Museum'']]\nZem\u00ed was also the name the people gave to their physical representations of the Zemis, whether objects or drawings. They were made in many forms and materials and have been found in a variety of settings. The majority of zem\u00eds were crafted from wood, but stone, [[bone]], [[Seashell|shell]], [[pottery]], and cotton were used as well.<ref>Rouse, pp. 13, 118.</ref> Zem\u00ed [[petroglyph]]s were carved on rocks in streams, ball courts, and on [[stalagmite]]s in caves. ''Cem\u00ed'' [[pictograph]]s were found on secular objects such as pottery, and on [[tattoos]]. Yucah\u00fa, the zemi of cassava, was represented with a three-pointed zem\u00ed, which could be found in ''conucos'' to increase the yield of cassava. Wood and stone zem\u00eds have been found in [[caves]] in Hispaniola and Jamaica.<ref>Rouse, p. 118.</ref> ''Cem\u00eds'' are sometimes represented by [[toads]], turtles, fish, [[snakes]], and various abstract and human-like faces. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Taino. Cohoba Spoon, 1200-1500.jpg|thumbnail|right|Cohoba Spoon, 1200\u20131500<br />''[[Brooklyn Museum]]'']]\n[[File:Petroglyph at Caguana.jpg|thumb|right|Rock [[petroglyph]] overlaid with chalk in the Caguana Indigenous Ceremonial Center in Utuado, Puerto Rico]]\nSome zem\u00eds are accompanied by a small table or tray, which is believed to be a receptacle for [[hallucinogen]]ic [[Herbal smokeless tobacco|snuff]] called ''[[cohoba]],'' prepared from the beans of a species of ''[[Piptadenia]]'' tree. These trays have been found with ornately carved snuff tubes. Before certain ceremonies, Ta\u00ednos would purify themselves, either by inducing vomiting (with a swallowing stick) or by [[fasting]].<ref>Rouse, p. 14.</ref> After communal bread was served, first to the zem\u00ed, then to the cacique, and then to the common people, the people would sing the village epic to the accompaniment of [[maraca]] and other instruments.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nOne Ta\u00edno [[oral tradition]] explains that the Sun and Moon come out of caves. Another story tells of people who once lived in caves and only came out at night, because it was believed that the Sun would transform them. The Ta\u00edno believed they were descended from the union of the cultural hero Demin\u00e1n Caracaracol and a female turtle.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} The origin of the oceans is described in the story of a huge flood that occurred when a father murdered his son (who was about to murder the father). The father put his son's bones into a [[gourd]] or [[calabash]]. When the bones turned into fish, the gourd broke, and all the water of the world came pouring out. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nTa\u00ednos believed that Jupias, the souls of the dead, would go to Coaybay, the underworld, and there they rest by day. At night they would assume the form of bats and eat the [[guava]] fruit. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Spaniards and Ta\u00edno==\nColumbus and the crew of his ship were the first [[European ethnic groups|Europeans]] to encounter the Ta\u00edno people, as they landed in The Bahamas on October 12, 1492. After their first interaction, Columbus described the Ta\u00ednos as a physically tall, well-proportioned people, with a noble and kind personality.\n\nIn [[Christopher Columbus's journal|his diary]], Columbus wrote:\n{{quote|They traded with us and gave us everything they had, with good will&nbsp;... they took great delight in pleasing us&nbsp;... They are very gentle and without knowledge of what is evil; nor do they murder or steal...Your highness may believe that in all the world there can be no better people&nbsp;... They love their neighbours as themselves, and they have the sweetest talk in the world, and are gentle and always laughing.<ref>Kirkpatrick Sale, ''The Conquest of Paradise'', p. 100, {{ISBN|0-333-57479-6}}</ref>}}\n\nAt this time, the neighbors of the Ta\u00edno were the [[Guanahatabey]]s in the western tip of Cuba, the Island-Caribs in the Lesser Antilles from [[Guadeloupe]] to [[Grenada]], and the [[Calusa]] and [[Ais (tribe)|Ais]] nations of [[Florida]]. Guanahan\u00ed was the Ta\u00edno name for the island that Columbus renamed as ''San Salvador'' (Spanish for \"Holy Savior\"). Columbus called the Ta\u00edno \"Indians\", a reference that has grown to encompass all the indigenous peoples of the [[Western Hemisphere]]. A group of Ta\u00edno people accompanied Columbus on his return voyage to Spain.<ref>{{cite book |title=North American Exploration: A New World Disclosed. Volume: 1 |author=Allen, John Logan |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |year=1997 |page=13}}</ref>\n\nOn Columbus' second voyage to their culture, he began to require tribute from the Ta\u00edno in Hispaniola. According to [[Kirkpatrick Sale]], each adult over 14 years of age was expected to deliver a hawks bell full of gold every three months, or when this was lacking, twenty-five pounds of spun cotton. If this tribute was not brought, the Spanish cut off the hands of the Ta\u00edno and left them to bleed to death.<ref>Kirkpatrick Sale, \"The Conquest of Paradise\", p. 155, {{ISBN|0-333-57479-6}}</ref> These cruel practices inspired many revolts by the Ta\u00edno and campaigns against the Spanish \u2014 some being successful, some not.\n\nIn 1511, several caciques in Puerto Rico, such as [[Ag\u00fceyban\u00e1 II]], [[Arasibo]], [[Hayuya]], [[Jumacao]], [[Urayo\u00e1n]], [[Guarionex]], and [[Orocobix]], allied with the Carib and tried to oust the Spaniards. The revolt was suppressed by the Indio-Spanish forces of Governor [[Juan Ponce de Le\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=three%20thousand%20islanders&f=false | accessdate=31 July 2010 | page=143| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> [[Hatuey]], a Ta\u00edno chieftain who had fled from Hispaniola to Cuba with 400 natives to unite the Cuban natives, was burned at the stake on February 2, 1512.\n\nIn Hispaniola, a Ta\u00edno chieftain named [[Enriquillo]] mobilized more than 3,000 Ta\u00edno in a successful rebellion in the 1520s. These Ta\u00edno were accorded land and a charter from the royal administration. Despite the small Spanish military presence in the region, they often used diplomatic divisions and, with help from powerful native allies, controlled most of the region.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=water%20extreme%20heat&f=false | accessdate=10 July 2010 | page=132| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=onepage&q=concluding&f=false | accessdate=10 July 2010 | page=199| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> In exchange for a seasonal salary, religious and language education, the Ta\u00edno were required to work for Spanish and Indian land owners. This system of labor was part of the ''[[encomienda]]''.\n\n==Women==\n\nTa\u00edno society was based on a [[Matrilineality|matrilineal]] system and descent was traced through the mother. Women lived in village groups containing their children. The men lived separately. Because of this Ta\u00edno women had extensive control over their lives, their co-villagers, and their bodies.<ref>Saunders, Nicholas J. Peoples of the Caribbean: An Encyclopedia of Archeology and Traditional Culture. Santa Barbara, CA: ABC-CLIO, 2005. Web.</ref> Since they lived separately from men, they were able to decide when they wanted to participate in sexual contact. This social organization partially shaped the views of [[conquistador]]s who came in contact with Ta\u00edno culture. They reportedly perceived women as \"macha women\" who had strong control over the men. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nAlthough unclear, most historical evidence suggests that Ta\u00edno gender roles were non exclusive regarding most of the activities in their community. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nTa\u00edno women played an important role in intercultural interaction between [[Spaniards]] and the Ta\u00edno people. When Ta\u00edno men were away fighting intervention from other groups, women assumed the roles of primary food producers or ritual specialists.<ref>Dale, Corrine H., and J. H. E. Paine. Women on the Edge: Ethnicity and Gender in Short Stories by American Women. New York: Garland Pub., 1999. Web.</ref> Women seem to have  participated in all levels of the Ta\u00edno political hierarchy, occupying roles as high up as being ''[[cacique|cazicas]]''.<ref>Taylor, Patrick, and Frederick I. Case. The Encyclopedia of Caribbean Religions Volume 1: A-L; Volume 2: M-Z. Baltimore: U of Illinois, 2015. Web. Chapter title Ta\u00ednos.</ref> Potentially, this meant Ta\u00edno women could make important choices for the village and could assign tasks to tribe members.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Deagan | first1 = Kathleen | year = 2004 | title = Reconsidering Taino Social Dynamics after Spanish Conquest: Gender and Class in Culture Contact Studies | url = | journal = American Antiquity | volume = 69 | issue = 4| pages = 597\u2013626 | doi=10.2307/4128440|jstor=4128440}}</ref> There is evidence that suggests that the women who were wealthiest among the tribe collected crafted goods that they would then use for trade or as gifts.\n\nDespite women being seemingly independent in Ta\u00edno society, during the era of contact Spaniards took Ta\u00edno women as an exchange item, putting them in a non-autonomous position. Dr. Chanca, a physician who traveled with [[Christopher Columbus]], reported in a letter that Spaniards took as many women as they possibly could and kept them as [[Concubinage|concubines]].<ref>Hotep, Amon. \"Women.\" Race and History.com | TAINO | Women. N.p., n.d. Web. 29 Nov. 2016.</ref> Some sources report that, despite women being free and powerful before the contact era, they became the first commodities up for Spaniards to trade, or often, steal. This marked the beginning of a lifetime of kidnapping and abuse of Ta\u00edno women.<ref>Sloan, Kathryn A. Women's Roles in Latin America and the Caribbean. Santa Barbara, CA: Greenwood, 2011. Web.</ref>\n\n==Depopulation==\n\nEarly population estimates of Hispaniola, probably the most populous island inhabited by Ta\u00ednos, range from 100,000 to 1,000,000 people. The maximum estimates for Jamaica and Puerto Rico are 600,000 people.{{sfn|Rouse|1992|p=7}} The Spanish priest and defender of the Ta\u00edno, [[Bartolom\u00e9 de las Casas]] (who had lived in [[Santo Domingo]]), wrote in his 1561 multi-volume ''History of the Indies'':<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.interamerdeminst.org/H8.html|title= Endless War of Domination|accessdate= 2007-10-02|work= Student-Employee Assistance Program Against Chemical Dependency|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071016185314/http://interamerdeminst.org/H8.html|archivedate= 2007-10-16}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|There were 60,000 people living on this island [when I arrived in 1508], including the Indians; so that from 1494 to 1508, over three million people had perished from war, [[slavery]] and the mines. Who in future generations will believe this?}}\n\nResearchers today doubt Las Casas' figures for the pre-contact levels of the Ta\u00edno population, considering them an exaggeration. For example, Anderson C\u00f3rdova estimates a maximum of 500,000 people inhabiting the island.<ref>{{cite book |author=Karen Anderson C\u00f3rdova |title=Hispaniola and Puerto Rico: Indian Acculturation and Heterogeneity, 1492\u20131550 |year=1990 |publisher=University Microfilms International |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan |type=PhD dissertation|id= }}</ref> They had no resistance to [[Old World]] diseases, notably [[smallpox]].<ref>Citation Needed</ref> The ''[[encomienda]]'' system brought many Ta\u00edno to work in the fields and mines in exchange for Spanish [[civil disorder|protection]],<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=onepage&q=begged&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=112| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> [[Spanish language|education]], and a seasonal salary.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=cheerfully&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=182| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> Under the pretense of searching for gold and other materials,<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=columbus%20rapacity&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=111| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> many Spaniards took advantage of the regions now under control of the ''[[Indian auxiliaries|anaborios]]'' and Spanish ''encomenderos'' to exploit the native population by seizing their [[land]] and [[wealth]]. Historian [[David Stannard]] characterizes the encomienda as a genocidal system which \"had driven many millions of native peoples in Central and South America to early and agonizing deaths.\"<ref>{{cite book |last= Stannard|first=David E.|date=1993|title=American Holocaust: The Conquest of the New World|url=https://archive.org/details/americanholocaus00stan|url-access= registration|location= |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/americanholocaus00stan/page/139 139] |isbn=978-0195085570|author-link=David Stannard}}</ref> It would take some time before the Ta\u00edno revolted against their oppressors \u2014 both Indian and Spanish alike \u2014 and many military campaigns before [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Charles V]] eradicated the ''encomienda'' system as a form of slavery.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=snippet&q=three%20thousand&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=143| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Columbus and Las Casas: the conquest and Christianization of America, 1492\u20131566 | author=David M. Traboulay | url=https://books.google.com/?id=7Jmi4Wb1DdsC&pg=PA44&dq=enriquillo+revolt#v=onepage&q=enriquillo%20revolt&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=44| isbn=9780819196422 | year=1994 }}</ref>\n\nDiseases obviously had a lot to do with the decimation of the indigenous population, but forced labor was also one of the chief reasons as to why the population decimated.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} The first man to introduce this forced labor among the Ta\u00ednos was leader of the European Colonization of Puerto Rico, Ponce de Le\u00f3n.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} This forced labor eventually led to the Ta\u00edno rebellions, in which the Spaniards responded with violent military expeditions known as \"cabalgadas\".{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} The purpose of the military expedition was to capture the indigenous peoples.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} This violence by the Spaniards was a reason why there was a decline in the Ta\u00edno population since it forced many of these people to emigrate.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn thirty years, between 80% and 90% of the Ta\u00edno population died.<ref>\"La trag\u00e9die des Ta\u00efnos\", in ''[[L'Histoire]]'' n\u00b0322, July\u2013August 2007, p. 16.</ref> Because of the increased number of people (Spanish) on the island, there was a higher demand for food. Ta\u00edno cultivation was converted to Spanish methods. In hopes of frustrating the Spanish, some Ta\u00ednos refused to plant or harvest their crops. The supply of food became so low in 1495 and 1496 that some 50,000 died from the severity of the famine.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=onepage&q=50%2C000&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=108| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref> Historians have determined that the massive decline was due more to infectious disease outbreaks than any warfare or direct attacks.<ref>{{cite book | title=De Orbe Novo, the Eight Decades of Peter Martyr D'Anghera | author= Anghiera Pietro Martire D'| url=https://books.google.com/?id=e7hU_LePtIQC&pg=PA122&dq=guarionex+revolt#v=onepage&q=thirty&f=false | accessdate=21 July 2010 | page=160| isbn= 9781113147608| date= July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Arthur C. Aufderheide|author2=Conrado Rodr\u00edguez-Mart\u00edn|author3=Odin Langsjoen|title=The Cambridge encyclopedia of human paleopathology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qubTdDk1H3IC|year=1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-55203-5|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=qubTdDk1H3IC&pg=PA204 204]|access-date=2016-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202055608/https://books.google.com/books?id=qubTdDk1H3IC|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref> By 1507 their numbers had shrunk to 60,000. Scholars believe that [[pandemic|epidemic]] disease ([[smallpox]], [[influenza]], [[measles]], and [[typhus]]) was an overwhelming cause of the population decline of the indigenous people,<ref name=Watts>{{cite book|last=Watts|first=Sheldon|title=Disease and medicine in world history|year=2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-27816-4|pages=86, 91|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nc9Aq8HOVaEC&pg=PA86|access-date=2016-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202055608/https://books.google.com/books?id=Nc9Aq8HOVaEC&pg=PA86|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref> and also attributed a \"large number of Ta\u00edno deaths...to the continuing bondage systems\" that existed.<ref name=Schimmer>{{cite web|last=Schimmer|first=Russell|title=Puerto Rico|url=http://www.yale.edu/gsp/colonial/puerto-rico/index.html|work=Genocide Studies Program|publisher=Yale University|access-date=2011-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110908234849/http://www.yale.edu/gsp/colonial/puerto-rico/index.html|archive-date=2011-09-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Raudzens>{{cite book|last=Raudzens|first=George|title=Technology, Disease, and Colonial Conquests, Sixteenth to Eighteenth Centuries|year=2003|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-0-391-04206-3|pages=41|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_PFSc4kCyxcC&pg=PA41|access-date=2016-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202055608/https://books.google.com/books?id=_PFSc4kCyxcC&pg=PA41|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Academics, such as historian [[Andr\u00e9s Res\u00e9ndez]] of the [[University of California, Davis]], assert that disease alone does not explain the total destruction of indigenous populations of Hispaniola. While the populations of Europe rebounded following the devastating population decline associated with the [[Black Death]], there was no such rebound for the indigenous populations of the Caribbean. He concludes that, even though the Spanish were aware of deadly diseases such as smallpox, there is no mention of them in the New World until 1519, meaning perhaps they didn't spread as fast as initially believed, and that unlike Europeans, the indigenous populations were subjected to slavery, exploitation and forced labor in gold and silver mines on an enormous scale.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-native-american-slavery-20160505-snap-story.html|title=The new book 'The Other Slavery' will make you rethink American history|last=Treuer|first=David|date=May 13, 2016|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=June 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623103420/https://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-native-american-slavery-20160505-snap-story.html|archive-date=June 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Res\u00e9ndez says that \"slavery has emerged as a major killer\" of the indigenous people of the Caribbean.<ref name=\"Res\u00e9ndez\"/> Anthropologist [[Jason Hickel]] of the [[London School of Economics]] estimates that a third of indigenous workers died every six months from lethal forced labor in these mines.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hickel|first=Jason|date=2018 |title=The Divide: A Brief Guide to Global Inequality and its Solutions|url= |location= |publisher=Windmill Books|page=70 |isbn=978-1786090034}}</ref>\n\n== Ta\u00edno descendants today ==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{essay-like|date=December 2019}}\n{{tone|date=December 2019}}\n{{POV section|date=December 2019}}\n}}\nHistories of the Caribbean commonly describe the Taino as extinct, killed off by disease, slavery, and war with the Spaniards. Some present-day residents of the Caribbean self-identify as Taino, and claim that Taino culture and identity have survived into the present.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/what-became-of-the-taino-73824867/|title=What Became of the Ta\u00edno?|last=Poole|first=Robert M.|date=October 2011|work=Smithsonian|access-date=13 December 2019}}</ref> Groups advocating this point of view are known as Neo-Ta\u00ednos, and are established in the Puerto Rican communities located in New Jersey and New York, as well. A few Neo-Ta\u00edno groups are pushing not only for recognition, but respect for their cultural assets.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Curet|first=Antonio L.|date=Spring 2015|title=Indigenous Revival, Indigeneity, and the J\u00edbaro in Borik\u00e9n|url=|journal=Centro Journal|volume=27|pages=206\u2013247|via=}}</ref>\n\nA genetic study published in 2018 provided some evidence of a present-day Caribbean population being related to the Ta\u00ednos. DNA was extracted from a tooth of a 1,000 year old female skeleton found in a cave in [[Lucaya, Bahamas]], and the genetic results show that she is most closely related to present-day Arawakan speakers from northern South America. The study's authors write that this demonstrates continuity between pre-contact populations and present-day Latino populations in the Caribbean.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Origins and genetic legacies of the Caribbean Taino|first1=Hannes|last1=Schroeder|first2=Martin|last2=Sikora|first3=Shyam|last3=Gopalakrishnan|first4=Lara M.|last4=Cassidy|first5=Pierpaolo Maisano|last5=Delser|first6=Marcela Sandoval|last6=Velasco|first7=Joshua G.|last7=Schraiber|first8=Simon|last8=Rasmussen|first9=Julian R.|last9=Homburger|first10=Mar\u00eda C.|last10=\u00c1vila-Arcos|first11=Morten E.|last11=Allentoft|first12=J. V\u00edctor|last12=Moreno-Mayar|first13=Gabriel|last13=Renaud|first14=Alberto|last14=G\u00f3mez-Carballa|first15=Jason E.|last15=Laffoon|first16=Rachel J. A.|last16=Hopkins|first17=Thomas F. G.|last17=Higham|first18=Robert S.|last18=Carr|first19=William C.|last19=Schaffer|first20=Jane S.|last20=Day|first21=Menno|last21=Hoogland|first22=Antonio|last22=Salas|first23=Carlos D.|last23=Bustamante|first24=Rasmus|last24=Nielsen|first25=Daniel G.|last25=Bradley|first26=Corinne L.|last26=Hofman|first27=Eske|last27=Willerslev|date=March 6, 2018|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=115|issue=10|pages=2341\u20132346|doi=10.1073/pnas.1716839115|pmid=29463742|pmc=5877975}}</ref><ref name=\"Genes found\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2018/02/genes-extinct-caribbean-islanders-found-living-people|title=Genes of 'extinct' Caribbean islanders found in living people|date=February 19, 2018|website=Science &#124; AAAS}}</ref> Today, Ta\u00ednos from places such as the diaspora in the United States and the islands, are gathering together.<ref name=\"Guyana\">{{cite magazine |last=Estevez |first=Jorge Baracutei  |date=August 30, 2017 |title=CARIBBEAN TAINO AND GUYANA INDIGENOUS PEOPLES CACIQUE CROWN A SYMBOL OF BROTHERHOOD - CELEBRATING OUR INDIGENOUS HERITAGE THE ART OF FEATHER WORK CACHUCHABANA FEATHER HEADDRESSES OF THE TAINO PEOPLES|url=http://guyfolkfest.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/GCA-SEPT.-2017-E-MAG.ART-FINAL.pdf |magazine=Guyana Folk & Culture |location= US|publisher=Guyana Cultural Association of New York Inc.on-line Magazine |access-date=December 12, 2019|pages=6\u20137}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2006, there were a couple of dozen activist Taino organizations from Florida to Puerto Rico and California to New York with growing memberships numbering in the thousands. These efforts are known as the \"Ta\u00edno restoration\", a revival movement for Ta\u00edno culture that seeks official recognition of the survival of the Ta\u00edno people.<ref name=\"Forte2006\">{{cite book|author1=L. Guitar|author2=P. Ferbel-Azcarate|author3=J. Esteves|editor=Maximilian Christian Forte|title=Indigenous Resurgence in the Contemporary Caribbean: Amerindian Survival and Revival|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qXZeQZMDpgYC&pg=PA62|year=2006|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-7488-5|page=62|chapter=Ocama-Daca Ta\u00edno}}</ref>\n\nIn Puerto Rico, the history of the Ta\u00edno is being taught in schools and children are encouraged to celebrate the culture and identity of Ta\u00edno through dance, costumes and crafts. Mart\u00ednez Cruzado, a geneticist at the [[University of Puerto Rico at Mayag\u00fcez]] said celebrating and learning about their Ta\u00edno roots is helping Puerto Ricans feel connected to one another.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/02/world/americas/02iht-puerto.4.18336408.html|title=Puerto Rico pageant celebrates a vanished native culture|first=Damien|last=Cave|date=December 2, 2008|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nWhile the scholar Yolanda Mart\u00ednez-San Miguel sees the development of the Neo-Taino movement in Puerto Rico as a useful counter to the domination of the island by the United States and the Spanish legacies of island society, she also notes that the Neo-Taino movement in Puerto Rico \"could be seen as a useless anachronistic reinvention of a 'Boricua coqui' identity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mart\u00ednez-San Miguel|first=Yolanda|date=Spring 2011|title=Taino Warriors?: Strategies for Recovering Indigenous Voices in Colonial and Contemporary Hispanic Caribbean Discourses|url=https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/377/37722223008.pdf|journal=Centro Journal|volume=13|pages=211|via=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n* [[Ciboney]] \n* [[Enriquillo]], rebel cacique\n* [[Garifuna]]\n* [[Hupia]], spirit of the dead\n* [[Indigenous Amerindian genetics]]\n* [[Island Caribs]]\n* [[Jurac\u00e1n]], god of chaos\n* [[List of Ta\u00ednos]]\n* [[Pomier Caves]]\n* [[Tibes Indigenous Ceremonial Center]]\n* [[West Indies]]\n* [[Y\u00facahu]], central Ta\u00edno deity\n* [[Yamaye]]{{div col end}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n|last=Abbot\n|first=Elizabeth\n|title=Sugar: A Bitterweet History\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aaxc1WdKmwEC\n|accessdate=5 March 2013\n|date=1 April 2010\n|publisher=Penguin\n|isbn=978-1-59020-772-7\n|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Chrisp\n|first=P.\n|title=DK Discoveries: Christopher Columbus\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=twyVezztw_UC&pg=PA34\n|accessdate=5 March 2013\n|year= 2006\n|publisher=Penguin\n|isbn=978-0-7566-8616-1\n|ref={{sfnref|Chrisp|2006}} }}\n* {{cite journal |author=Ricardo Alegr\u00eda |date=April 1951 |title=The Ball Game Played by the Aborigines of the Antilles |journal=American Antiquity  |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=348\u2013352 |id= |url= |accessdate= |doi=10.2307/276984 |jstor = 276984}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rouse |first=Irving |author-link=Irving Rouse |title=The Tainos: Rise and Decline of the People Who Greeted Columbus |url=https://archive.org/details/tainosrisedeclin00rous |url-access=registration |year=1992 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=0-300-05696-6 |ref=harv }}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite book\n|last1=Accilien\n|first1=C\u00e9cile\n|last2= Adams\n|first2=Jessica\n|last3= M\u00e9l\u00e9ance\n|first3=Elmide\n|others=Paintings by Ulrick Jean-Pierre\n|title=Revolutionary Freedoms: A History of Survival, Strength and Imagination in Haiti\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O-p7qRKl_G0C&pg=PA1\n|accessdate=21 February 2013\n|year=2006\n|publisher=Educa Vision Inc.\n|isbn=978-1-58432-293-1\n|ref= {{sfnref|Accilien et al.|2003}} }}\n\n<!-- L -->\n* {{cite book\n|last= L\u00e9ger\n|first=Jacques Nicolas\n|title=Haiti, Her History and Her Detractors\n|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924079570762\n|accessdate=21 February 2013\n|year=1907\n|publisher=Neale Publishing Company\n|ref=harv}} [[s:Haiti: Her History and Her Detractors|wikisource]]\n\n* {{cite journal |last=Guitar |first=Lynne |date=2000 |title=Criollos: The Birth of a Dynamic New Indo-Afro-European People and Culture on Hispaniola |url=https://archive.org/stream/KacikeJournal_34/LynneGuitar_djvu.txt |journal=Kacike |publisher=Caribbean Amerindian Centrelink |volume= 1 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201317  |issn= 1562-5028  |name-list-format=vanc |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Guitar |first1=Lynne |last2=Ferbel-Azcarate |first2=Pedro |last3=Estevez |first3=Jorge |title=Indigenous Resurgence in the Contemporary Caribbean: Amerindian Survival and Revival |editor1-last=Forte |editor1-first=Maximilian C. |chapter=Ocama-Daca Ta\u00edno (Hear Me, I Am Ta\u00edno): Ta\u00edno Survival on Hispaniola, Focusing on the Dominican Republic |location=New York |publisher=Peter Lang Publishing |year=2006 |isbn=978-0820474885 |chapter-url=http://www.openanthropology.org/resurgence/abstracts.htm |ref=harv }}\n* DeRLAS. [http://www.udel.edu/LASP/Vol1-2MartinezC.html \"Some important research contributions of Genetics to the study of Population History and Anthropology in Puerto Rico\"]. Newark, Delaware: ''Delaware Review of Latin American Studies''. August 15, 2000.\n* \"The Role of Cohoba in Ta\u00edno Shamanism\", [[Constantino Manuel Torres|Constantino M. Torres]] in ''Eleusis'' No. 1 (1998)\n* \"Shamanic Inebriants in South American Archaeology: Recent Investigations\" [[Constantino Manuel Torres|Constantino M. Torres]] in ''Eleusis'' No. 5 (2001)\n* Tinker, T & Freeland, M. 2008. \"Thief, Slave Trader, Murderer: Christopher Columbus and Caribbean Population Decline\". ''Wicazo Sa Review'', Vol. 23, No. 1, Spring, 2008: 25\u201350. Retrieved from Academic Search Premier Database on 23 Sept. 2008.\n* {{cite journal|last= Guitar |first=Lynne |title=Documenting the Myth of Ta\u00edno Extinction |journal=Kacike}}\n*{{cite book | title= ''The art heritage of Puerto Rico, pre-Columbian to present'' | location=New York | publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art and El Museo del Barrio| year=1973| url= http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/ref/collection/p15324coll10/id/211362}} (Chapter 1: \"The Art of the Taino Indians of Puerto Rico\")\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ta\u00edno}}\n* [http://cronkite.asu.edu/buffett/puertorico/identity.html ''Statehood Issue Stirs Passions About Puerto Rican Identity.'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060624114357/http://www.pem.org/island/ ''Island Thresholds''], Peabody Essex Museum's interactive feature, showcases the work of Caribbean artists and their exploration of culture and identity.\n* [https://www.amstardmc.com/blog/the-cave-of-wonders-in-la-romana/ The Cave of Wonders - Taino Cave Art in La Romana]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071013032642/http://www.taino-tribe.org/terms1.htm ''Ta\u00edno Diccionary''], A dictionary of words of the indigenous peoples of caribbean from the encyclopedia \"Cl\u00e1sicos de Puerto Rico, second edition, publisher, Ediciones Latinoamericanas. S.A., 1972\" compiled by Puerto Rican historian Dr. Cayetano Coll y Toste of the \"Real Academia de la Historia\".\n* [http://www.smithsonianmag.com/people-places/What-Became-of-the-Taino.html 2011 ''Smithsonian'' article on Ta\u00edno culture remnant in the Dominican Republic]\n\n{{pre-Columbian}}\n{{Indigenous peoples by continent}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taino}}\n[[Category:Ta\u00edno| ]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples of the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Cultural history of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Extinct Native American peoples]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples in Cuba]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Haiti]]\n[[Category:History of the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Native American tribes]]\n[[Category:Pre-Columbian cultures]]\n[[Category:Social history of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Spanish West Indies]]\n[[Category:Extinct ethnic groups]]\n", "name_user": "Packer1028", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ta%C3%ADno"}
{"title_page": "Huckster", "text_new": "{{hatnote|A Huckster is also a [[character class]] in the [[role-playing game]] ''[[Deadlands]]''.}}\n{{for|the Web-based shopping tool|Hukkster}}\n\n[[File:The Irish sketch-book (1845) (14594583307).jpg|thumb|Women huckstering from ''The Irish Sketch-Book'', 1845]]\n\nA '''huckster''' is anyone who sells something or serves biased interests, using pushy or showy tactics. Historically, the term was meant any type of vendor, but over time it has assumed [[pejorative]] connotations.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe original meaning of huckster is a person who sells small articles, either door-to-door or from a stall or small store, like a [[peddler]] or hawker. The term probably derives from the Middle English ''hucc'' meaning to haggle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/huckster|title=huckster|publisher=|via=The Free Dictionary}}</ref> The word was in use circa 1200 (as \"huccsteress\"). During the medieval period, the word assumed the feminine word ending \"ster\" as in huck''ster'' reflecting the fact that most hucksters were women.<ref>Davis, J., ''Medieval Market Morality: Life, Law and Ethics in the English Marketplace, 1200-1500,'' Cambridge University Press, 2012, p. 7</ref> The word assumed various spellings at different times: ''hukkerye'', ''hukrie'', ''hockerye'', ''huckerstrye'' or ''hoxterye.'' The word was still in use in England in the 1840s, when it appeared as a black market occupation. It is related to the [[Middle Dutch]] ''hokester, hoekster'' and the [[Middle Low German]] ''h\u00f6ker'', but appears earlier than any of these.<ref>''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', 2nd ed. (1989), \"Huckster, ''n.''\"</ref> In the United States, there developed a connotation of trickery \u2013 the huckster might trick others into buying cheap imitation products as if they were the real thing.\n\n==Other meanings==\n[[File:A French itinerant medicine vendor on stage selling his ware Wellcome L0032279.jpg|thumb|Itinerant medicine salesmen were often known as 'hucksters']]\n\nThe term, 'huckster', was used in different ways across Europe and also took on different meanings at different times.\n\n===In Scotland===\nIn [[Scotland]], the term huckster referred to a person, usually a woman, who bought goods, watered them down, and resold them in tiny quantity to others who were too poor to buy quality products available at market value{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}. These items tended to be in the poorer quality range since economy was paramount. Scots [[burgh]]s often felt the need to control hucksters because they operated without a stall, on the economic fringes. In particular, they were subject of accusations of [[forestalling]], in this case the practice of buying goods wholesale, \"before the stall\" and therefore before tax was paid.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\n\n===In England and Europe===\n\nIn England  and Europe during the medieval period, the term 'huckster' was synonymous with peddler. Hucksters and peddlers belonged to a broad group of [[Reseller|resellers]] who purchased surplus stocks from weekly provincial markets and fairs and then resold them at larger daily markets or engaged in door-to-door selling.\n\nOver time, the distinction between hucksters and peddlers became more pronounced. During the medieval period, the term, huckster, came to refer to market-based food vendors while peddlers referred to itinerant vendors of a wide range of merchandise. Hucksters were often women, who dealt in low-priced goods such as meat, poultry, dairy, bread and baked goods including pies and pastries. They sourced raw materials from their own holdings or purchased goods from other sellers, and carried their products to the market place in baskets or on their heads. These women either lived in the market town, or travelled into the market place from the surrounding area. Hucksters were at the bottom of the market hierarchy, both in terms of wealth and status since they made only small returns. <ref>Davis, J., ''Medieval Market Morality: Life, Law and Ethics in the English Marketplace, 1200-1500,'' Cambridge University Press, 2012, pp 7-8</ref>\n\nLuca Clerici has made a detailed study of Vicenza\u2019s food market during the sixteenth century. He found that there were many different types of reseller operating out of the markets. For example, in the dairy trade, cheese and butter was sold by the members of two craft guilds (i.e., cheesemongers who were shopkeepers) and that of the so-called \u2018resellers\u2019 (hucksters selling a wide range of foodstuffs), and by other sellers who were not enrolled in any guild.  Cheesemongers\u2019 shops were situated at the town hall and were very lucrative. Resellers and peddlers increased the number of sellers, thus increasing competition, to the benefit of consumers. Direct sellers, who brought produce from the surrounding countryside, sold their wares through the central market place and priced their goods at considerably lower rates than cheesemongers.<ref>Clerici, L., \"Le prix du bien commun. Taxation des prix et approvisionnement urbain (Vicence, XVIe-XVIIe si\u00e8cle)\" [The price of the common good. Official prices and urban provisioning in sixteenth and seventeenth century Vicenza] in I prezzi delle cose nell\u2019et\u00e0 preindustriale /''The Prices of Things in Pre-Industrial Times,'' [forthcoming], Firenze University Press, 2017.</ref>\n\n===In 20th-century Philadelphia===\n\n[[File:Swindlers, Hucksters and Snake Oil Salesman - Hype and Hope Marketing Anti-Aging Products to Seniors.pdf|thumb|Hearing Before the Special Committee on Aging. [[United States Senate]], [[107th United States Congress]]. First Session. Washington, D.C. Serial No. 107-14.]]\nIn the Philadelphia of the past century the huckster was the man who came around with his cart of vegetables.  The cart may have been mechanical or even horse drawn.  He was the man from whom you bought all your products.  The huckster made his presence known by crying out loud what he had to offer.  In old time Philadelphia dialect, to say \"like a huckster\" meant to be too loud in one's speech.{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n==In literature and popular culture ==\n\n===In \"The Goblin and the Grocer\"===\nThe story \"[[The Goblin and the Grocer]]\" by [[Hans Christian Andersen]] relates that human nature is attracted to a state of happiness as represented by [[poetry]] and to sensual pleasure as represented by [[jam]] and [[butter]] at [[Christmas]]. Although the story has been mistakenly called \"The Goblin and the Huckster,\" it has nothing to do with that term (pejoratively). The Grocer, through his haggling and bargaining, is seen as industrious because he possesses the jam and butter (sensual pleasure) and the student is seen as poor but happy because he appreciates the beauty of poetry above all else. Meanwhile, the Grocer's talkative wife and the cask in which are stored old newspapers both have plenty of authoritative knowledge to share but are paid little attention compared to the primal desires of humankind, which constantly compete for (the [[goblin]]'s) attention.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lang|first= Andrew|authorlink=Andrew Lang|title=The Pink Fairy Book |year=1889|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/lfb/pi/pifb05.htm|website=www.sacred-texts.com}}</ref>\n\n===''Huckster'' used in citation===\n<blockquote>Hucksters want their claims to look like science for a reason. Science works hard to ascertain facts. But just looking like science is not the same as having all the evidence. Pseudoscience is like a magician's trick. It seems believable, but it is all crafty illusion. ''Douglas Allchin''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allchin |first1=Douglas |title=Podcast #704 - January 5th, 2019 |url=https://www.theskepticsguide.org/podcast/sgu/704 |website=The Skeptics Guide to the Universe |accessdate=8 February 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n===In science fiction fandom===\nIn [[science fiction fandom]], the term \"huckster\" is used non-[[pejorative]]ly to designate dealers in [[science fiction]]\u2013related books, magazines and paraphernalia,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fanac.org/Fannish_Reference_Works/FandBook/FandBook.html |first=Donald |last=Franson |title=A Key to the Terminology of Science Fiction Fandom |work= National Fantasy Fan Federation |year=1962}}</ref> particularly those who deal at [[science fiction conventions]].\n\n==Popular references==\n{{wiktionary}}\n* ''[[The Hucksters]]'' (1947), an American film starring [[Clark Gable]] as a slick [[Madison Avenue#Advertising industry|Madison Avenue]] advertiser.\n\n* ''[[#Hucksters4Life]]'' Popular hashtag within the Twitter #WritingCommunity. Some of the first #Hucksters in the #Hucksters4Life group as determined by a third party Twitter user include Darryl Ballegeer, Patrick F. Johnson, Torsten Krol, Rebecca Velland, Mike Wells, David Gane, Dzintra Sulliven and Mandy Lawson.\n\n==See also ==\n\n* [[Arabber]]\n* [[Costermonger]]\n* [[Direct sales]]\n* [[Hawker (trade)]]\n* [[History of marketing]]\n* [[Market (place)]]\n* [[Market town]]\n* [[Merchant]]\n* [[Peddler]] \n* [[Personal selling]]\n* [[Quackery]]\n* [[Retail]]\n* [[Street vendor]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Sales occupations]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fandom]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|A Huckster is also a [[character class]] in the [[role-playing game]] ''[[Deadlands]]''.}}\n{{for|the Web-based shopping tool|Hukkster}}\n\n[[File:The Irish sketch-book (1845) (14594583307).jpg|thumb|Women huckstering from ''The Irish Sketch-Book'', 1845]]\n\nThe term '''huckster''' describes a person who sells something or serves biased interests, using pushy or showy tactics. Historically, the term \"huckster\" was applied to any type of vendor or reseller, but over time it has assumed distinctive [[pejorative]] connotations.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe original meaning of huckster is a person who sells small articles, either door-to-door or from a stall or small store, like a [[peddler]] or hawker. The term probably derives from the Middle English ''hucc'' meaning to haggle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/huckster|title=huckster|publisher=|via=The Free Dictionary}}</ref> The word was in use circa 1200 (as \"huccsteress\"). During the medieval period, the word assumed the feminine word ending \"ster\" as in huck''ster'' reflecting the fact that most hucksters were women.<ref>Davis, J., ''Medieval Market Morality: Life, Law and Ethics in the English Marketplace, 1200-1500,'' Cambridge University Press, 2012, p. 7</ref> The word assumed various spellings at different times: ''hukkerye'', ''hukrie'', ''hockerye'', ''huckerstrye'' or ''hoxterye.'' The word was still in use in England in the 1840s, when it appeared as a black market occupation. It is related to the [[Middle Dutch]] ''hokester, hoekster'' and the [[Middle Low German]] ''h\u00f6ker'', but appears earlier than any of these.<ref>''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', 2nd ed. (1989), \"Huckster, ''n.''\"</ref> In the United States, there developed a connotation of trickery \u2013 the huckster might trick others into buying cheap imitation products as if they were the real thing.\n\n==Other meanings==\n[[File:A French itinerant medicine vendor on stage selling his ware Wellcome L0032279.jpg|thumb|Itinerant medicine salesmen were often known as 'hucksters']]\n\nThe term, 'huckster', was used in different ways across Europe and also took on different meanings at different times.\n\n===In Scotland===\nIn [[Scotland]], the term huckster referred to a person, usually a woman, who bought goods, watered them down, and resold them in tiny quantity to others who were too poor to buy quality products available at market value{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}. These items tended to be in the poorer quality range since economy was paramount. Scots [[burgh]]s often felt the need to control hucksters because they operated without a stall, on the economic fringes. In particular, they were subject of accusations of [[forestalling]], in this case the practice of buying goods wholesale, \"before the stall\" and therefore before tax was paid.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\n\n===In England and Europe===\n\nIn England  and Europe during the medieval period, the term 'huckster' was synonymous with peddler. Hucksters and peddlers belonged to a broad group of [[Reseller|resellers]] who purchased surplus stocks from weekly provincial markets and fairs and then resold them at larger daily markets or engaged in door-to-door selling.\n\nOver time, the distinction between hucksters and peddlers became more pronounced. During the medieval period, the term, huckster, came to refer to market-based food vendors while peddlers referred to itinerant vendors of a wide range of merchandise. Hucksters were often women, who dealt in low-priced goods such as meat, poultry, dairy, bread and baked goods including pies and pastries. They sourced raw materials from their own holdings or purchased goods from other sellers, and carried their products to the market place in baskets or on their heads. These women either lived in the market town, or travelled into the market place from the surrounding area. Hucksters were at the bottom of the market hierarchy, both in terms of wealth and status since they made only small returns. <ref>Davis, J., ''Medieval Market Morality: Life, Law and Ethics in the English Marketplace, 1200-1500,'' Cambridge University Press, 2012, pp 7-8</ref>\n\nLuca Clerici has made a detailed study of Vicenza\u2019s food market during the sixteenth century. He found that there were many different types of reseller operating out of the markets. For example, in the dairy trade, cheese and butter was sold by the members of two craft guilds (i.e., cheesemongers who were shopkeepers) and that of the so-called \u2018resellers\u2019 (hucksters selling a wide range of foodstuffs), and by other sellers who were not enrolled in any guild.  Cheesemongers\u2019 shops were situated at the town hall and were very lucrative. Resellers and peddlers increased the number of sellers, thus increasing competition, to the benefit of consumers. Direct sellers, who brought produce from the surrounding countryside, sold their wares through the central market place and priced their goods at considerably lower rates than cheesemongers.<ref>Clerici, L., \"Le prix du bien commun. Taxation des prix et approvisionnement urbain (Vicence, XVIe-XVIIe si\u00e8cle)\" [The price of the common good. Official prices and urban provisioning in sixteenth and seventeenth century Vicenza] in I prezzi delle cose nell\u2019et\u00e0 preindustriale /''The Prices of Things in Pre-Industrial Times,'' [forthcoming], Firenze University Press, 2017.</ref>\n\n===In 20th-century Philadelphia===\n\n[[File:Swindlers, Hucksters and Snake Oil Salesman - Hype and Hope Marketing Anti-Aging Products to Seniors.pdf|thumb|Hearing Before the Special Committee on Aging. [[United States Senate]], [[107th United States Congress]]. First Session. Washington, D.C. Serial No. 107-14.]]\nIn the Philadelphia of the past century the huckster was the man who came around with his cart of vegetables.  The cart may have been mechanical or even horse drawn.  He was the man from whom you bought all your products.  The huckster made his presence known by crying out loud what he had to offer.  In old time Philadelphia dialect, to say \"like a huckster\" meant to be too loud in one's speech.{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n==In literature and popular culture ==\n\n===In \"The Goblin and the Grocer\"===\nThe story \"[[The Goblin and the Grocer]]\" by [[Hans Christian Andersen]] relates that human nature is attracted to a state of happiness as represented by [[poetry]] and to sensual pleasure as represented by [[jam]] and [[butter]] at [[Christmas]]. Although the story has been mistakenly called \"The Goblin and the Huckster,\" it has nothing to do with that term (pejoratively). The Grocer, through his haggling and bargaining, is seen as industrious because he possesses the jam and butter (sensual pleasure) and the student is seen as poor but happy because he appreciates the beauty of poetry above all else. Meanwhile, the Grocer's talkative wife and the cask in which are stored old newspapers both have plenty of authoritative knowledge to share but are paid little attention compared to the primal desires of humankind, which constantly compete for (the [[goblin]]'s) attention.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lang|first= Andrew|authorlink=Andrew Lang|title=The Pink Fairy Book |year=1889|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/lfb/pi/pifb05.htm|website=www.sacred-texts.com}}</ref>\n\n===''Huckster'' used in citation===\n<blockquote>Hucksters want their claims to look like science for a reason. Science works hard to ascertain facts. But just looking like science is not the same as having all the evidence. Pseudoscience is like a magician's trick. It seems believable, but it is all crafty illusion. ''Douglas Allchin''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allchin |first1=Douglas |title=Podcast #704 - January 5th, 2019 |url=https://www.theskepticsguide.org/podcast/sgu/704 |website=The Skeptics Guide to the Universe |accessdate=8 February 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n===In science fiction fandom===\nIn [[science fiction fandom]], the term \"huckster\" is used non-[[pejorative]]ly to designate dealers in [[science fiction]]\u2013related books, magazines and paraphernalia,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fanac.org/Fannish_Reference_Works/FandBook/FandBook.html |first=Donald |last=Franson |title=A Key to the Terminology of Science Fiction Fandom |work= National Fantasy Fan Federation |year=1962}}</ref> particularly those who deal at [[science fiction conventions]].\n\n==Popular references==\n{{wiktionary}}\n* ''[[The Hucksters]]'' (1947), an American film starring [[Clark Gable]] as a slick [[Madison Avenue#Advertising industry|Madison Avenue]] advertiser.\n\n* ''[[#Hucksters4Life]]'' Popular hashtag within the Twitter #WritingCommunity. Some of the first #Hucksters in the #Hucksters4Life group as determined by a third party Twitter user include Darryl Ballegeer, Patrick F. Johnson, Torsten Krol, Rebecca Velland, Mike Wells, David Gane, Dzintra Sulliven and Mandy Lawson.\n\n==See also ==\n\n* [[Arabber]]\n* [[Costermonger]]\n* [[Direct sales]]\n* [[Hawker (trade)]]\n* [[History of marketing]]\n* [[Market (place)]]\n* [[Market town]]\n* [[Merchant]]\n* [[Peddler]] \n* [[Personal selling]]\n* [[Quackery]]\n* [[Retail]]\n* [[Street vendor]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Sales occupations]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fandom]]\n", "name_user": "Pgan002", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huckster"}
{"title_page": "The Wednesday Wars", "text_new": "{{Refimprove article|date=June 2015}}\n{{for|the professional wrestling rivalry|Wednesday Night Wars}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name = The Wednesday Wars\n| image = The wednesday wars.jpg\n| caption = Hardcover dust jacket (2007)\n| author = [[Gary D. Schmidt]]\n| cover_artist = Jonathan Gray\n| language = English\n| genre = [[Historical Fiction]],<br/> [[Children's Literature]]\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Harcourt\n| release_date = May 21, 2007\n| media_type = Print<br/> (Hardback & Paperback)\n| isbn = 0-618-72483-4\n| congress = PZ7.S3527 We 2007\n| oclc = 71044136\n| followed_by = [[Okay for Now]]\n}}\n{{Portal|Children's literature}} '''''The Wednesday Wars''''' is a 2007 [[young adult literature|young adult]] historical fiction novel written by [[Gary D. Schmidt]], the author of ''[[Lizzie Bright and the Buckminster Boy]].'' The novel is set in suburban [[Long Island]] during the 1967\u201368 school year. The [[Vietnam War]] is an important backdrop for the novel. It was given a [[Newbery Honor]] medal in 2008, and was also nominated for the [[Rebecca Caudill Young Reader's Book Award]] in 2010. But toads,beetles,bats. If you can't figure that out for yourself, then a southwest blow on ye and blister you all o'er.\n\n==Synopsis==\nHolling Hoodhood is a seventh grader during the 1967-1968 school year. In his school, the student body is largely divided between Catholics and Jews, and every Wednesday both groups go to their separate churches for religious classes. Holling, a Presbyterian, has no religious class to attend, therefore he is forced to remain at class with his teacher, Mrs. Baker.\n\nHolling is convinced that Mrs. Baker resents him for this. This suspicion is compounded when she begins having him read Shakespeare. As he begins to enjoy the plays, though, he also begins to understand Mrs. Baker, whose husband, he learns, is stationed in Vietnam.\n\nThe story's main focus is on Holling's struggle to get out from his overbearing father's shadow. Mr. Hoodhood is an ambitious, social climbing, and at times, the cutthroat architect who is determined that Holling take over the business when he retires. In fact, Mr. Hoodhood believes that nothing is more important than their family business and ensuring that it flourishes.  Because of this, all of the Hoodhoods must be on their best behavior at all times.  Whenever Holling brings up a particular person, his father breaks down who the person is, as well as their status; if they're someone who owns a business, Mr. Hoodhood demands Holling to be respectful at all times.  This causes a strained relationship between Holling and his father.  Holling ultimately finds an ally in his older sister, Heather, and eventually comes to understand that Mrs. Baker is also trying to help him learn to be his own person.\n\nOther subplots in the story include: Holling entering track and field; running the big race for track; going on his first date with classmate Meryl Lee, whose father is of the other architecture firm in town, Kowalski and Associates; his sister Heather running away to California with her boyfriend; and the ever-present shadow of the Vietnam War \u2014 as well as other historical events, such as the shootings of [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]. In addition, television news anchorman [[Walter Cronkite]] is mentioned throughout the novel, as an important presence while delivering the news. Cronkite is presented as the voice of the people, with the ability to sway Americans to a particular side.\n\nThe plot follows a steady, progression-focused format, lacking any clear climax. Instead, it simply follows Holling as he struggles through school, forms friends out of supposed enemies, and tries to grow up.\n\n==Publication history==\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/wednesdaywars00schm |title=The Wednesday Wars |author=Schmidt, Gary D. |author-link=Gary D. Schmidt |author-mask=\u2014 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=978-0-618-72483-3 |date=21 May 2007 |edition=1st, hc |accessdate=4 May 2018 |url-access=registration }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Wednesday Wars |author=Schmidt, Gary D. |author-link=Gary D. Schmidt |author-mask=\u2014 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=978-0-547-23760-2 |date=18 May 2009 |edition=1st, pb |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/wednesdaywars00gary }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Wednesday Wars |author=Schmidt, Gary D. |author-link=Gary D. Schmidt |author-mask=\u2014 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=978-0-547-34624-3 |date=2007 |edition=eBook }}\n\n==Critical reception==\n''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called the novel \"another virtuoso turn by the author of ''Lizzie Bright and the Buckminster Boy'' (2005)\" in its starred review.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/gary-d-schmidt/the-wednesday-wars/ |title=The Wednesday Wars |author= |date=15 May 2007 |work=Kirkus Reviews |accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> Susan Faust, reviewing for the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', wrote it was a \"graceful novel [...] full of goodwill, yearning and heart\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Review-Growing-up-in-The-Wednesday-Wars-3296554.php |title=Review: Growing up in 'The Wednesday Wars' |author=Faust, Susan |date=27 January 2008 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n* 2008 [[Newbery Honor]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/newberymedal/newberyhonors/2008newberymedalhonors.cfm|title=2008 Newbery Medal and Honour Books|publisher=Association for Library Services to Children|accessdate=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[Rebecca Caudill Young Reader's Book Award|Rebecca Caudill]] (nominated)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rebeccacaudill.org/images/CaudillCumulativeList.pdf |title=Rebecca Caudill Young Readers' Book Award Cumulative List 1988-2019 |author= |date=23 March 2018 |publisher=Rebecca Caudill |accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite interview |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/interviews/article/11072-children-s-bookshelf-talks-with-gary-schmidt.html |title=Children's Bookshelf Talks with Gary Schmidt |subject=Gary Schmidt |interviewer=Sue Corbett |date=3 May 2007 |publisher=Publishers Weekly |accessdate=15 May 2018}}\n\n===Reviews===\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/16/books/review/Stone-t.html |title=Starting Out in the '60s |author=Stone, Tanya Lee |author-link=Tanya Lee Stone |date=16 December 2007 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=14 May 2018}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-618-72483-3 |title=The Wednesday Wars |author= |date=May 2007 |work=Publishers Weekly |accessdate=15 May 2018}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://blogs.slj.com/afuse8production/2012/05/30/top-100-childrens-novels-37-the-wednesday-wars-by-gary-d-schmidt/ |title=Top 100 Children\u2019s Novels #37: The Wednesday Wars by Gary D. Schmidt |author=Bird, Elizabeth |date=30 May 2012 |website=A Fuse8 Production |publisher=School Library Journal |accessdate=15 May 2018}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://hopeisthewordblog.com/2014/10/01/the-wednesday-wars-by-gary-d-schmidt/ |title=The Wednesday Wars by Gary D. Schmidt |author=Amy |date=1 October 2014 |website=Hope is the Word |accessdate=15 May 2018}}\n*[[Benjy Eversberg|Eversberg, Benjy]] (12 November 2018).\n\n{{Gary D. Schmidt}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wednesday Wars, The}}\n[[Category:2007 American novels]]\n[[Category:2007 children's books]]\n[[Category:American young adult novels]]\n[[Category:Children's historical novels]]\n[[Category:Long Island in fiction]]\n[[Category:Newbery Honor-winning works]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1967]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1968]]\n[[Category:Novels set in schools]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove article|date=June 2015}}\n{{for|the professional wrestling rivalry|Wednesday Night Wars}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name = The Wednesday Wars\n| image = The wednesday wars.jpg\n| caption = Hardcover dust jacket (2007)\n| author = [[Gary D. Schmidt]]\n| cover_artist = Jonathan Gray\n| language = English\n| genre = [[Historical Fiction]],<br/> [[Children's Literature]]\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Harcourt\n| release_date = May 21, 2007\n| media_type = Print<br/> (Hardback & Paperback)\n| isbn = 0-618-72483-4\n| congress = PZ7.S3527 We 2007\n| oclc = 71044136\n| followed_by = [[Okay for Now]]\n}}\n{{Portal|Children's literature}} '''''The Wednesday Wars''''' is a 2007 [[young adult literature|young adult]] historical fiction novel written by [[Gary D. Schmidt]], the author of ''[[Lizzie Bright and the Buckminster Boy]].'' The novel is set in suburban [[Long Island]] during the 1967\u201368 school year. The [[Vietnam War]] is an important backdrop for the novel. It was given a [[Newbery Honor]] medal in 2008, and was also nominated for the [[Rebecca Caudill Young Reader's Book Award]] in 2010.\n\n==Synopsis==\nHolling Hoodhood is a seventh grader during the 1967-1968 school year. In his school, the student body is largely divided between Catholics and Jews, and every Wednesday both groups go to their separate churches for religious classes. Holling, a Presbyterian, has no religious class to attend, therefore he is forced to remain at class with his teacher, Mrs. Baker.\n\nHolling is convinced that Mrs. Baker resents him for this. This suspicion is compounded when she begins having him read Shakespeare. As he begins to enjoy the plays, though, he also begins to understand Mrs. Baker, whose husband, he learns, is stationed in Vietnam.\n\nThe story's main focus is on Holling's struggle to get out from his overbearing father's shadow. Mr. Hoodhood is an ambitious, social climbing, and at times, the cutthroat architect who is determined that Holling take over the business when he retires. In fact, Mr. Hoodhood believes that nothing is more important than their family business and ensuring that it flourishes.  Because of this, all of the Hoodhoods must be on their best behavior at all times.  Whenever Holling brings up a particular person, his father breaks down who the person is, as well as their status; if they're someone who owns a business, Mr. Hoodhood demands Holling to be respectful at all times.  This causes a strained relationship between Holling and his father.  Holling ultimately finds an ally in his older sister, Heather, and eventually comes to understand that Mrs. Baker is also trying to help him learn to be his own person.\n\nOther subplots in the story include: Holling entering track and field; running the big race for track; going on his first date with classmate Meryl Lee, whose father is of the other architecture firm in town, Kowalski and Associates; his sister Heather running away to California with her boyfriend; and the ever-present shadow of the Vietnam War \u2014 as well as other historical events, such as the shootings of [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]. In addition, television news anchorman [[Walter Cronkite]] is mentioned throughout the novel, as an important presence while delivering the news. Cronkite is presented as the voice of the people, with the ability to sway Americans to a particular side.\n\nThe plot follows a steady, progression-focused format, lacking any clear climax. Instead, it simply follows Holling as he struggles through school, forms friends out of supposed enemies, and tries to grow up.\n\n==Publication history==\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/wednesdaywars00schm |title=The Wednesday Wars |author=Schmidt, Gary D. |author-link=Gary D. Schmidt |author-mask=\u2014 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=978-0-618-72483-3 |date=21 May 2007 |edition=1st, hc |accessdate=4 May 2018 |url-access=registration }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Wednesday Wars |author=Schmidt, Gary D. |author-link=Gary D. Schmidt |author-mask=\u2014 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=978-0-547-23760-2 |date=18 May 2009 |edition=1st, pb |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/wednesdaywars00gary }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Wednesday Wars |author=Schmidt, Gary D. |author-link=Gary D. Schmidt |author-mask=\u2014 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=978-0-547-34624-3 |date=2007 |edition=eBook }}\n\n==Critical reception==\n''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called the novel \"another virtuoso turn by the author of ''Lizzie Bright and the Buckminster Boy'' (2005)\" in its starred review.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/gary-d-schmidt/the-wednesday-wars/ |title=The Wednesday Wars |author= |date=15 May 2007 |work=Kirkus Reviews |accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> Susan Faust, reviewing for the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', wrote it was a \"graceful novel [...] full of goodwill, yearning and heart\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Review-Growing-up-in-The-Wednesday-Wars-3296554.php |title=Review: Growing up in 'The Wednesday Wars' |author=Faust, Susan |date=27 January 2008 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n* 2008 [[Newbery Honor]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/newberymedal/newberyhonors/2008newberymedalhonors.cfm|title=2008 Newbery Medal and Honour Books|publisher=Association for Library Services to Children|accessdate=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[Rebecca Caudill Young Reader's Book Award|Rebecca Caudill]] (nominated)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rebeccacaudill.org/images/CaudillCumulativeList.pdf |title=Rebecca Caudill Young Readers' Book Award Cumulative List 1988-2019 |author= |date=23 March 2018 |publisher=Rebecca Caudill |accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite interview |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/interviews/article/11072-children-s-bookshelf-talks-with-gary-schmidt.html |title=Children's Bookshelf Talks with Gary Schmidt |subject=Gary Schmidt |interviewer=Sue Corbett |date=3 May 2007 |publisher=Publishers Weekly |accessdate=15 May 2018}}\n\n===Reviews===\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/16/books/review/Stone-t.html |title=Starting Out in the '60s |author=Stone, Tanya Lee |author-link=Tanya Lee Stone |date=16 December 2007 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=14 May 2018}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-618-72483-3 |title=The Wednesday Wars |author= |date=May 2007 |work=Publishers Weekly |accessdate=15 May 2018}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://blogs.slj.com/afuse8production/2012/05/30/top-100-childrens-novels-37-the-wednesday-wars-by-gary-d-schmidt/ |title=Top 100 Children\u2019s Novels #37: The Wednesday Wars by Gary D. Schmidt |author=Bird, Elizabeth |date=30 May 2012 |website=A Fuse8 Production |publisher=School Library Journal |accessdate=15 May 2018}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://hopeisthewordblog.com/2014/10/01/the-wednesday-wars-by-gary-d-schmidt/ |title=The Wednesday Wars by Gary D. Schmidt |author=Amy |date=1 October 2014 |website=Hope is the Word |accessdate=15 May 2018}}\n*[[Benjy Eversberg|Eversberg, Benjy]] (12 November 2018).\n\n{{Gary D. Schmidt}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wednesday Wars, The}}\n[[Category:2007 American novels]]\n[[Category:2007 children's books]]\n[[Category:American young adult novels]]\n[[Category:Children's historical novels]]\n[[Category:Long Island in fiction]]\n[[Category:Newbery Honor-winning works]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1967]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1968]]\n[[Category:Novels set in schools]]\n", "name_user": "2601:602:880:9410:90bd:e03a:ac22:efd9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added a quote that basically sums up the whole book.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wednesday_Wars"}
{"title_page": "Elena Pautova", "text_new": "{{short description|Russian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Elena Pautova\n| image = Elena Pautova - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg\n| image_size = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| caption = Pautova at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]].\n| nationality = [[Russia]]n\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1986|01|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Adler Microdistrict|Adler]], Russia\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| website = \n| sport = [[track and field]]\n| disability = \n| disability_class = T12\n| event = [[800m]]<br/>[[1500m]]\n| collegeteam = \n| club = \n| coach = Pyotr Buylov\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|2|0|3\n|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]|3|1|1\n|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]|3|0|0\n}}\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[para-athletics]] }}\n{{MedalCountry|{{RUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2004 Summer Paralympics|2004 Athens]] | [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T12|1500 metres \u2013 T12]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T12|1500 metres \u2013 T12]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2004 Summer Paralympics|2004 Athens]] | [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 800 metres T12|800 metres \u2013 T12]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T13|1500 metres \u2013 T13]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 800 metres T12/13|800 metres - T12/13]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|{{nowrap|[[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships|2006 Assen]]}}|[[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m T13]]}}\n{{MedalGold|{{nowrap|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]]}}|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m T13]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|{{nowrap|[[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships|2006 Assen]]}}|[[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 800 metres|800m T13]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2019 World Para Athletics Championships|2019 Dubai]]|[[2019 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|IPC European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 Stadskanaal]]|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m - T12]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Elena Pautova''' (born 22 January 1986) is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Russia]] competing mainly in category [[T12 (classification)|T12]] middle distance events. She is a two times Paralympic gold medalist and three times World Championship gold medalist in the 1500m race. Pautova also broke the world record in the T13 5000m event in 2003.\n\n==Career history==\nPautova, who is visually impaired, first took to athletics while she attended a specialised boarding school in [[Armavir, Russia]].<ref name=\"IPC profile\">{{cite web|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=-1&personid=687902&refreshauto=1 |title=Pautova, Elena |accessdate=9 August 2013 |publisher=ipc.infostradasports.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061640/http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=-1&personid=687902&refreshauto=1 |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref> She began competing competitively whilst still a teenager, and she competed in both middle and long distance events. At the age of 17 she entered an international meet in Quebec, Canada and ran in a T13 5000m contest. There she posted an officially recognized time of 17:50.45, a new world record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/sdms/web/at/record.pdf.at.php?xml=0&rct=RCTWR&spec=out&gen=&evt=AT050|title=IPC Athletics World Records|accessdate=9 August 2013|page=2|publisher=paralympic.org}}</ref> Due to the rarity of official T13 5000m races at major competitions, Pautova's record, as of 2013, still stands. Pautova then switched to middle-distance events, and at the age of 18 she was selected for her first [[Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]], chosen to represent Russia at the [[2004 Summer Paralympics]] in [[Athens]]. It was an extremely successful competition for Pautova, winning the gold medal in the T12 1500m and a bronze medal in the T12 800m.\n\nIn 2006, she travelled to Assen where she took part in the [[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships|Athletics World Championships]]. There she entered her favoured two events the 800, and 1,500m, and finished with an identical result to Athens; a gold in the 1,500m and bronze in the 800m. She returned to the Paralympics in [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008]] in [[Beijing]], [[China]], winning two more bronze medals in the T13 1500m and the joint classified T12/13 800m.\n\nIn 2011, she retained her World title in the 1,500m, successfully defending it at the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Christchurch, New Zealand. Then in the run-up to the 2012 London Paralympics, she took the gold, again in the 1,500m, at the [[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 European Championships]] in [[Stadskanaal]]. In London she posted a season's best of 4:37.65 to beat her nearest rival, Spain's [[Elena Congost]], by almost seven seconds to take her second Paralympic gold medal. After her triumph in London, Pautova was awarded the [[Order of Honour (Russian Federation)|Order of Honour]], and received her medal form President [[Vladimir Putin]] at a ceremony held in the Kremlin.<ref name=\"IPC profile\"/>\n\nIn 2013 Pautova secured a third World gold title in the 1,500m with a win at the  [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Lyon, making her the undefeated World champion at that distance for eight years.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=elena-pautova|old_id=687902}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pautova, Elena}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Russia]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Russia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Russia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Honour (Russia)]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Elena Pautova\n| image = Elena Pautova - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg\n| image_size = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| caption = Pautova at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]].\n| nationality = [[Russia]]n\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1986|01|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Adler Microdistrict|Adler]], Russia\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| website = \n| sport = [[track and field]]\n| disability = \n| disability_class = T12\n| event = [[800m]]<br/>[[1500m]]\n| collegeteam = \n| club = \n| coach = Pyotr Buylov\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|2|0|3\n|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]|3|1|1\n|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]|3|0|0\n}}\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[para-athletics]] }}\n{{MedalCountry|{{RUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2004 Summer Paralympics|2004 Athens]] | [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T12|1500 metres \u2013 T12]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T12|1500 metres \u2013 T12]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2004 Summer Paralympics|2004 Athens]] | [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 800 metres T12|800 metres \u2013 T12]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T13|1500 metres \u2013 T13]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 800 metres T12/13|800 metres - T12/13]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|{{nowrap|[[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships|2006 Assen]]}}|[[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m T13]]}}\n{{MedalGold|{{nowrap|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]]}}|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m T13]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|{{nowrap|[[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships|2006 Assen]]}}|[[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 800 metres|800m T13]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2019 World Para Athletics Championships|2019 Dubai]]|[[2019 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|IPC European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 Stadskanaal]]|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m - T12]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m - T13]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Elena Pautova''' (born 22 January 1986) is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Russia]] competing mainly in category [[T12 (classification)|T12]] middle distance events. She is a two times Paralympic gold medalist and three times World Championship gold medalist in the 1500m race. Pautova also broke the world record in the T13 5000m event in 2003.\n\n==Career history==\nPautova, who is visually impaired, first took to athletics while she attended a specialised boarding school in [[Armavir, Russia]].<ref name=\"IPC profile\">{{cite web|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=-1&personid=687902&refreshauto=1 |title=Pautova, Elena |accessdate=9 August 2013 |publisher=ipc.infostradasports.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061640/http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=-1&personid=687902&refreshauto=1 |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref> She began competing competitively whilst still a teenager, and she competed in both middle and long distance events. At the age of 17 she entered an international meet in Quebec, Canada and ran in a T13 5000m contest. There she posted an officially recognized time of 17:50.45, a new world record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/sdms/web/at/record.pdf.at.php?xml=0&rct=RCTWR&spec=out&gen=&evt=AT050|title=IPC Athletics World Records|accessdate=9 August 2013|page=2|publisher=paralympic.org}}</ref> Due to the rarity of official T13 5000m races at major competitions, Pautova's record, as of 2013, still stands. Pautova then switched to middle-distance events, and at the age of 18 she was selected for her first [[Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]], chosen to represent Russia at the [[2004 Summer Paralympics]] in [[Athens]]. It was an extremely successful competition for Pautova, winning the gold medal in the T12 1500m and a bronze medal in the T12 800m.\n\nIn 2006, she travelled to Assen where she took part in the [[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships|Athletics World Championships]]. There she entered her favoured two events the 800, and 1,500m, and finished with an identical result to Athens; a gold in the 1,500m and bronze in the 800m. She returned to the Paralympics in [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008]] in [[Beijing]], [[China]], winning two more bronze medals in the T13 1500m and the joint classified T12/13 800m.\n\nIn 2011, she retained her World title in the 1,500m, successfully defending it at the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Christchurch, New Zealand. Then in the run-up to the 2012 London Paralympics, she took the gold, again in the 1,500m, at the [[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 European Championships]] in [[Stadskanaal]]. In London she posted a season's best of 4:37.65 to beat her nearest rival, Spain's [[Elena Congost]], by almost seven seconds to take her second Paralympic gold medal. After her triumph in London, Pautova was awarded the [[Order of Honour (Russian Federation)|Order of Honour]], and received her medal form President [[Vladimir Putin]] at a ceremony held in the Kremlin.<ref name=\"IPC profile\"/>\n\nIn 2013 Pautova secured a third World gold title in the 1,500m with a win at the  [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Lyon, making her the undefeated World champion at that distance for eight years.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|687902}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pautova, Elena}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Russia]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Russia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Russia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Honour (Russia)]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elena_Pautova"}
